var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Samples","page":"Samples","text":"A Sample is the data unit Zenoh delivers to a subscriber, a query reply, or a get. It bundles everything the network carried alongside the data: the key expression it was published on, the payload bytes, the kind (a put or a delete), the encoding of the payload, an optional timestamp, an optional attachment, and four quality-of-service values (express, congestion_control, priority, reliability). Zenoh's Rust API defines it as \"the data unit received by Subscriber or Querier or Session::get; it contains the payload and all metadata associated with the data\" (zenoh::sample::Sample).\n\nSamples are received-only. You read their fields through the accessor functions below; you never construct one to publish. To send data, pass it through the call options of put, delete!, and reply.\n\nThis page also covers ZTimestamp, the sibling timestamp value you read off an inbound sample with timestamp or mint from a session to stamp an outbound put.","title":"Samples"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#The-three-sample-representations","page":"Samples","text":"Zenoh.jl gives you a sample in one of three forms, each with its own lifetime. All three subtype AbstractSample, so every accessor below works uniformly on any of them.\n\nForm You get it from Lifetime\nOwned Sample take!, the :keep_all channel A stable value you hold for as long as you like; reclaimed by GC.\nLoaned Sample sample(::Reply) (so the replies of a get) Borrows from an owner value — valid only while that owner lives.\nSampleHolder You allocate one; recv! / tryrecv! / for s in sub refill it Reusable single slot — its occupant is valid only until the next refill.\n\nThe owned form is the safe default: hold it, stash it, pass it around. The loaned form and the SampleHolder occupant are borrows — valid only while their backing lives.\n\nwarning: Borrowed samples are valid only until their backing goes away\nAnything derived from a loaned Sample or a SampleHolder occupant — the payload ZBytes, the keyexpr string, the attachment — is valid only until the next recv!/tryrecv! refill (for a holder) or until the owner is collected (for a loaned sample). To keep data past that point, copy it out: String(payload(s)), collect(payload(s)), the String from keyexpr(s).","title":"The three sample representations"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Reading-a-sample","page":"Samples","text":"Every accessor works uniformly on any sample form, returning the same value regardless of which representation you hold.\n\nAccessor Returns Notes\nkeyexpr(s) String A fresh copy of the key expression.\nkeyexpr_view(f, s) f's result Zero-copy byte view for hot paths; no String allocated.\npayload(s) ZBytes Loaned; decode with String, Vector{UInt8}, or a reader.\nencoding(s) Encoding The payload's format descriptor.\nkind(s) SampleKind SampleKinds.PUT or SampleKinds.DELETE.\ntimestamp(s) ZTimestamp or nothing nothing when no timestamp is associated.\nattachment(s) ZBytes or nothing nothing when no attachment is present.\npriority(s) Priority QoS.\ncongestion_control(s) CongestionControl QoS.\nexpress(s) Bool Whether batching was bypassed.\nreliability(s) Reliability QoS.\n\nkind returns one of the SampleKinds singletons. Compare them with ===:\n\nif kind(s) === SampleKinds.PUT\n    # value was published\nelseif kind(s) === SampleKinds.DELETE\n    # key was deleted\nend\n\nSampleKinds is a module holding the two singleton instances SampleKinds.PUT and SampleKinds.DELETE, both subtyping the abstract SampleKind returned by kind.","title":"Reading a sample"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Zero-allocation-receive-loops","page":"Samples","text":"A SampleHolder is a caller-owned single slot you allocate once and refill in place, so a tight receive loop allocates nothing per sample. recv! blocks for the next sample, refills the holder in place (dropping the prior occupant), and returns it — or nothing once the subscriber is closed and drained. tryrecv! is the non-blocking variant: it refills the holder and returns it, or returns nothing when nothing is buffered.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nsession = open(Config())\nsub     = open(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/**\"); channel = :fifo, capacity = 16)\n\nholder = SampleHolder()\nwhile (s = recv!(sub, holder)) !== nothing\n    # `s` (and anything derived from it) is valid only until the next recv!.\n    if kind(s) === SampleKinds.PUT\n        key  = keyexpr(s)            # String, copied out\n        body = String(payload(s))    # decode the ZBytes payload, copied out\n        @info \"put\" key body encoding=encoding(s) priority=priority(s)\n\n        ts = timestamp(s)            # ZTimestamp or nothing\n        ts === nothing || @info \"stamped\" ntp64 = ntp64_time(ts)\n    elseif kind(s) === SampleKinds.DELETE\n        @info \"delete\" key = keyexpr(s)\n    end\nend\n\nclose(sub)\n\nIterating a buffered subscriber (for s in sub) reuses one holder internally, giving the same per-sample lifetime: process each s within its loop iteration.","title":"Zero-allocation receive loops"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Timestamps","page":"Samples","text":"A ZTimestamp is a Zenoh timestamp: an NTP64 time produced by a Hybrid Logical Clock plus the zid of the HLC that generated it. On a put, \"the first Zenoh router receiving this value automatically associates it with a timestamp\" (Zenoh timestamp).\n\nYou obtain a ZTimestamp two ways: read one off an inbound sample with timestamp, or mint a fresh one from a session's clock to stamp an outbound put, delete, or reply.\n\nts = ZTimestamp(session)                       # mint from the session's HLC\nput(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/example\"), \"hello\"; timestamp = ts)\n\nntp64_time returns the raw 64-bit NTP64 value as a UInt64. Split it yourself into the high 32 bits (seconds) and low 32 bits (fraction):\n\nraw      = ntp64_time(ts)\nseconds  = raw >> 32\nfraction = raw & 0xffffffff","title":"Timestamps"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Public-API","page":"Samples","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/samples/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Samples","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nSample Sample sample::Sample z_owned_sample_t / z_loaned_sample_t\npayload Value (payload half) Sample::payload() z_sample_payload\nkeyexpr / keyexpr_view Key expression Sample::key_expr() z_sample_keyexpr\nencoding Encoding Sample::encoding() z_sample_encoding\nkind → SampleKind SampleKind sample::SampleKind z_sample_kind, z_sample_kind_t\ntimestamp Timestamp Sample::timestamp() z_sample_timestamp\nattachment — Sample::attachment() z_sample_attachment\nexpress — Sample::express() z_sample_express\ncongestion_control — Sample::congestion_control() z_sample_congestion_control\npriority — Sample::priority() z_sample_priority\nreliability — Sample::reliability() z_sample_reliability\nZTimestamp Timestamp time::Timestamp z_timestamp_t\nZTimestamp(::Session) — Session::new_timestamp z_timestamp_new\nntp64_time NTP64 time time::NTP64 via get_time() z_timestamp_ntp64_time\nzid(::ZTimestamp) node UUID TimestampId via get_id() z_timestamp_id\n\nEach Zenoh.jl accessor maps one-to-one onto the corresponding z_sample_* C function (called through the loaned form), which in turn mirrors the Rust Sample accessor of the same name — including the four QoS accessors express, congestion_control, priority, and reliability, which match Rust's Sample::express(), Sample::congestion_control(), Sample::priority(), and Sample::reliability(). The mapping diverges in the following named ways.\n\nnote: Value is split into payload and encoding\nZenoh's Value fuses a payload with its encoding. Zenoh.jl exposes the two halves independently — payload returns a ZBytes and encoding returns an Encoding — with no fused Value wrapper, following zenoh-c.\n\nnote: kind reifies the enum as singleton types\nRust's SampleKind is an enum with Put and Delete variants. Zenoh.jl reifies these as the singleton instances SampleKinds.PUT and SampleKinds.DELETE under an abstract SampleKind supertype; compare them with ===.\n\nnote: NTP64 is returned raw\nntp64_time returns the raw 64-bit value as a UInt64. Split the high 32 bits (seconds) and low 32 bits (fraction) yourself. ZTimestamp holds z_timestamp_t by value (it carries no external resources), so there is no owned/loaned split and no drop.\n\nwarning: SampleHolder is a Zenoh.jl construct with no Zenoh counterpart\nSampleHolder reuses a single z_owned_sample_t slot for zero-allocation receive loops. It has no analog in the Rust or C API. Its occupant — and anything derived from it — is valid only until the next refill, a lifetime hazard absent from owned Samples. Rust models the borrow distinction through the borrow checker; Zenoh.jl enforces it by retaining owner and by convention.\n\nwarning: Samples are received-only\nRust offers SampleBuilder (and Put/Delete/Any variants) to construct a Sample, and SampleFields to destructure one without cloning. Zenoh.jl has neither: you only ever receive samples and read them through per-field accessors. Rust's source_info() (source id and sequence number, an unstable Rust API) likewise has no Zenoh.jl accessor, and the C z_sample_clone path is internal-only — the owned Sample comes from the receive machinery, never an explicit user clone.\n\nAll sample and timestamp functions live in the stable core C API (the z_ prefix); none use the zc_ config helpers or the experimental ze_ extensions (zenoh-c API).\n\nzid is exported, and zid(::ZTimestamp) is a method on that same generic shared with zid(::Session). After using Zenoh, call it directly as zid(ts) (or fully qualified as Zenoh.zid(ts)).","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.Sample","page":"Samples","text":"Sample\n\nA received sample. The owned form (from take! / :keep_all / get) owns its handle and drops it on GC, so it may be held arbitrarily long; the loaned form (from sample(::Reply)) borrows from owner.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Sample"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.SampleHolder","page":"Samples","text":"SampleHolder()\n\nA reusable, caller-owned sample slot for zero-allocation receiving. Allocate one and refill it in place with recv!/tryrecv!, or let for s in sub reuse one internally. Holds one owned sample at a time (dropped on the next recv! and on GC). The contained sample is valid only until the next refill — don't stash it or anything derived from it (payload, keyexpr, …) past then.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SampleHolder"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.payload","page":"Samples","text":"payload(s::AbstractSample) -> ZBytes\n\nThe sample's data as a loaned ZBytes borrowing from s, so the bytes stay valid for as long as the returned value is reachable. Pair with encoding to interpret them.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.payload"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.keyexpr","page":"Samples","text":"keyexpr(s::AbstractSample) -> String\n\nThe sample's key expression, copied into a freshly allocated String. On decode hot paths that only hash or compare the key, keyexpr_view avoids this allocation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.keyexpr"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.keyexpr_view","page":"Samples","text":"keyexpr_view(f, s::AbstractSample)\n\nCall f(ptr::Ptr{UInt8}, len::Int) with a zero-copy view of the sample's keyexpr bytes for the duration of f, without allocating the String that keyexpr copies out. s (and thus the borrowed keyexpr) is kept alive across f via GC.@preserve; the pointer is valid only within f. For decode hot paths that hash/compare the keyexpr bytes and only materialize a String on a cold miss.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.keyexpr_view"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.encoding","page":"Samples","text":"encoding(s::AbstractSample) -> Encoding\n\nThe Encoding describing the format of the sample's payload.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.encoding"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.attachment","page":"Samples","text":"attachment(s::AbstractSample) -> Union{ZBytes, Nothing}\n\nThe sample's attachment as a loaned ZBytes borrowing from s, or nothing when the sample carries no attachment.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.attachment"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.timestamp","page":"Samples","text":"timestamp(s::AbstractSample) -> Union{ZTimestamp, Nothing}\n\nThe sample's ZTimestamp (NTP64 time plus the generating node's id), or nothing when the sample carries none. The first Zenoh router to receive a put stamps it; samples that were never routed through a timestamping node arrive unstamped.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.timestamp"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.kind","page":"Samples","text":"kind(s::AbstractSample) -> SampleKind\n\nThe sample's SampleKind singleton: SampleKinds.PUT for a value-carrying put, SampleKinds.DELETE for a key deletion. Compare with ===.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.kind"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.priority","page":"Samples","text":"priority(s::AbstractSample) -> Priority\n\nThe Priority QoS the sample was published with.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.priority"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.congestion_control","page":"Samples","text":"congestion_control(s::AbstractSample) -> CongestionControl\n\nThe CongestionControl QoS the sample was published with.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.congestion_control"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.express","page":"Samples","text":"express(s::AbstractSample) -> Bool\n\nWhether the sample was sent express, bypassing the batching layer for lower latency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.express"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.reliability","page":"Samples","text":"reliability(s::AbstractSample) -> Reliability\n\nThe Reliability QoS the sample was published with.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.reliability"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.ZTimestamp","page":"Samples","text":"ZTimestamp\n\nA Zenoh timestamp held by value: an NTP64 time (a Hybrid Logical Clock reading) paired with the Zenoh id of the node that generated it. Read ntp64_time for the raw 64-bit time and Zenoh.zid for the generating node's id.\n\nMint a fresh one from a session's clock with ZTimestamp(::Session) to stamp an outbound put, delete, or reply; read one off an inbound sample with timestamp(::Sample). The underlying z_timestamp_t is a plain value carrying no external resources, so it lives by value in a Ref with no drop.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZTimestamp"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/samples/#Zenoh.ntp64_time","page":"Samples","text":"ntp64_time(z::ZTimestamp)\n\nReturns the timestamp's raw 64-bit NTP64 time as a UInt64, with the high 32 bits holding seconds and the low 32 bits the fraction (seconds << 32 | fraction); split them yourself to recover each part.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ntp64_time"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Shared-Memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"Shared memory (SHM) is Zenoh's same-host zero-copy transport: the payload lives in a POSIX shared-memory segment, and a receiver on the same machine reads it in place — zero network copy. Zenoh allocates the buffer from a provider, the publisher fills it, and the receiver gets a reference to that same segment — the bytes never leave it. Zenoh's SHM subsystem was heavily reworked in 1.0 with reference-counted buffers, dynamic transport negotiation, and aligned allocations.\n\nZenoh.jl exposes SHM through one typed handle, ZRef. The headline path is two calls: open a session with SHM enabled, then zref(session, T), which allocates from shared memory when it is available and falls back to the Julia heap otherwise — the same ZRef{T} either way, with no provider, buffer type, or SHM-specific call to name. Below that sit the receive-side views (borrow, with_memory) and, for direct control, the provider and buffer types (ShmProvider, alloc, ShmBufMut).\n\nwarning: Unstable upstream API\nZenoh's SHM API is documented as unstable, and cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments is Linux-only. The Zenoh.jl surface is stable, but the semantics it sits on may shift across Zenoh releases.","title":"Shared Memory"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Enabling-shared-memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"SHM requires both ends to opt in. The publisher allocates from a provider; the receiver maps incoming segments only after opening with a ShmClientStorage. A session opened without shm_clients reports shm_state :none and quietly uses the network for every payload.\n\nPass default_shm_clients to open on both ends:\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nsub = open(Config(); shm_clients = default_shm_clients())\npub = open(Config(); shm_clients = default_shm_clients(), wait_for_shm = true)\n\nThe provider warms up shortly after the session connects, so shm_state at open may be :initializing or :unavailable before settling (typically within a second or two). Two controls handle the warm-up:\n\nwait_for_shm = true (or a timeout in seconds) on open blocks until the provider is ready.\nshm_ready re-probes a live session and adopts the provider the moment it becomes usable.\n\nif shm_ready(pub)\n    @info \"SHM ready\" state = shm_state(pub) capable = shm_capable(pub)\nend\n\nshm_capable reports whether a provider is cached — true exactly when zref(session, T) will allocate from SHM.","title":"Enabling shared memory"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#The-transparent-path:-zref(session,-T)","page":"Shared Memory","text":"zref builds a typed handle over a payload buffer for an isbitstype T. Given a session it picks the backing for you: a shared-memory segment when the session has a provider, the Julia heap otherwise. Either way the handle is the same: write with r[] = x, read with r[], then put it.\n\nr = zref(pub, NTuple{4, Float64})   # writable handle into an SHM segment (or the Julia heap)\nr[] = (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0)\nput(pub, Keyexpr(\"demo/shm\"), r)    # hands the buffer off as the payload\n\nput takes ownership of the ZRef and consumes it; the payload travels without a copy. Reusing a consumed ZRef throws.\n\nIf the provider has not been obtained yet, zref(session, T) lazily attempts the obtain, so the fast path self-heals once SHM becomes ready without an explicit shm_ready call. A full segment surfaces as a ShmAllocError, which degrades to the Julia heap; register on_shm_alloc_error at open to escalate that failure instead of degrading silently.\n\nnote: `T` must be isbits, and zero-copy needs alignment\nzref rejects any T that is not isbitstype — a type holding Julia references would serialize live heap pointers. zref(session, T) requests T-alignment for the segment; SHM is the only transport that carries the sender's alignment through to the receiver, so it is the only one guaranteed to be read in place. Network paths read in place only when the slice is already T-aligned, and copy otherwise.","title":"The transparent path: zref(session, T)"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#The-receive-side","page":"Shared Memory","text":"A subscriber reconstructs the value with the same zref, passing the Sample. The callback form of open delivers each sample to your function:\n\nopen(sub, Keyexpr(\"demo/shm\")) do sample\n    r = zref(sample, NTuple{4, Float64})\n    @info \"received\" value = r[] borrowed = isborrowed(r)\nend\n\nzref(sample, T) resolves through three tiers, picking the fastest the payload allows:\n\nSHM — the payload is a shared segment, contiguous and sender-aligned: read in place, zero copy.\nContiguous network slice — a single network slice that happens to be T-aligned: read in place, zero copy.\nCopy — fragmented or misaligned: the bytes are copied once into an aligned box.\n\nisborrowed tells the two apart: true for tiers 1 and 2 (a zero-copy view), false when a copy was materialized. Use it to assert the fast path held.\n\nwarning: A borrowed view must not escape the callback\nA borrowed ZRef, Borrowed, or PayloadView pins the sample and is valid only while the sample is reachable. Read or copy the value out before the callback returns. as_memory(payload(sample), T) copies the payload into an owned Memory{T} you can keep; collect on a Borrowed does the same.\n\nFor byte-oriented access scoped to a block, borrow and with_memory hand you a Borrowed{T} view — b[] or b.field for a struct, b[i]/iteration for a buffer. with_memory closes the borrow when its function returns, so an escaped view raises a catchable BorrowError on its next use:\n\nopen(sub, Keyexpr(\"demo/shm\")) do sample\n    total = with_memory(sample, Float64) do b\n        sum(b)              # zero-copy on the SHM / aligned-slice path\n    end\n    @info \"sum\" total\nend\n\nThe lower-level with_payload_memory and the validated with_payload_memory_checked variants are covered under Payloads & Serialization. The unsafe_* variants (unsafe_with_memory, unsafe_memory) drop the per-access checks for known-correct hot paths.","title":"The receive side"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Direct-provider-and-buffer-control","page":"Shared Memory","text":"For raw byte buffers, control over allocation policy, or capacity inspection, work with a provider directly. Two kinds exist, both AbstractShmProvider:\n\nShmProvider(size) — a standalone POSIX provider of fixed byte capacity.\nobtain_shm_provider(session) — the session's own provider (a SharedShmProvider), the same one zref(session, T) uses.\n\nalloc returns a writable ShmBufMut; fill it, then turn it into a payload with ZBytes, which hands the buffer off as the message body:\n\nprov = obtain_shm_provider(pub)         # SharedShmProvider\n@info \"available bytes\" available(prov)\n\nbuf = alloc(prov, 1024; align = 8, blocking = true)   # ShmBufMut\ncopyto!(buf, rand(UInt8, 1024))\nput(pub, Keyexpr(\"demo/raw\"), ZBytes(buf))            # hands the buffer off as the payload\n\nalloc has two modes: the default allocates immediately and throws ShmAllocError on a full segment; blocking = true first garbage-collects and defragments, then waits for space. align requests a power-of-2 alignment and selects the aligned allocator; an invalid layout throws ShmLayoutError.\n\navailable, defragment, and garbage_collect inspect and maintain a provider's free space, each returning a size in bytes. On the receive side, as_shm views a received ZBytes as a ShmBuf for a zero-copy read, and is_shm tests SHM backing without obtaining the buffer; data exposes a buffer's bytes as a Memory{UInt8}.\n\nwarning: Orphaned segments are not freed on close\nPOSIX /dev/shm segments left by a process that exited without releasing them are reclaimed only by cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments (Linux) or process-level cleanup — never when the provider is released or the session closes. The session obtains its provider at most once per lifetime, so it materializes only one set of segments.\n\ncleanup_orphaned_shm_segments()   # Linux: reclaim segments left by dead processes","title":"Direct provider and buffer control"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Public-API","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Session-SHM-controls","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Session SHM controls"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Providers-and-allocation","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Providers and allocation"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Buffers-and-payload-bridge","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Buffers and payload bridge"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Client-storage-and-maintenance","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Client storage and maintenance"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Errors","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Errors"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Typed-handles-and-views","page":"Shared Memory","text":"","title":"Typed handles and views"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Shared Memory","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nShmProvider(size) ShmProvider (POSIX backend) ShmProvider<PosixShmProviderBackend> z_posix_shm_provider_new\nSharedShmProvider / obtain_shm_provider session-derived SHM provider session/global provider z_obtain_shm_provider\nalloc(p, n; align, blocking) provider alloc + AllocPolicy ShmProvider::alloc(...).with_policy z_shm_provider_alloc / _aligned / _gc_defrag_blocking / _gc_defrag_blocking_aligned\navailable / defragment / garbage_collect provider inspection/maintenance ShmProvider::available / defragment / garbage_collect z_shm_provider_available / _defragment / _garbage_collect\nShmBufMut / ShmBuf ZShmMut / ZShm ZShmMut / ZShm z_owned_shm_mut_t / z_owned_shm_t / z_loaned_shm_t\nShmBuf(::ShmBufMut) freeze mutable → immutable ZShm: From<ZShmMut> z_shm_from_mut\nZBytes(::ShmBufMut) / ZBytes(::ShmBuf) SHM buffer → payload bytes from SHM z_bytes_from_shm_mut / z_bytes_from_shm\nas_shm / is_shm view payload as SHM bytes as loaned SHM z_bytes_as_loaned_shm\nshm_state symbols ShmProviderState ShmProviderState z_shm_provider_state\nShmAllocError / ShmLayoutError alloc / layout failures ZAllocError / ZLayoutError z_alloc_error_t / z_layout_error_t\nShmClientStorage / default_shm_clients ShmClientStorage ShmClientStorage z_owned_shm_client_storage_t / z_shm_client_storage_new_default\nopen(cfg; shm_clients=...) session with SHM clients Session::open with client storage z_open_with_custom_shm_clients\ncleanup_orphaned_shm_segments orphan-segment cleanup (Linux) cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments zc_cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments\nZRef / zref — — —\n\nThe provider, buffer, client-storage, error, and inspection types map one-to-one onto the zenoh::shm module and its zenoh-c z_-prefixed counterparts. The equivalence is exact for these, with a few precise narrowings.\n\nalloc folds four distinct C entry points — and Rust's AllocBuilder policy chain — into one call governed by two keywords. Only two policies are reachable: the default (Rust JustAlloc) and blocking = true (Rust GarbageCollect + Defragment + BlockOn). The intermediate GarbageCollect-only, Defragment-only, and non-blocking BlockOn policies have no Julia surface. ShmProvider(size) takes only a size — z_posix_shm_provider_new with an implied layout — rather than an explicit z_memory_layout_t; alignment is expressed per allocation through align instead. The owned/loaned/moved distinction is internal: ShmBufMut and ShmBuf (parameterized by backing) are the only user-facing buffer types, and finalizers plus a consumed flag enforce drop and move-once invariants, so you never name z_loan/z_move/z_drop.\n\nA few capabilities present upstream are not surfaced from Julia: custom ShmClient protocol implementations (default_shm_clients is the only client set), an explicit MemoryLayout type, and Zenoh's typed-SHM Typed<T> wrapper — Zenoh.jl provides typed access through its own ZRef{T} / Borrowed{T} over raw byte buffers.\n\nnote: Zenoh.jl extension: `ZRef` and the transparent session path\nZRef and zref have no Zenoh or zenoh-c counterpart. They unify four backings — a Julia Ref box, a ShmBufMut, a ShmBuf, and a contiguous network view — behind one typed handle so the authoring, send, and receive API is identical with or without SHM. The transparent session policy — zref(session, T) using SHM when ready and degrading to the Julia heap on a full segment or no provider, plus the on_shm_alloc_error escalation hook — is a Zenoh.jl construct. So is the session-level lifecycle: shm_state's :none and :unavailable symbols (Zenoh's ShmProviderState has only ready/initializing/disabled/error), shm_capable, shm_ready, the warm-up wait, lazy self-healing obtain, and the one-obtain-per-session leak guard are all Zenoh.jl bookkeeping over z_obtain_shm_provider.\n\nSee Payloads & Serialization for the full view-and-borrow API, Sessions & Configuration for open, and Publish & Subscribe for put/declare.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.shm_state","page":"Shared Memory","text":"shm_state(s::Session) -> Symbol\n\nThe session's shared-memory capability as discovered at open (snapshot):\n\n:none        — opened without shm_clients; SHM was never requested.\n:unavailable — obtaining a provider failed (build/config has no SHM).\n:disabled    — provider reports disabled.\n:initializing— provider is warming up (lazy mode); allocations may not                  succeed yet but zref(s, T) will start using SHM once ready.\n:ready       — provider is usable now.\n:error       — provider entered an error state.\n\nzref(s, T) uses shared memory when this is :ready or :initializing, and falls back to Julia memory otherwise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.shm_state"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.shm_capable","page":"Shared Memory","text":"shm_capable(s::Session) -> Bool\n\nTrue if the session has a cached SHM provider that zref(s, T) will allocate from (state :ready or :initializing); false if zref falls back to Julia memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.shm_capable"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.shm_ready","page":"Shared Memory","text":"shm_ready(s::Session) -> Bool\n\nRe-probe the session now and report whether its SHM provider is ready to allocate. Unlike shm_state (a snapshot taken at open), this re-attempts the provider obtain and adopts the provider into the session cache if it has since become usable — so once this returns true, shm_capable(s) is also true and zref(s, T) allocates from shared memory. Useful when SHM hadn't finished warming up at open (a session reports :unavailable/:initializing until the provider settles, typically within a second or two of connecting). Always false for a session opened without shm_clients.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.shm_ready"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.AbstractShmProvider","page":"Shared Memory","text":"AbstractShmProvider\n\nSupertype of the shared-memory provider wrappers, ShmProvider (a standalone POSIX segment) and SharedShmProvider (a session-derived provider). A provider is the source zero-copy SHM buffers are allocated from; alloc, available, defragment, garbage_collect, and zref(p, T) all dispatch on this type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AbstractShmProvider"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmProvider","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmProvider <: AbstractShmProvider\nShmProvider(size::Integer)\n\nA standalone POSIX shared-memory provider of fixed byte capacity, backed by a /dev/shm segment created directly via z_posix_shm_provider_new. The owned provider handle is released by a finalizer.\n\nUse this to allocate SHM buffers without a session; for the provider tied to an open session (and the transparent zref(s::Session, T) fast path), see SharedShmProvider and obtain_shm_provider.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmProvider"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.SharedShmProvider","page":"Shared Memory","text":"SharedShmProvider <: AbstractShmProvider\n\nThe shared-memory provider belonging to an open Session, obtained from its SHM subsystem via z_obtain_shm_provider. This is the provider cached in Session.shm and used by the transparent zref(s::Session, T) fast path; obtain_shm_provider returns one for explicit use.\n\nWhen obtained through the public API it pins its Session alive (loaning the provider reaches into session state); the session's own cached copy holds no back-reference, since the session already outlives it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SharedShmProvider"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.session_shm_provider","page":"Shared Memory","text":"session_shm_provider(s::Session) -> Union{SharedShmProvider, Nothing}\n\nThe session's own cached SHM provider (bound at open when shm_clients was supplied and SHM became usable), or nothing otherwise. A pure read — unlike obtain_shm_provider it neither re-obtains nor pins the session, so a caller reuses the session's single provider with no double-obtain; it is released with the session.\n\nNote the provider warms up lazily: just after open (without wait_for_shm) this may still be nothing even though SHM will shortly become ready. Capturing the result once is therefore only safe behind open(...; wait_for_shm=true) or a shm_ready(s) gate — otherwise a capture taken too early pins the Julia fallback for the session's life. For the transparent self-healing path that re-checks on every call, use zref(s::Session, T) instead.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.session_shm_provider"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.obtain_shm_provider","page":"Shared Memory","text":"obtain_shm_provider(s::Session) -> SharedShmProvider\n\nObtain the SharedShmProvider for an open session, for explicit allocation via alloc or inspection via available. The returned provider pins s alive for as long as it is held.\n\nFor the transparent fast path that allocates SHM when available and falls back to Julia memory otherwise, prefer zref(s::Session, T), which uses the session's own cached provider.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.obtain_shm_provider"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.alloc","page":"Shared Memory","text":"alloc(p::AbstractShmProvider, n::Integer; align=nothing) -> ShmBufMut\n\nAllocate an n-byte writable ShmBufMut from the provider, trying once and returning immediately. align, when given, must be a power of two and constrains the segment's start to that boundary.\n\nThrows ShmAllocError when the segment cannot satisfy the request (full or fragmented — the expected steady state under load; see try_alloc for a non-throwing twin) and ShmLayoutError when the size/alignment layout is invalid. For the GC + defragment + blocking policy, see alloc_blocking.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.alloc"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.try_alloc","page":"Shared Memory","text":"try_alloc(p::AbstractShmProvider, n::Integer; align=nothing) -> Union{ShmBufMut, Nothing}\n\nNon-throwing, try-once twin of alloc: returns the ShmBufMut on success and nothing when the segment is full or fragmented (ShmAllocError's conditions — the expected steady state under load, so no exception is constructed on that path). A genuine misconfiguration still throws: an invalid size/alignment layout raises ShmLayoutError, and a non-power-of-two align raises ArgumentError. Use this on degrade-aware paths to avoid try/catch over a non-exceptional outcome.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.try_alloc"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.alloc_blocking","page":"Shared Memory","text":"alloc_blocking(p::AbstractShmProvider, n::Integer; align=nothing) -> ShmBufMut\n\nLike alloc but selects the GC + defragment + blocking allocation policy: it reclaims and coalesces free space and waits for room rather than failing fast.\n\nwarning: Warning\nThis blocks the calling task until room frees up — keep it off a publish/serialize hot path, where a stall would back up your own pipeline. The blocking ccall is marked gc_safe, so it does not stall a stop-the-world GC on another thread (unlike a plain blocking ccall, which would — see core/gc_safe_threadcall.jl). The split from alloc is deliberate: the hot path cannot reach the blocking policy by flipping a flag.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.alloc_blocking"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.available","page":"Shared Memory","text":"available(p::AbstractShmProvider) -> Int\n\nBytes currently free for allocation from the provider. Wraps z_shm_provider_available.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.available"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.defragment","page":"Shared Memory","text":"defragment(p::AbstractShmProvider) -> Int\n\nCoalesce the provider's free space into larger contiguous runs and return the resulting size. Useful to recover from a ShmAllocError(:need_defragment) before retrying alloc. Wraps z_shm_provider_defragment.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.defragment"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.garbage_collect","page":"Shared Memory","text":"garbage_collect(p::AbstractShmProvider) -> Int\n\nReclaim free chunks no longer referenced anywhere in the SHM domain and return the collected size. Wraps z_shm_provider_garbage_collect.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.garbage_collect"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmBufMut","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmBufMut\n\nAn owned, writable shared-memory segment produced by alloc, exposing its bytes as a Memory{UInt8} (data, pointer, length, copyto!). Write the payload, then move it into a sendable ZBytes (ZBytes(buf), the zero-copy send path) or freeze it into an immutable ShmBuf (ShmBuf(buf)). Wraps z_owned_shm_mut_t; the handle is released by a finalizer, or consumed by the move.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmBufMut"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmBuf","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmBuf{R}\n\nAn immutable shared-memory buffer exposing its bytes as a Memory{UInt8} (data, pointer, length), in one of two forms selected by the backing R:\n\nowned (Base.RefValue{z_owned_shm_t}) — frozen from a ShmBufMut via ShmBuf(buf), dropped by a finalizer.\nborrowed (Ptr{z_loaned_shm_t}) — a zero-copy view over a received SHM payload returned by as_shm, pinning its parent ZBytes so the loan stays valid.\n\nSend an owned buffer by moving it into a ZBytes (ZBytes(buf)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmBuf"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.data","page":"Shared Memory","text":"data(b::ShmBufMut) -> Memory{UInt8}\ndata(b::ShmBuf)    -> Memory{UInt8}\n\nThe buffer's bytes as a Memory{UInt8} backed directly by the shared-memory segment (zero-copy). Mutating the result of data(::ShmBufMut) writes the segment in place.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.data"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.as_shm","page":"Shared Memory","text":"as_shm(z::ZBytes) -> Union{ShmBuf,Nothing}\n\nView a received payload as a borrowed ShmBuf for zero-copy reads, pinning z so the loan stays valid. Returns nothing when the payload is not backed by a shared-memory segment (e.g. it arrived over the network). Use is_shm to test without constructing a view.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.as_shm"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.is_shm","page":"Shared Memory","text":"is_shm(z::ZBytes) -> Bool\n\nTrue if the received payload is backed by a shared-memory segment (and so can be read zero-copy via as_shm); false if it arrived as a plain byte copy.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.is_shm"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmClientStorage","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmClientStorage\n\nThe set of SHM client implementations a session registers at open so it can read incoming shared-memory buffers. Each registered client knows how to map one SHM protocol's segments into the process, giving the session the capability to interpret SHM-backed payloads it receives. Pass one to open via the shm_clients keyword; without it the session has no SHM and shm_state reports :none.\n\nBuild the default set with default_shm_clients. Wraps z_owned_shm_client_storage_t.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmClientStorage"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.default_shm_clients","page":"Shared Memory","text":"default_shm_clients() -> ShmClientStorage\n\nA ShmClientStorage populated with the default client set, ready to enable shared memory on a session. Pass it as open(cfg; shm_clients = default_shm_clients()) so the session can read SHM buffers for the standard protocols.\n\nWraps z_shm_client_storage_new_default.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.default_shm_clients"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments","page":"Shared Memory","text":"cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments()\n\nReclaim POSIX /dev/shm segments left behind by processes that exited without releasing them (Linux only). SHM buffers are reference-counted and auto-reclaimed across the domain, but a crashed process's backing segments need this sweep — they are not freed on provider drop or session close. Wraps the unstable zenoh-c-specific zc_cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.cleanup_orphaned_shm_segments"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmAllocError","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmAllocError <: Exception\n\nSignals that a runtime shared-memory allocation could not be satisfied. The kind::Symbol field carries the reason from zenoh's allocator:\n\n:need_defragment — the segment is fragmented; defragment may free a contiguous run large enough to retry.\n:out_of_memory   — the provider has no free space for the request.\n:other           — any other allocator failure.\n\nThrown by alloc. zref(s::Session, T) catches this and falls back to Julia memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmAllocError"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ShmLayoutError","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ShmLayoutError <: Exception\n\nSignals that a shared-memory allocation's size/alignment layout is invalid or the provider cannot honor it. The kind::Symbol field is one of:\n\n:incorrect_layout_args  — the requested size/alignment is not a valid layout.\n:provider_incompatible  — the provider cannot serve the requested layout.\n\nThrown by alloc.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ShmLayoutError"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.ZRef","page":"Shared Memory","text":"ZRef{T, B}\n\nA typed, transport-agnostic, minimum-copy handle over a payload buffer for an isbits type T. The authoring API (r[] = x, r[], pointer(r)), the send path (put), and the receive constructor are identical whether the bytes live in Julia heap, a shared-memory segment, or a network view; the backing B is the only axis of variation.\n\nConstruct one with zref: a writable handle backed by Julia memory or an SHM segment on the send side, or a reconstruction of a received Sample on the receive side. isborrowed reports whether the handle is a zero-copy view or owns a materialized copy.\n\nA send-side ZRef is single-use: put borrows or moves its backing and marks it consumed, after which any access throws. A receive-side borrowed ZRef is valid only while reachable (it pins the sample) — read or copy out before the callback returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZRef"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.zref","page":"Shared Memory","text":"zref(T) -> ZRef{T}\n\nA writable, Julia-memory-backed handle for a value of isbits type T. Write it with r[] = x (or field-wise through pointer(r)), then put it. zenoh borrows the buffer on send — no copy into a zenoh buffer.\n\n\n\n\n\nzref(provider::AbstractShmProvider, T) -> ZRef{T}\n\nAllocate a shared-memory buffer for T from provider and return a handle that writes straight into the segment. Requests alignment matching T so the receiver can view it in place; if the provider can't honor that alignment (ShmLayoutError) it retries unaligned, and the receiver falls back to a copy.\n\n\n\n\n\nzref(s::Session, T) -> ZRef{T}\n\nThe transparent fast path: allocate from the session's SHM provider when one is available (the session was opened with shm_clients and SHM is enabled), otherwise fall back to Julia memory. A full segment (ShmAllocError) also degrades to Julia memory. Either way you get the same ZRef{T} and never name a provider.\n\nIf the provider hasn't been obtained yet (it warms up shortly after the session connects, and open didn't wait_for_shm), this lazily attempts the obtain so the fast path self-heals once SHM becomes ready — without you having to call shm_ready. The attempt is skipped for terminal states (:none/:disabled/ :error); while still warming up the obtain fails cheaply and allocates nothing.\n\nOn the ShmAllocError degrade path a @debug is emitted and the session's on_shm_alloc_error callback (if registered at open) is invoked with the error — it may throw to escalate instead of falling back.\n\n\n\n\n\nzref(sample::Sample, T) -> ZRef{T}\n\nReconstruct a T from a received sample, transport-agnostically. Zero-copy when the payload is SHM-backed (tier 1) or a single contiguous, T-aligned network slice (tier 2); otherwise the bytes are copied once into an aligned box (tier 3). Read the value with r[]. A borrowed ZRef is only valid while reachable (it pins the sample) — read or copy out before the callback returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.zref"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.isborrowed","page":"Shared Memory","text":"isborrowed(r::ZRef) -> Bool\n\nTrue if r is a zero-copy view into the underlying payload (SHM or contiguous network slice); false if it owns a materialized copy. Useful for asserting the fast path was taken.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.isborrowed"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.borrow","page":"Shared Memory","text":"borrow(z::ZBytes, T=UInt8; writable=false)   -> Borrowed{T}\nborrow(s::Sample, T=UInt8; writable=false)   -> Borrowed{T}\n\nA scope-validated view of the payload as T. Read a single struct with b[] or b.field, a buffer with b[i]/iteration; get the length with length(b). The borrow pins its source while valid; call close(b) when done, after which any use throws a BorrowError. Prefer with_memory, which closes automatically (and so detects escapes).\n\nWith writable=false (default) the view is zero-copy when possible (SHM-backed or a single contiguous, T-aligned network slice), else a one-time copy, and is read-only — mutating a view of received/shared memory is unsafe. With writable=true it always owns a private copy, and b.field = v / b[i] = v / b[] = v mutate that copy in place (use collect/as_memory to extract it).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.borrow"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.Borrowed","page":"Shared Memory","text":"Borrowed{T}\n\nA scope-validated, value-first view of a payload reinterpreted as T. It reads both like the struct — b[] dereferences the single element, b.field reads a field — and like an array — b[i], iteration, length, collect. While valid it pins its source (the Sample/ZBytes or an owned copy) so the bytes stay live; close(b) drops the pin, after which every access throws a BorrowError.\n\nMutation (b.field = v, b[i] = v, b[] = v) requires a writable borrow, which owns a private copy. A zero-copy view of a received payload is read-only, since its backing is loaned or shared memory.\n\nConstruct one with borrow, or scope it to a block with with_memory, which closes it automatically and so catches escapes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Borrowed"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.BorrowError","page":"Shared Memory","text":"BorrowError <: Exception\n\nSignals that a Borrowed view (or a GuardedPayloadView) was used outside its valid scope: after close, or after it escaped the with_memory / with_payload_memory_checked call that produced it. The check fires on every access so a stale view raises a catchable error rather than reading freed memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.BorrowError"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.PayloadView","page":"Shared Memory","text":"PayloadView <: DenseVector{UInt8}\n\nAn isbits (ptr, len) view of a byte buffer as a DenseVector{UInt8}, so a borrowed payload can back a CDRReader / CDRString / CDRView with no heap allocation — unlike unsafe_wrap(Memory{UInt8}, …), which heap-allocates a Memory header per borrow. Because it is isbits, a CDRString{PayloadView} (and the CDRView holding it) is itself isbits and stack-allocates.\n\nHolds no GC root of its own: the bytes are kept alive by the enclosing with_payload_memory's GC.@preserve for the duration of f only. Any use past f (a view that escapes the handler) reads freed memory — the same contract as with_payload_memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.PayloadView"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.GuardedPayloadView","page":"Shared Memory","text":"GuardedPayloadView <: DenseVector{UInt8}\n\nLike PayloadView but carrying a shared validity flag: once the enclosing with_payload_memory_checked call returns, the flag is cleared and every subsequent access throws BorrowError. This turns the fast-path's silent use-after-free (a CDRView/CDRString that escaped the handler) into a loud, debuggable error — over the same representation the zero-copy path ships, so it validates the exact code you'll run unchecked.\n\nNot isbits (it holds the flag Ref), so it allocates — it's the validation tier, not the production tier.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.GuardedPayloadView"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.as_memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"as_memory(z::ZBytes, T=UInt8) -> Memory{T}\n\nCopy the payload into a freshly-allocated, owned Memory{T} — safe to keep past the originating sample/callback, and ready to hand to a (de)serializer. The byte length must be a multiple of sizeof(T). For zero-copy access scoped to a block, use with_memory. To go the other way (publish a Memory), ZBytes(m).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.as_memory"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.with_memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"with_memory(f, z::ZBytes, T=UInt8; writable=false)\nwith_memory(f, s::AbstractSample, T=UInt8; writable=false)\n\nCall f(b::Borrowed{T}) with a scope-validated view of the payload, then close the borrow — so a Borrowed (or pointer) that escapes f is invalidated and any later use throws a BorrowError instead of reading freed memory. Read a single struct with b[]/b.field, a buffer with b[i]/iteration. With writable=true, b owns a copy you may mutate (b.field = v, b[i] = v). Returns f's result. To keep data past the call, copy out with as_memory or collect(b).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.with_memory"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.with_payload_memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"with_payload_memory(f, z::ZBytes)\nwith_payload_memory(f, s::AbstractSample)\n\nCall f(view::PayloadView) with a zero-copy PayloadView of the payload bytes for the duration of f, with no allocation on the contiguous path: no Borrowed/_ZRefView wrappers (unlike with_memory) and — since PayloadView is isbits — no unsafe_wrap Memory header either. SHM payloads and a single contiguous network slice are viewed in place; a fragmented payload falls back to an owned as_memory copy, still presented as a PayloadView (so f sees one type on every tier). The backing bytes are kept alive across f via GC.@preserve.\n\nLower-level than with_memory: it skips the scope-validated BorrowError safety net, so it's for internal decode paths that consume the bytes within f and don't let them escape. Anything escaping f reads freed memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.with_payload_memory"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.with_payload_memory_checked","page":"Shared Memory","text":"with_payload_memory_checked(f, z::ZBytes)\nwith_payload_memory_checked(f, s::AbstractSample)\n\nLike with_payload_memory but hands f a GuardedPayloadView: the zero-copy fast-path representation plus a runtime escape check. The view is invalidated the instant f returns, so a CDRView/CDRString that escaped f throws BorrowError on its next access instead of reading freed memory. The validation tier — run a view handler under this to confirm it doesn't escape, then switch to with_payload_memory for the allocation-free production path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.with_payload_memory_checked"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.unsafe_with_memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"unsafe_with_memory(f, z::ZBytes, T=UInt8)\nunsafe_with_memory(f, s::Sample, T=UInt8)\n\nLike with_memory but passes f a raw Memory{T} instead of a validated Borrowed — no per-access checks and no escape detection. The view is zero-copy when possible (SHM / contiguous aligned slice), else a one-time copy, and is pinned only for the duration of f via GC.@preserve. If the Memory (or a pointer into it) escapes f, any later use is undefined behaviour. Returns f's result.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.unsafe_with_memory"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.unsafe_memory","page":"Shared Memory","text":"unsafe_memory(b::Borrowed{T}) -> Memory{T}\n\nExtract the underlying Memory{T} from a Borrowed for a tight inner loop, bypassing the per-access checks. Validity is checked once, here; the returned Memory is raw — it is only valid while b is (before close(b) / before the enclosing with_memory returns), and you must keep b reachable (e.g. GC.@preserve b) while using it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.unsafe_memory"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.shm_serialize","page":"Shared Memory","text":"shm_serialize(fill!, p::AbstractShmProvider, n::Integer; align=nothing) -> ZBytes\n\nAllocate an n-byte SHM buffer from p, call fill!(mem::Memory{UInt8}) to write the payload straight into the segment, then move it into a sendable owned ZBytes — alloc, fill, bounded move, and cleanup all inside the library. If fill! throws, the buffer is released on the calling task (close) before rethrowing, so a half-filled segment never leaks. Throws the same ShmAllocError/ShmLayoutError as alloc when the segment can't be obtained; catch those to fall back to heap memory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.shm_serialize"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/shared-memory/#Zenoh.put-Tuple{Publisher, ZRef}","page":"Shared Memory","text":"put(p::Publisher, r::ZRef; kwargs...)\nput(s::Session, k::Keyexpr, r::ZRef; congestion_control, priority, express, allowed_destination, kwargs...)\n\nPublish the value held by ZRef r. A Julia-backed handle is borrowed (pinned for the lifetime of the payload); an SHM-backed handle is moved into the payload zero-copy. Either way the backing becomes the published bytes and r is marked consumed — a second put (or any access) on it throws.\n\nkwargs set per-put options such as encoding, attachment, and timestamp.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.put"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Logging","page":"Logging","text":"Zenoh runs its own Rust logger over the tracing crate. Zenoh.jl gives you two ways to consume it. Tier A initializes the built-in stderr subscriber from a fallback level plus the RUST_LOG/ZENOH_LOG environment variables — the standard way to watch what a session is doing. Tier B installs an in-process callback that captures the log stream into Julia as a bounded, pull-based LogStream of LogRecords; route them wherever you like, such as onto a ROS logging topic for unified remote debugging.\n\nLogging is an observability concern of the implementation, so this page documents wrapper and runtime behavior. (It is the one page here with no entry in Zenoh's abstractions.) Zenoh's log initialization is process-global, one-shot, and irreversible: the two tiers are mutually exclusive, the first call wins, and a second call throws.","title":"Logging"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Tier-A-—-stderr-/-environment","page":"Logging","text":"setup_logging installs Zenoh's stderr subscriber with a fallback filter, used when neither RUST_LOG nor ZENOH_LOG is set. The fallback is a level string (\"info\", \"debug\", …, following tracing's EnvFilter syntax) or a LogSeverity.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nZenoh.setup_logging()                            # fallback \"info\", overridable by RUST_LOG / ZENOH_LOG\nZenoh.setup_logging(\"debug\")                     # or any tracing filter string\nZenoh.setup_logging(Zenoh.LogSeverities.WARN)    # or a LogSeverity\n\ntry_init_logging_from_env installs the same stderr subscriber purely from RUST_LOG/ZENOH_LOG, with no fallback, and is a no-op when both are unset — the right choice when logging should stay silent until an operator opts in via the environment.\n\nZenoh.try_init_logging_from_env()   # env-only; silent if RUST_LOG / ZENOH_LOG are unset\n\nBoth are global and one-shot; choose this path or Tier B at startup.","title":"Tier A — stderr / environment"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Tier-B-—-capture-into-Julia","page":"Logging","text":"open_log_stream installs Zenoh's in-process log callback and captures every record at min_severity and above into a fixed-capacity ring, returned as a LogStream. Capture is opt-in: nothing is installed until you call it.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nls = Zenoh.open_log_stream(; min_severity = Zenoh.LogSeverities.WARN, capacity = 256)\n\nmin_severity is enforced inside Zenoh: below-floor records are never delivered to Julia. The floor is therefore free and is the primary feedback-loop defense (see Feedback loops when forwarding logs). capacity bounds the ring; when the consumer falls behind, the oldest records are dropped and counted by dropped_count. Memory stays bounded.\n\nA LogStream yields LogRecords, the exact (severity, message) pair Zenoh passes to the callback. Consume them by iterating (blocks per record), with take! (blocking), or with tryrecv! (non-blocking); call close when done.\n\n# Drain promptly on a task so the ring does not overflow.\nconsumer = @async for rec in ls            # iterate blocks for each record\n    println(rec.severity, \": \", rec.message)   # rec.severity::LogSeverity, rec.message::String\nend\n\n# Non-blocking poll:\nrec = Zenoh.tryrecv!(ls)            # a LogRecord, or nothing if the ring is empty or the stream is closed\nrec === nothing || handle(rec.severity, rec.message)\n\n# Blocking pull of a single record:\nrec = take!(ls)                     # blocks until a record arrives; throws if closed while waiting\n\n@info \"dropped so far\" Zenoh.dropped_count(ls)\n\nclose(ls)   # stop delivery and free buffered records; the logger stays installed for the process\n\ntake!, close, and iterate are Base methods specialized on LogStream, used as shown above; the Zenoh.jl exports are open_log_stream, tryrecv!, and dropped_count.","title":"Tier B — capture into Julia"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Lifecycle","page":"Logging","text":"Because Zenoh's logger is process-global and one-shot, exactly one LogStream exists per process. close stops delivery and frees buffered records, but cannot uninstall Zenoh's logger. Logging stays initialized for the process, so a later open_log_stream (or setup_logging) still throws.\n\nwarning: Decide at startup\nChoose between Tier A (setup_logging / try_init_logging_from_env) and Tier B (open_log_stream) when the process starts. The first call wins; the second throws; close does not re-enable a fresh open_log_stream.","title":"Lifecycle"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Severities","page":"Logging","text":"Severities are singleton values under the LogSeverities module, ordered TRACE < DEBUG < INFO < WARN < ERROR; Base.isless and <= compare them directly.\n\nLogSeverity\nLogSeverities.TRACE\nLogSeverities.DEBUG\nLogSeverities.INFO\nLogSeverities.WARN\nLogSeverities.ERROR\n\nThe exported abstract supertype LogSeverity is the accepted argument type for setup_logging and min_severity in open_log_stream, and the field type of LogRecord.severity.","title":"Severities"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Feedback-loops-when-forwarding-logs","page":"Logging","text":"Forwarding a captured log back over Zenoh (for example, republishing it onto a ROS logging topic) makes Zenoh log that publish, which could be captured and forwarded again. The callback delivers only (severity, message), with no structured origin: the wrapper cannot tell a log caused by its own forwarding publish from any other. Loop prevention rests on two mechanisms and belongs to the integrator:\n\nOpen the stream at WARN or higher. A forwarding publish's own logs are data-plane DEBUG/TRACE; a WARN floor enforced inside Zenoh keeps them out of the stream entirely, so steady-state forwarding cannot feed itself.\nRely on the bounded drop-oldest ring as the backstop. A genuine WARN/ERROR that does loop churns the ring and bumps dropped_count — a diagnosable storm of one repeated message, with memory still bounded.\n\nOne self-sustaining ERROR loop the floor cannot stop: a record that reports a failure of the logging transport itself, republished onto that same transport. Guard against it by dropping records whose text matches the logging endpoint, or by forwarding logs over a dedicated session you never log-forward about. Surface dropped_count as a health metric — nonzero means the consumer or the forwarding path cannot keep up, or a loop is churning the ring.","title":"Feedback loops when forwarding logs"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#API","page":"Logging","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/logging/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Logging","text":"The zenoh-c documentation renders as one long single-file page; follow a C-symbol link, then in-page search for the zc_ name to reach its definition.\n\nZenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nsetup_logging — (operational, not an abstraction) zenoh::init_log_from_env_or zc_init_log_from_env_or\ntry_init_logging_from_env — zenoh::try_init_log_from_env zc_try_init_log_from_env\nopen_log_stream — (no safe-Rust equivalent) zc_init_log_with_callback + zc_closure_log\nLogSeverity / LogSeverities — (none; enum) zc_log_severity_t\nLogRecord — (callback args) zc_closure_log_call args (severity, msg)\nLogStream / tryrecv! / dropped_count / take! / close — (no Zenoh API) (no Zenoh API)\n\nsetup_logging calls zc_init_log_from_env_or, the C wrapper over Rust zenoh::init_log_from_env_or, installing the tracing stderr subscriber with the supplied filter as the fallback when RUST_LOG/ZENOH_LOG is unset. try_init_logging_from_env calls zc_try_init_log_from_env (zenoh::try_init_log_from_env), installing it only when the environment variable is set. The LogSeverities constants map 1:1 onto zc_log_severity_t enumerators, and the Julia isless ordering reproduces the C enum's 0..4 order. A LogRecord materializes the (severity, message) pair Zenoh passes to the log closure.\n\nsetup_logging is the Zenoh.jl name for init_log_from_env_or; try_init_logging_from_env corresponds to try_init_log_from_env. Severities are singleton structs under LogSeverities, matching the Quality of Service pattern.\n\nnote: Not core Zenoh\nLogging is absent from Zenoh's abstractions (Key, Key Expression, Selector, Value, Encoding, Timestamp, Subscriber, Publisher, Queryable, Storage, Admin space).\n\nwarning: Capture is a zenoh-c extension with no safe-Rust equivalent\nThe documented Rust API exposes only init_log_from_env_or and try_init_log_from_env (stderr via tracing). There is no safe-Rust counterpart to zc_init_log_with_callback; programmatic in-process log capture is a zenoh-c (zc_) extension. open_log_stream wraps that C-only capability.\n\nnote: Zenoh.jl extension: buffering, backpressure, and the pull API\nZenoh's callback is fire-and-forget from foreign threads. The fixed-capacity drop-oldest ring, the tryrecv! / take! / iteration / dropped_count / close surface, and the global one-shot mutual-exclusion guard are all Zenoh.jl machinery built on top of Zenoh's bare callback.\n\nSee also Sessions & Configuration for opening the session whose activity these logs report, and Quality of Service for the singleton-enum pattern the severities follow.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.LogSeverity","page":"Logging","text":"LogSeverity\n\nAbstract supertype of the five severity levels in LogSeverities (TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR). Accepted wherever a level is named: the filter argument to setup_logging, the min_severity floor of open_log_stream, and the severity field of a LogRecord.\n\nLevels are ordered TRACE < DEBUG < INFO < WARN < ERROR via isless/<=.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LogSeverity"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.LogSeverities","page":"Logging","text":"LogSeverities\n\nNamespace holding the five log-severity levels as singleton instances: LogSeverities.TRACE, DEBUG, INFO, WARN, and ERROR. Each is a distinct singleton type under the shared LogSeverity supertype and maps 1:1 to a ZC_LOG_SEVERITY_* value in the underlying C enum.\n\nThe levels order TRACE < DEBUG < INFO < WARN < ERROR (via isless/<=), matching the C enum's 0..4 ranking. Pass a level to setup_logging as the stderr fallback or to open_log_stream as the capture floor.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LogSeverities"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.LogRecord","page":"Logging","text":"LogRecord\n\nOne captured Zenoh log line: severity::LogSeverity and message::String.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LogRecord"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.LogStream","page":"Logging","text":"LogStream\n\nA bounded, pull-based view of Zenoh's log stream, returned by open_log_stream. Consume LogRecords with take! (blocking), tryrecv! (non-blocking), or by iterating; call close when done.\n\nRecords arrive from Zenoh's internal threads into a fixed-capacity ring; overflow drops the oldest (count via dropped_count). Because Zenoh's logger is global and one-shot, only one LogStream exists per process. close stops delivery and frees buffered records, but cannot uninstall the global logger.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LogStream"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.setup_logging","page":"Logging","text":"setup_logging(filter=\"info\")\n\nInitialize Zenoh's built-in logger writing to stderr, with filter as the fallback level/spec (overridden by the RUST_LOG/ZENOH_LOG env vars). filter may be a level string (\"info\", \"debug\", …) or a LogSeverity.\n\nGlobal and one-shot — mutually exclusive with open_log_stream.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.setup_logging"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.try_init_logging_from_env","page":"Logging","text":"try_init_logging_from_env()\n\nInitialize Zenoh's stderr logger from the RUST_LOG/ZENOH_LOG env vars only (no fallback); a no-op if they're unset. Global and one-shot.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.try_init_logging_from_env"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.open_log_stream","page":"Logging","text":"open_log_stream(; min_severity=LogSeverities.WARN, capacity=256) -> LogStream\n\nCapture Zenoh's logs (at min_severity and above) into a bounded LogStream. Opt-in: nothing is installed until this is called.\n\nmin_severity is enforced inside Zenoh — below-floor records never reach the callback. Keep it at WARN (the default) when forwarding logs back over Zenoh (e.g. to ROS): the data-plane DEBUG/TRACE logs a forwarding publish generates then never enter the stream, which is the primary defense against a log feedback loop (see docs/logging.md). Global and one-shot — mutually exclusive with setup_logging.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.open_log_stream"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.tryrecv!-Tuple{LogStream}","page":"Logging","text":"tryrecv!(s::LogStream) -> Union{LogRecord, Nothing}\n\nPop the next buffered LogRecord, or nothing if none is waiting. Never blocks.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.tryrecv!"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/logging/#Zenoh.dropped_count","page":"Logging","text":"dropped_count(s::LogStream) -> Int\n\nCumulative number of log records dropped because the ring was full.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.dropped_count"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Payloads-and-Serialization","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"A ZBytes is Zenoh's raw byte payload: the data half of every message that crosses the network. Zenoh's model calls the data-plus-format unit a Value — \"a user provided data item along with its encoding\" — and ZBytes carries the data, the raw payload bytes held with minimized copying. The matching Encoding is a separate object (see Encoding); you assemble a Value at the call site by passing both to put or reply, so the two halves stay independent.\n\nThis page covers two distinct layers:\n\nRaw payloads — ZBytes, its readers/writer, and ZSlice. These move bytes verbatim and conform to Julia's IO interface.\nThe structured codec — ZSerializer / ZDeserializer and the serialize / deserialize helpers. This is zenoh-ext's portable, framed, length-prefixed, defined-endian encoding that round-trips typed values across Zenoh's Rust, C++, Python, and Julia bindings.\n\nA raw ZBytes ships bytes you already have; the codec produces a ZBytes a peer in another language can decode field-by-field. Both travel as a ZBytes on the wire.","title":"Payloads & Serialization"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Sending-raw-bytes","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"put and reply accept anything ZBytes can wrap, so the common case needs no explicit construction:\n\nusing Zenoh\n\npub = Publisher(session, kexpr\"demo/raw\")\nput(pub, UInt8[1, 2, 3, 4])   # wrapped in a ZBytes for you\nput(pub, \"hello\")             # a String works the same way\n\nConstructing a ZBytes yourself matters when you care about ownership and copying. The byte- and string-buffer constructors default to zero-copy take-ownership: Zenoh borrows your buffer in place and frees it through a deleter once transmission completes. Zenoh.jl pins the Julia source for you until that deleter fires, so the buffer stays alive exactly as long as Zenoh needs it.\n\nbuf = rand(UInt8, 1 << 20)\nput(pub, ZBytes(buf))             # zero-copy: `buf` is pinned until zenoh releases it\nput(pub, ZBytes(buf; copy=true))  # immediate copy: `buf` is free to mutate afterward\n\nPass copy=true when the source is short-lived or about to be mutated; Zenoh copies immediately, so the source need not outlive the call. A Symbol becomes a static-lifetime string payload with no copy and no pinning, since interned symbol data is effectively static.","title":"Sending raw bytes"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Ownership-and-cleanup","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"Clean up an owned ZBytes on the caller's task — Zenoh.jl attaches no GC finalizer, because dropping a shared-memory-backed payload off-thread would corrupt Zenoh's SHM bookkeeping and can wedge delivery. Two leak-free exits cover every owned ZBytes you can hold:\n\nMove-on-send — passing it to put, reply, or get hands ownership to Zenoh, which frees it.\nExplicit close — close(z) drops it on your task when you build one but decide not to send it.\n\nz = ZBytes(UInt8[0xde, 0xad])\n# ... decide not to send it ...\nclose(z)   # reclaim on this task\n\nBuilding an owned ZBytes and dropping the reference without sending or closing it leaks the buffer. Inbound payloads are loaned (see below), so this concerns only payloads you construct. ZSlice differs here: it attaches a drop finalizer, because slices are not SHM-backed and carry no deadlock risk.","title":"Ownership and cleanup"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Reading-inbound-payloads","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"A payload that arrives in a subscriber or queryable callback is a loaned ZBytes borrowing the Sample's buffer (see payload). The ZBytes holds the Sample as its owner, so the borrowed buffer stays valid while the ZBytes is reachable. To keep data past the callback, materialize a copy:\n\nfunction on_sample(s)\n    data = Vector{UInt8}(payload(s))   # copy out into an owned Julia vector\n    text = String(payload(s))          # or decode the whole payload as a String\nend\n\nString(z) and Vector{UInt8}(z) each consolidate the entire payload — including a fragmented one stitched from several network buffers — into one independent Julia value.","title":"Reading inbound payloads"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Streaming-reads","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"For large payloads, read incrementally. open(z, Val(:read)) returns a ZBytesReader, a seekable IO cursor over the payload:\n\nr = open(payload(s), Val(:read))\nheader = read(r, UInt32)\nseek(r, 8)\nrest = readavailable(r)\n\nIt supports read, unsafe_read, readbytes!, seek, skip, position, bytesavailable, and eof.\n\nA second reader, open(z, Val(:readslice)), returns a ZBytesSliceReader that walks the payload's underlying slices and copies directly out of each one, avoiding the per-read crossing into the standard reader — worthwhile in tight read loops. It is a Julia-only performance variant.","title":"Streaming reads"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Iterating-slices","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"A ZBytes may be assembled from several network buffers. Iterating one walks those slices in place:\n\nfor slice in payload(s)\n    # `slice` is a view into one underlying slice\nend","title":"Iterating slices"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Building-payloads-incrementally","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZBytesWriter assembles a payload piece by piece through the IO interface, then finishes into a ZBytes. Prefer the do-block form: it finishes on success and cleans up the writer if the body throws, so the writer is always reclaimed:\n\nbytes = open(ZBytes, Val(:write)) do w\n    write(w, \"header:\")\n    write(w, UInt8[0xde, 0xad])\nend\nput(pub, bytes)   # `bytes` (owned) is moved into `put`; do not reuse it afterward\n\nappend!(w, z) splices an existing ZBytes onto the writer's tail by moving it (zero-copy when possible); the appended ZBytes is dead afterward. A ZBytes that has been moved — by append!, finish, or a send — must not be used again.\n\nThe bare ZBytesWriter constructor and close/finish are available when the do-block shape does not fit, cleaned up on the caller's task like ZBytes: finish consumes the writer to produce the payload, and close discards an unfinished one.","title":"Building payloads incrementally"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Slices","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"A ZSlice wraps Zenoh's owned or loaned contiguous byte slice. It appears as the element type when iterating a ZBytes, and the materialize paths build one internally; you seldom construct one yourself. The buffer constructor mirrors ZBytes: ZSlice(buf) defaults to zero-copy take-ownership and ZSlice(buf; copy=true) copies immediately. Unlike ZBytes, an owned ZSlice carries a drop finalizer.","title":"Slices"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Structured-serialization","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"The codec encodes typed values into a portable framed layout that any Zenoh binding can decode. Use it when the receiver is a different language or you want a self-describing field sequence rather than a raw byte blob. It lives in the external zenoh-ext layer, so the structured codec evolves independently of raw byte handling.\n\nThe one-shot helpers cover the common case. They are public but unexported, so qualify them as Zenoh.serialize / Zenoh.deserialize:\n\n# Serialize a Tuple and send it:\nid16 = ntuple(i -> UInt8(i), 16)          # NTuple{16,UInt8} -> fixed-width [u8; 16]\nput(pub, Zenoh.serialize((Int64(42), id16)))\n\n# Deserialize in a callback (copy out before the callback returns):\nfunction on_structured(s)\n    seq, id = Zenoh.deserialize(Tuple{Int64, NTuple{16,UInt8}}, s)\nend\n\nFor streaming reads, exhaustion checks, or interleaved field handling, drive the cursors directly. ZSerializer accumulates values and finishes into a payload; ZDeserializer reads them back in write order:\n\nbuf = open(ZSerializer) do ser\n    write(ser, Int64(7))\n    write(ser, UInt8[0xaa, 0xbb])   # length-prefixed Vector{UInt8}\nend\n\nd = ZDeserializer(buf)\nn  = read(d, Int64)\nbs = read(d, Vector{UInt8})\n@assert Zenoh.is_done(d)\n\nZSerializer and ZDeserializer encapsulate ZBytes: a deserializer is built from a Sample (or a ZBytes) and yields owned Julia values; a serializer's finish yields the payload you hand to put. Normal structured use never names ZBytes.\n\nwarning: Read before the callback returns\nA ZDeserializer reads in place against the borrowed payload buffer. Read or copy every value out before the originating Sample or callback returns — values left unread point at freed memory once the buffer is released.","title":"Structured serialization"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Supported-types-and-the-extension-point","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"The codec wraps these value types today:\n\nJulia type Wire shape\nInt64 defined-endian i64\nUInt8 u8\nVector{UInt8} length-prefixed Vec<u8>\nNTuple{N,UInt8} fixed-width [u8; N], no length prefix\nTuple concatenation of its element encodings\n\nVector{UInt8} carries a length prefix; NTuple{N,UInt8} is fixed-width. The two encode differently, so pick the one whose shape the peer expects.\n\nzenoh-ext additionally defines bool, the full integer and float width family, str/string, and sequence-length framing, available to bind but not yet wrapped. Adding one is a single write(::ZSerializer, ::T) method plus a matching read(::ZDeserializer, ::Type{T}); the Mapping section shows the underlying binding pattern.","title":"Supported types and the extension point"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#API","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Raw-payloads","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"","title":"Raw payloads"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Reusable-and-borrowed-payloads","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"The default ZBytes constructors allocate a fresh owned payload per call. For hot publish loops, two paths reuse one payload across sends and drop that per-send allocation:\n\nCopy path. reusable_copy_bytes allocates one owned box; re-arm it each send with copy_bytes!, which copies the bytes into zenoh's own storage. The source buffer is free to mutate the instant copy_bytes! returns. OwnedZBytes is the concrete type both return, for typing a held field.\nBorrow (zero-copy) path. lent_bytes hands zenoh your buffer in place with no copy, plus a deleter that fires once transmission completes. You own the buffer's lifetime: keep it alive and unmodified until the deleter fires. CompletionCell is a ready-made deleter that wakes the lending task when zenoh is done; completion_deleter and completion_ctx supply its on_release and ctx.","title":"Reusable and borrowed payloads"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Structured-codec","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"","title":"Structured codec"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nZBytes payload of a Value zenoh::bytes::ZBytes z_owned_bytes_t / z_loaned_bytes_t\nZBytesReader byte read cursor zenoh::bytes::ZBytesReader z_bytes_reader_t\nZBytesWriter + finish byte write cursor zenoh::bytes::ZBytesWriter z_owned_bytes_writer_t\nBase.iterate(::ZBytes) slice iterator zenoh::bytes::ZBytesSliceIterator z_bytes_slice_iterator_t\nZSlice Slice (internal) z_owned_slice_t / z_loaned_slice_t\nZSerializer / ZDeserializer / serialize / deserialize structured serialization (zenoh-ext) z_serialize / z_deserialize ze_serializer_* / ze_deserializer_*\nZenoh.is_done deserializer exhaustion — ze_deserializer_is_done\n\nZBytes is the Julia handle for the zenoh::bytes module's payload type. The default ZBytes(::Vector) / ZBytes(::String) constructors map to C's z_bytes_from_buf / z_bytes_from_str (take-ownership with a deleter callback); copy=true maps to z_bytes_copy_from_buf; ZBytes(::Symbol) maps to z_bytes_from_static_str. ZBytesReader and ZBytesWriter are the Julia IO-conforming mirrors of Rust's std::io::Read + std::io::Seek and std::io::Write cursors over a payload. The structured codec is the front-end to zenoh-ext: write/read bind one method per type onto ze_serializer_serialize_* / ze_deserializer_deserialize_*.\n\nThe codec's per-type wrapping is also its extension point. The bool, float, full int/uint width, and str/string functions are bound in gen/LibZenohC.jl; wrapping one adds a write method that loans the serializer into ze_serializer_serialize_* and a read method that calls ze_deserializer_deserialize_* into an output Ref, each through the internal loan/pointer/result helpers:\n\nfunction Base.write(s::ZSerializer, x::Float64)\n    Zenoh._handle_result(Zenoh.LibZenohC.ze_serializer_serialize_double(Zenoh._ser_loan(s), x))\n    return nothing\nend\nfunction Base.read(d::ZDeserializer, ::Type{Float64})\n    out = Ref{Float64}()\n    GC.@preserve d Zenoh._handle_result(\n        Zenoh.LibZenohC.ze_deserializer_deserialize_double(Zenoh._deser_ptr(d), out))\n    return out[]\nend\n\nThe equivalence is exact except where named below.\n\nnote: Value is a call-site pair\nZenoh's Value bundles a payload and an Encoding. Zenoh.jl has no Value type: the payload is a ZBytes, the encoding is a separate Encoding, and you pass them independently to put or reply. A Value exists only as the pair of arguments at the call site.\n\nnote: Ownership is a type parameter\nRust and C present an owned ZBytes (z_owned_bytes_t) and a separate loaned reference (z_loaned_bytes_t). Zenoh.jl folds both into one parametric ZBytes whose R type parameter selects the owned or loaned C form, so ownership state is a Julia type parameter rather than a distinct type. ZSlice does the same for slices.\n\nwarning: Structured codec is zenoh-ext, not core\nZSerializer / ZDeserializer and the serialize / deserialize helpers wrap the external zenoh-ext crate (the ze_ C prefix), not core Zenoh. They are layered above ZBytes: a one-shot Zenoh.serialize(x) runs through a ZSerializer open/finish cycle (it does not bind C's one-shot ze_serialize_*).\n\nFurther divergences:\n\nNo GC finalizer on owned ZBytes. Cleanup runs on the caller's task by move-on-send or explicit close — because z_bytes_drop invokes the buffer deleter, and dropping an SHM-backed payload off the GC thread corrupts SHM bookkeeping. ZSlice does finalize, since slices are not SHM-backed.\nZBytesSliceReader has no Rust or C counterpart. It is a Julia-only IO reader (open(z, Val(:readslice))) that copies directly out of each slice's data pointer, distinct from the standard ZBytesReader (open(z, Val(:read))) that calls z_bytes_reader_read per read.\nNo OptionZBytes. Rust's OptionZBytes ergonomic optional-payload wrapper has no Julia equivalent; Julia uses a ZBytes, or nothing where an optional payload is needed.\nThe codec handles are not <: IO. ZSerializer / ZDeserializer sit off the IO hierarchy so read/write always run the framed-codec methods. Were they <: IO, Julia's generic write(io, x) = unsafe_write(io, Ref(x), sizeof(x)) fallback would emit raw isbits bytes. Contrast ZBytesWriter / ZBytesReader, which are <: IO and move raw bytes.\nCodec value-type subset. Only Int64, UInt8, Vector{UInt8}, NTuple{N,UInt8}, and Tuple are wrapped. C/zenoh-ext additionally offer bool, floats, the full int/uint width family, str/string, and sequence-length framing — bound but not yet wrapped (see the extension point above).\nserialize, deserialize, and is_done are public but unexported. Reach them as Zenoh.serialize / Zenoh.deserialize / Zenoh.is_done. Only ZSerializer and ZDeserializer are exported from the codec.\nfinish is one name, two methods. finish(::ZBytesWriter) extracts a payload from the byte writer; finish(::ZSerializer) extracts one from the structured serializer. Both consume (move) their handle.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZBytes","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZBytes\n\nZenoh's raw byte payload, with minimized copying. The R type parameter selects the underlying C handle: an owned z_owned_bytes_t for payloads you build to send, or a borrowed z_loaned_bytes_t for inbound payloads that borrow a Sample's buffer. A single payload may stitch together multiple network fragments, so iterating a ZBytes walks its byte slices (see iterate); materialize the whole thing with String(z) or Vector{UInt8}(z).\n\nConstructors:\n\nZBytes() — empty owned payload.\nZBytes(v::Vector{T}; copy=false), ZBytes(m::Memory{T}), ZBytes(r::Ref{T}) — by default zero-copy: the source is pinned and handed to libzenoh with a deleter, so it is freed only once the C side is done. Pass copy=true for libzenoh to take its own copy immediately, releasing the source.\nZBytes(s::String; copy=false) — same zero-copy/copy choice for a string.\nZBytes(s::Symbol) — a static-lifetime string payload, no pinning.\n\nOwned ZBytes deliberately carry no GC finalizer: reclaim one by moving it into put/reply/get, which hands ownership to zenoh, or by closeing it on your own task. A moved ZBytes is consumed and must not be reused. This keeps cleanup on the caller's task, never a finalizer thread, which avoids an SHM bookkeeping deadlock.\n\nSee also ZBytesWriter for incremental construction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZBytes"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZBytesReader","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZBytesReader\n\nAn IO-conforming, seekable reader over a ZBytes payload. Obtain one with open(z, Val(:read)); it borrows the payload's buffer (so the source ZBytes must outlive it) and reads the bytes back via the usual IO interface — read, readbytes!, unsafe_read, readavailable, plus seek/skip/position, bytesavailable, and eof. Borrowing nothing of its own, close is a no-op.\n\nFor walking the payload one network fragment at a time without copying, see ZBytesSliceReader.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZBytesReader"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZBytesSliceReader","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZBytesSliceReader\n\nAn IO-conforming reader that streams a ZBytes payload across its underlying network fragments, copying out of one borrowed slice at a time rather than materializing the whole payload. Obtain one with open(z, Val(:readslice)); it borrows the payload's buffer (so the source ZBytes must outlive it). Reads — read, readbytes!, unsafe_read — transparently advance to the next slice when the current one is exhausted; skip, position, bytesavailable, and eof track progress over the whole payload. Borrowing nothing of its own, close is a no-op.\n\nFor a seekable reader over the payload as a single stream, see ZBytesReader.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZBytesSliceReader"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZBytesWriter","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZBytesWriter()\n\nAn IO-conforming, incremental builder for a ZBytes payload. write(w, x) appends a value's raw bytes and append!(w, z) splices an existing ZBytes onto the tail (moving it, zero-copy when possible). finish(w) consumes the writer and returns the assembled payload.\n\nThe writer owns a C resource and carries no GC finalizer, so reclaim it explicitly on your own task: finish consumes it, or close drops an unfinished one. The do-block form open(ZBytes, Val(:write)) do w … end guarantees one of these always fires and returns the finished payload:\n\nbytes = open(ZBytes, Val(:write)) do w\n    write(w, \"header\")\n    write(w, payload)\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZBytesWriter"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZSlice","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZSlice{S}\n\nA contiguous byte slice, Zenoh's z_owned_slice_t / z_loaned_slice_t. The S type parameter selects the ownership state: an owned slice (Ref{z_owned_slice_t}) or a borrowed one (Ptr{z_loaned_slice_t}).\n\nConstruct one of three ways:\n\nZSlice() — an empty owned slice.\nZSlice(buf::Vector{UInt8}; copy=false) — wraps a Julia byte vector. The default takes ownership zero-copy: buf is pinned and freed only once libzenoh releases it, so it must stay reachable. Pass copy=true to have libzenoh take its own copy immediately, freeing buf from that obligation.\nZSlice(ref::Ptr{z_loaned_slice_t}) — a loaned slice borrowing C-owned memory.\n\nOwned slices carry a GC drop finalizer; loaned slices own nothing and need no cleanup. length and isempty report the slice's byte count.\n\nUnlike an owned ZBytes, which deliberately omits a finalizer, owned slices finalize on the GC because they are never SHM-backed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZSlice"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.finish","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"finish(w::ZBytesWriter) -> ZBytes\n\nConsume the writer and return the assembled owned ZBytes payload. This moves the writer's C resource out, so the writer is spent afterward and any further write/append!/finish errors.\n\nfinish is also defined for ZSerializer, where it closes out the structured codec into a payload.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.finish"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.reusable_copy_bytes","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"reusable_copy_bytes() -> OwnedZBytes\n\nA held, re-armable owned ZBytes for the copy publish path: the copy=true analogue of a pooled buffer. Allocates the Ref{z_owned_bytes_t} box + wrapper once; hold it for the publisher's lifetime and re-arm it every send with copy_bytes! — zero per-send ZBytes allocation, and none of the deleter / preserve_handle / foreign-thread machinery lent_bytes needs (zenoh takes its own synchronous copy, so the source buffer is free the instant copy_bytes! returns).\n\nThe box is seeded in the gravestone (null) state, so the first copy_bytes!'s drop-first is a safe no-op. Like every owned ZBytes it carries no GC finalizer — reclaim it with close (gravestone-idempotent) on the holder's teardown; do not just drop the reference.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.reusable_copy_bytes"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.copy_bytes!","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"copy_bytes!(zb::OwnedZBytes, buf::DenseVector{UInt8}, len::Integer) -> zb\n\nRe-arm a held reusable_copy_bytes box in place from buf[1:len], copying into zenoh's own storage. Drop-first, then copy: z_bytes_drop frees any prior owned copy and resets the box to gravestone (no-op if already gravestone/moved-from); z_bytes_copy_from_buf then constructs into that slot — it does not free prior content, so the leading drop is the leak guard, not an optimization. The two C calls take different pointer types (z_moved_bytes_t* from _move vs the bare z_owned_bytes_t*), which is why this lives in Zenoh.jl.\n\nMutates zb.b[] in place and returns the same zb (re-armed) — never reassign the held field. Single-writer: the drop+copy is two non-atomic C calls on shared state, so the caller must serialize copy_bytes!/put on a given box (e.g. under the publisher's buffer lock); it is not internally thread-safe. put/_make_put_opts consume (_move) the box every send → gravestoned → the next copy_bytes!'s drop-first is a safe no-op.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.copy_bytes!"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.OwnedZBytes","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"OwnedZBytes\n\nConcrete alias for an owned ZBytes (ZBytes{Ref{z_owned_bytes_t}}) — the type reusable_copy_bytes returns, so callers can type a held field concretely.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.OwnedZBytes"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.lent_bytes","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"lent_bytes(buf::DenseVector{UInt8}, len::Integer, on_release::Ptr{Cvoid}, ctx::Ptr{Cvoid}) -> ZBytes\n\nA zero-copy owned ZBytes that BORROWS buf[1:len] and hands libzenoh a caller-supplied deleter on_release, invoked once when zenoh is done with the buffer (post-transmission). Unlike ZBytes(buf; copy=false), this does not Base.preserve_handle the buffer — the caller owns the lifetime: buf (and whatever ctx points at) MUST stay alive and unmodified until on_release fires. Lend a buffer to a fire-and-forget put and reclaim it on that signal (see CompletionCell).\n\non_release must be a two-arg C deleter (data::Ptr{Cvoid}, ctx::Ptr{Cvoid}) — the z_bytes_from_buf ABI, NOT the one-arg closure-drop ABI — pre-built with @cfunction (so it is a constant pointer, not allocated per call). libzenoh calls it on one of its own runtime threads, so the deleter must follow the foreign-thread discipline (ccalls / pointer arithmetic only); see CompletionCell for a ready-made one.\n\nFiring contract:\n\nOn SUCCESS, ownership passes to the returned ZBytes; the deleter fires exactly once when that ZBytes is dropped. After _moveing it into a put, that drop happens inside zenoh once transmission finishes — the deleter, not the put return, is the completion signal.\nOn FAILURE (z_bytes_from_buf ≠ Z_OK, thrown here as a ZenohError), the deleter NEVER fires and nothing is returned, so the caller still owns buf and must reclaim it.\n\nDo NOT close/drop the returned ZBytes after _moveing it into a put — the move consumed it and a second drop would double-fire the deleter. If you build one and don't send, close(zb) drops it once (firing the deleter once) on the caller's task.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.lent_bytes"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.CompletionCell","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"CompletionCell()\n\nA reusable completion signal that tells the lending task when zenoh has released a lent_bytes buffer (transmission complete). Supply completion_deleter and completion_ctx as that buffer's on_release and ctx, and the lend's deleter targets this cell.\n\nEach send follows three steps:\n\narm! the cell, then build the lend and send it.\nwait(cell) blocks until zenoh's deleter fires on one of its runtime threads.\nReclaim or reuse the buffer — the wake carries the happens-before, so the bytes are safe to touch.\n\nisdone(cell) polls the same state without blocking. Keep the cell GC-rooted until its deleter has fired: its raw pointer lives inside zenoh, and a collected cell makes that pointer dangle. close the cell once no deleter can still fire for it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.CompletionCell"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.completion_deleter","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"completion_deleter() -> Ptr{Cvoid}\n\nThe @cfunction deleter pointer for CompletionCell, to pass as lent_bytes' on_release. Pair with completion_ctx.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.completion_deleter"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.completion_ctx","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"completion_ctx(c::CompletionCell) -> Ptr{Cvoid}\n\nThe raw ctx pointer for c, to pass as lent_bytes' ctx. The caller MUST keep c GC-rooted until the deleter fires — the pointer dangles otherwise.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.completion_ctx"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZSerializer","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZSerializer()\n\nA cursor that accumulates typed values in zenoh's structured format. Append with write(s, x), then finish(s) to produce the payload (consumes the serializer), or close(s) to discard an unfinished one. Prefer the do-block open(ZSerializer) do s … end, which finishes on success and closes on error, or the one-shot serialize.\n\nCarries no finalizer — same rationale as ZBytesWriter; clean up with finish or close on the caller's task.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZSerializer"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.ZDeserializer","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"ZDeserializer(sample::Sample)\nZDeserializer(z::ZBytes)\n\nA cursor over a received payload. Read values back in the order they were written with read(d, T); is_done(d) reports whether the payload is exhausted. Prefer the one-shot deserialize.\n\nze_deserializer_t is a by-value cursor that borrows from the payload buffer, so the handle pins its source (src) for its whole life — read or copy out before the originating sample/callback returns.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZDeserializer"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.serialize","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"serialize(x) -> payload\n\nSerialize x into a payload ready for put/reply (serialize owns the intermediate buffer — you do not handle it directly). x may be a single supported value or a Tuple of them.\n\nput(pub, Zenoh.serialize((Int64(42), id16)))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.serialize"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.deserialize","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"deserialize(T, src) -> T::T\n\nRead a T back from a received payload src (a Sample or ZBytes), returning owned Julia values. T may be a single supported type or a Tuple type for a composite payload.\n\n(seq, id) = Zenoh.deserialize(Tuple{Int64,Vector{UInt8}}, sample)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.deserialize"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/payloads-and-serialization/#Zenoh.is_done","page":"Payloads & Serialization","text":"is_done(d::ZDeserializer) -> Bool\n\ntrue once every value has been read off the cursor.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.is_done"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Advanced-Pub/Sub","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"Advanced Pub/Sub layers reliability onto plain Publish & Subscribe. A publisher caches recent samples and stamps each with a per-source sequence number. A subscriber replays that cache on join, recovers gaps by querying for retransmission, and reports any gap it cannot recover. These features build on the core Publisher (\"an entity declaring that it will be updating the key/value with keys matching a given key expression\") and Subscriber (\"an entity registering interest for any change ... to a value associated with a key matching the specified key expression\") abstractions.\n\nIt is an unstable extension whose availability varies across Zenoh implementations. Zenoh.jl exposes it through the concrete AdvancedPublisher and AdvancedSubscriber types. Both kinds share AbstractPublisher / AbstractCallbackSubscriber / AbstractSubscriberHandler with the plain types. put, delete!, close, iteration, MatchingListener, and matching_status therefore work uniformly across both.\n\nnote: Timestamping is required\nCache and miss detection stamp every sample, so the session must have timestamping enabled. Open it with Zenoh.open(Zenoh.Config(; str=\"{timestamping:{enabled:true}}\")) (or deploy behind a router that timestamps). Without it, declaring an advanced publisher with cache or miss_detection raises an error.","title":"Advanced Pub/Sub"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Declaring-advanced-endpoints","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"Two paths construct an advanced endpoint, and both return a type-stable concrete value:\n\nRouting. Publisher and open return an advanced type when any advanced keyword is present. Each advanced keyword carries its own options value, and presence of the keyword is the opt-in. Shared QoS keywords (priority, reliability, ...) never route.\nDirect construction. AdvancedPublisher and AdvancedSubscriber always return the concrete advanced type, regardless of which keywords you pass.\n\nThe publisher keywords are cache, miss_detection, and detection; the subscriber keywords are history, recovery, query_timeout_ms, and detection.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\n# Cache and miss detection stamp samples, so timestamping must be enabled.\ns = Zenoh.open(Zenoh.Config(; str = \"{timestamping:{enabled:true}}\"))\nkey = Zenoh.Keyexpr(\"demo/advanced\")\n\n# Routes to an AdvancedPublisher because `cache` is present.\nap = Zenoh.Publisher(s, key;\n        cache = CacheOptions(max_samples = 64),\n        miss_detection = MissDetectionOptions(heartbeat = :periodic, period_ms = 100),\n        priority = Zenoh.Priorities.REAL_TIME)\n@assert isadvanced(ap)\n\nZenoh.put(ap, \"hello\")","title":"Declaring advanced endpoints"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Holding-an-advanced-endpoint-in-a-struct","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"Routing means Publisher(s, k; cache=...) returns an AdvancedPublisher, not a Publisher. Type such a field by the shared supertype, because a field typed as the concrete Publisher rejects an AdvancedPublisher with a MethodError on convert:\n\nstruct Sensor{P<:Zenoh.AbstractPublisher}\n    pub::P\nend\n\nUse isadvanced when generic code must branch on which kind a routing constructor returned.","title":"Holding an advanced endpoint in a struct"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Publisher-cache-and-miss-detection","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"The publisher side carries two reliability features, each configured by an options struct:\n\nCacheOptions retains the last max_samples samples and serves them to late-joining or recovering subscribers. cache = 64 is shorthand for cache = CacheOptions(max_samples = 64).\nMissDetectionOptions stamps samples with per-source sequence numbers so subscribers can detect gaps, and selects a heartbeat that advertises the latest sequence number. heartbeat is :none, :periodic, or :sporadic; period_ms tunes the periodic heartbeat. miss_detection = :periodic is shorthand for miss_detection = MissDetectionOptions(heartbeat = :periodic).\n\n# Cache 64 samples; emit a periodic heartbeat every 100 ms.\nap = Zenoh.AdvancedPublisher(s, key;\n        cache = 64,\n        miss_detection = MissDetectionOptions(heartbeat = :periodic, period_ms = 100))\n\nAn advanced publisher publishes and tombstones exactly like a plain one:\n\nZenoh.put(ap, \"value\")\nZenoh.delete!(ap)            # DELETE-kind sample on the keyexpr\n\nIt also supports matching introspection — matching_status polls once for a matching subscriber, and MatchingListener notifies on each transition (see Matching).","title":"Publisher cache and miss detection"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Subscriber-history-and-recovery","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"The subscriber side mirrors the publisher's two features:\n\nHistoryOptions queries matching advanced publishers on declaration and replays their cached samples. max_samples and max_age_ms bound the replay window (0 means unbounded); detect_late_publishers also back-fills from publishers that appear after the subscriber.\nRecoveryOptions recovers gaps in one of two modes. The default RecoveryOptions() recovers from the publisher heartbeat and sequence numbers alone; a positive periodic_queries_period_ms additionally polls for missed last samples at that interval. Both modes need a publisher with miss_detection; query-based recovery also needs the publisher's cache.\n\nThe query_timeout_ms keyword bounds the per-query timeout (milliseconds) for history replay and query-based recovery.\n\n# Late-joining subscriber: replay up to 64 cached samples, then recover gaps.\nasub = Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriber(s, key;\n        history  = HistoryOptions(max_samples = 64, detect_late_publishers = true),\n        recovery = RecoveryOptions(periodic_queries_period_ms = 1000)) do sample\n    @info \"got\" payload = String(Zenoh.payload(sample))\nend\n\nThe callback form runs f(::Sample) on a dedicated task with a latest-wins single slot, exactly like the plain Subscriber. The no-callback form returns a buffered AdvancedSubscriberHandler that you iterate or poll with take! / tryrecv!:\n\nh = Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriber(s, key; channel = :fifo, capacity = 16,\n                             history = HistoryOptions())\nsample = Zenoh.tryrecv!(h)   # nothing if the buffer is empty\n\nchannel selects the same History policy as a plain SubscriberHandler: :fifo / :ring is a drop-oldest bounded ring, and :keep_all is a heap-backed unbounded buffer.","title":"Subscriber history and recovery"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Reacting-to-unrecoverable-gaps","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"When a gap cannot be recovered, an AdvancedSubscriber surfaces it as a SampleMiss: source is the publishing endpoint's entity id and count is the number of missed samples. SampleMissListener runs f(::SampleMiss) on a dedicated task for each one; close undeclares it.\n\nml = Zenoh.SampleMissListener(asub) do miss::SampleMiss\n    @warn \"missed samples\" source = miss.source count = miss.count\nend\n\n# ...\n\nclose(ml)\n\nSampleMissListener is declared on the concrete AdvancedSubscriber type, which alone carries miss detection.","title":"Reacting to unrecoverable gaps"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Liveliness-based-endpoint-detection","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"Pass detection = DetectionOptions() on either side to advertise the endpoint for liveliness-based discovery. On the publisher it lets matching subscribers discover it; on the subscriber it lets HistoryOptions(detect_late_publishers = true) find publishers that join later. Back-filling from late publishers therefore requires the publisher to enable both detection and cache.\n\nap = Zenoh.AdvancedPublisher(s, key;\n        cache = 64, detection = DetectionOptions())\nasub = Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriber(s, key;\n        detection = DetectionOptions(),\n        history = HistoryOptions(detect_late_publishers = true)) do sample\n    # ...\nend","title":"Liveliness-based endpoint detection"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#API","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust (zenoh-ext) zenoh-c (ze_)\nAdvancedPublisher Publisher extension AdvancedPublisher / AdvancedPublisherBuilder ze_declare_advanced_publisher\nAdvancedSubscriber / AdvancedSubscriberHandler Subscriber extension AdvancedSubscriber / AdvancedSubscriberBuilder ze_declare_advanced_subscriber\nCacheOptions publisher cache CacheConfig ze_advanced_publisher_cache_options_t\nMissDetectionOptions sample-miss detection MissDetectionConfig ze_advanced_publisher_sample_miss_detection_options_t\nHistoryOptions history replay HistoryConfig ze_advanced_subscriber_history_options_t\nRecoveryOptions gap recovery RecoveryConfig ze_advanced_subscriber_recovery_options_t\nDetectionOptions liveliness detection publisher_detection() / subscriber_detection() publisher_detection / subscriber_detection field\nSampleMiss missed-sample record Miss ze_miss_t\nSampleMissListener miss listener SampleMissListener ze_advanced_subscriber_declare_sample_miss_listener + ze_closure_miss\nput / delete! publish / tombstone AdvancedPublisher::put / ::delete ze_advanced_publisher_put / ze_advanced_publisher_delete\nMatchingListener / matching_status matching status matching status (shared) ze_advanced_publisher_declare_matching_listener / ze_advanced_publisher_get_matching_status\nisadvanced — — —\n\nThe option structs map onto the C nested option structs field-for-field: CacheOptions onto ze_advanced_publisher_cache_options_t, MissDetectionOptions onto ze_advanced_publisher_sample_miss_detection_options_t, HistoryOptions onto ze_advanced_subscriber_history_options_t, and RecoveryOptions onto ze_advanced_subscriber_recovery_options_t. Presence of the corresponding keyword forces the struct's is_enabled flag true. The prefixes follow the zenoh-c naming convention: z_ is the core Zenoh API, zc_ is zenoh-c-specific, and ze_ is API outside the core with no cross-implementation guarantee — Advanced Pub/Sub is entirely ze_. The advanced data path reuses the core z_closure_sample callback; only miss notifications use a dedicated ze_closure_miss.\n\nwarning: Not a core Zenoh abstraction\nAdvanced Pub/Sub is absent from the Zenoh abstractions page. It is an unstable zenoh-ext / ze_ extension layered on the Publisher and Subscriber abstractions, with no guarantee that it is available across Zenoh implementations.\n\nSeveral Zenoh.jl shapes diverge from the Rust API and must be stated precisely:\n\nRouting has no Rust or C analogue. Folding advanced and plain endpoints under shared abstract types and routing Publisher(s, k; ...) / open(s, k; ...) to an advanced type by keyword presence is a Zenoh.jl feature. Rust uses distinct builder types (AdvancedPublisherBuilder), and C uses separate ze_declare_* entrypoints; neither routes on values.\ndetection is a presence marker. Opting in passes detection = DetectionOptions(), the analogue of Rust's publisher_detection() / subscriber_detection() builder calls; there is no detection = true/false form. The detection-metadata keyexpr (publisher_detection_metadata in Rust/C) is not yet exposed.\nMissDetectionOptions collapses two Rust methods. Rust's MissDetectionConfig has separate heartbeat(Duration) and sporadic_heartbeat(Duration) methods; Zenoh.jl uses a single heartbeat::Symbol (:none / :periodic / :sporadic) plus period_ms, mirroring the C ze_advanced_publisher_heartbeat_mode_t enum.\nCacheOptions flattens reply QoS. Rust's CacheConfig configures reply QoS through a nested replies_config(RepliesConfig); CacheOptions exposes congestion_control / priority / express as flat fields, matching the flat C ze_advanced_publisher_cache_options_t.\nRecoveryOptions is narrower than Rust. Rust's RecoveryConfig has distinct heartbeat() and periodic_queries(Duration) modes. Zenoh.jl exposes only periodic_queries_period_ms: a positive value enables periodic queries, and 0 (the default) recovers from the heartbeat and sequence numbers alone — the C analogue of Rust's RecoveryConfig::heartbeat().\nTime units are milliseconds. max_age_ms, period_ms, and periodic_queries_period_ms are UInt64 milliseconds, matching the C *_ms fields. Rust's HistoryConfig::max_age takes f64 seconds and its heartbeat/query methods take a Duration, so a ported Rust example must convert.\n\nnote: Zenoh.jl extension\nisadvanced is a Julia-only trait with no Zenoh, Rust, or C counterpart. Rust and C yield a distinct advanced type by construction.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.AdvancedPublisher","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"AdvancedPublisher(s::Session, k::Keyexpr; cache, miss_detection, detection,\n                  encoding, congestion_control, priority, express,\n                  reliability, allowed_destination)\n\nDeclare an advanced publisher on k. Always returns an AdvancedPublisher (the routing Publisher(s, k; …) returns one transparently when an advanced keyword is set). Supports put, delete!, MatchingListener, matching_status, and close.\n\nnote: Note\ncache and miss_detection stamp samples, so the session must have timestamping enabled (Config(; str=\"{timestamping:{enabled:true}}\"), or a routed/timestamping deployment) — otherwise the declare fails with Z_EGENERIC.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AdvancedPublisher"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriber","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"AdvancedSubscriber(f, s::Session, k::Keyexpr; should_close_on_error=true,\n                   allowed_origin, history, recovery, query_timeout_ms, detection)\n\nCallback-form advanced subscriber. f(::Sample) runs on a dedicated Julia task (latest-wins single slot, like Subscriber), plus history/recovery per the advanced options. open(f, s, k; history=…) routes here transparently.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriber"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriberHandler","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"AdvancedSubscriberHandler\n\nBuffered advanced subscriber returned by AdvancedSubscriber(s, k; channel=…) (or open(s, k; history=…)). Iterate / take! / tryrecv! to consume Samples. See SubscriberHandler.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AdvancedSubscriberHandler"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.CacheOptions","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"CacheOptions(; max_samples=1, congestion_control=nothing, priority=nothing, express=nothing)\n\nPublisher-side sample cache: retains the last max_samples samples and serves them to late/recovering advanced subscribers. CacheOptions(n) is shorthand for CacheOptions(max_samples=n).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.CacheOptions"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.MissDetectionOptions","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"MissDetectionOptions(; heartbeat=:none, period_ms=0)\n\nPublisher-side sample-miss detection: stamps samples with per-source sequence numbers so subscribers can detect gaps. heartbeat is :none, :periodic, or :sporadic; period_ms tunes the periodic heartbeat. MissDetectionOptions(sym) is shorthand for MissDetectionOptions(heartbeat=sym).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.MissDetectionOptions"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.HistoryOptions","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"HistoryOptions(; detect_late_publishers=false, max_samples=0, max_age_ms=0)\n\nSubscriber-side history replay: on declaration, query matching advanced publishers and replay their cached samples. max_samples/max_age_ms of 0 mean unbounded. detect_late_publishers also back-fills from publishers that appear after the subscriber.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.HistoryOptions"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.RecoveryOptions","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"RecoveryOptions(; periodic_queries_period_ms=0)\n\nSubscriber-side gap recovery. A positive periodic_queries_period_ms polls for missed last samples at that interval. The default 0 recovers gaps from the publisher heartbeat and sequence numbers alone.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.RecoveryOptions"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.DetectionOptions","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"DetectionOptions()\n\nEnable liveliness-based detection of this endpoint (publisher or subscriber). The detection-metadata keyexpr is not yet exposed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.DetectionOptions"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.SampleMiss","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"SampleMiss\n\nA detected gap in an advanced publisher's stream, delivered to a SampleMissListener: source is the publisher's entity id and count is the number of missed samples.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SampleMiss"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.SampleMissListener","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"SampleMissListener(f, sub::AdvancedSubscriber; should_close_on_error=true)\n\nDeclare a sample-miss listener on advanced subscriber sub. f(::SampleMiss) runs on a dedicated Julia task each time an unrecoverable gap is detected. Call close(ml) to undeclare.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SampleMissListener"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.isadvanced","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"isadvanced(x) -> Bool\n\ntrue for the advanced publisher/subscriber variants, false for the plain ones. Lets generic code branch on the kind a routing constructor returned without isa.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.isadvanced"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.put-Tuple{AdvancedPublisher, Any}","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"put(ap::AdvancedPublisher, payload; shm=nothing, timestamp, encoding, attachment)\n\nPublish payload through advanced publisher ap via ze_advanced_publisher_put, caching it and stamping the configured per-source sequence number. The declare-time QoS applies, so the per-call options match the plain put(::Publisher, …) form (timestamp, encoding, attachment, and an SHM provider as shm).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.put"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.MatchingListener-Tuple{Function, AdvancedPublisher}","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"MatchingListener(f, ap::AdvancedPublisher; should_close_on_error=true)\n\nDeclare a matching listener on advanced publisher ap. Same semantics as the plain Publisher form.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.MatchingListener"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/advanced-pubsub/#Zenoh.matching_status-Tuple{AdvancedPublisher}","page":"Advanced Pub/Sub","text":"matching_status(ap::AdvancedPublisher) -> Bool\n\nOne-shot poll of ap's current matching status (true iff at least one matching subscriber exists). For change notifications use MatchingListener.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.matching_status"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Getting-Started","page":"Getting Started","text":"Zenoh is a distributed key/value data space supporting pub/sub, distributed queries, and storage, where / is the hierarchical key separator. Zenoh.jl wraps the C library (libzenohc, the zenoh-c bindings) so a Julia program joins that data space as a full peer: publish values, subscribe to changes, serve and issue queries.\n\nThis page walks the end-to-end flow with verified, runnable examples: build a Config and open a Session, publish with put, subscribe with both the callback and channel forms, query with get, then shut down with close. Each section links to the manual page that covers it in depth.\n\nThe examples need a live Zenoh network (a peer or a router) to exchange data, so they are shown as plain code rather than executed doctests. Start a router with zenohd from a Zenoh release, or run two Julia sessions in peer mode against each other.","title":"Getting Started"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#The-wrapper-model-in-one-paragraph","page":"Getting Started","text":"Every Zenoh entity Julia holds — a session, a publisher, a subscriber — is a resource with two release paths: an explicit close that releases it deterministically on your task, and a GC finalizer that releases it for you if you forget. close is idempotent, so calling it twice is harmless. Operations run immediately, returning their result or throwing a ZenohError. See the Zenoh.jl home page for the full ownership story.","title":"The wrapper model in one paragraph"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Connect:-build-a-config,-open-a-session","page":"Getting Started","text":"A Session holds the runtime that connects your node to the Zenoh network. Open one from a Config. With no arguments the config uses Zenoh's built-in defaults (peer mode, multicast scouting on):\n\nusing Zenoh\n\ns = open(Config())   # defaults: peer mode, multicast discovery\n\nConfig(; ...) builds from at most one source — the built-in defaults, the ZENOH_CONFIG environment variable (from_env=true), a file (file=\"...\"), or a JSON5 string (str=\"...\"):\n\ncfg = Config(; str = \"\"\"{ mode: \"peer\" }\"\"\")\ncfg[\"connect/endpoints\"] = [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"]   # JSON5-serialized insert\ns = open(cfg)\n\nopen copies the config, so one Config opens many sessions. Indexing reads and writes raw dotted keys. Assigning a String inserts it verbatim as pre-formatted JSON5; assigning any other Julia value serializes it to JSON5 first. The typed ZenohConfig builder is the idiomatic way to assemble a configuration — the Sessions & Configuration page covers both layers and the indexing trap in full.\n\nInspect a live session through these free functions — zid, router_zids, and peer_zids:\n\nzid(s)          # this session's 16-byte Zenoh ID\nto_le_bytes(zid(s))  # that ID as its raw little-endian NTuple{16,UInt8}\nrouter_zids(s)  # IDs of connected routers\npeer_zids(s)    # IDs of connected peers\nisopen(s)       # true until close\n\nto_le_bytes returns the ID in the byte order Zenoh hashes and serializes, which is the reverse of the printed/shown string.","title":"Connect: build a config, open a session"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Publish:-put-a-value","page":"Getting Started","text":"put associates a payload with a key expression. The one-shot session form needs no declared publisher and carries per-call QoS:\n\nput(s, kexpr\"demo/example/temp\", \"21.5\"; encoding = \"text/plain\")\n\nkexpr\"...\" builds a Keyexpr at parse time; Keyexpr(\"demo/...\") is the plain constructor. For repeated publication on one key, declare a long-lived Publisher: its QoS is fixed at declare time, so put(p, payload; ...) takes only per-call timestamp/encoding/attachment.\n\npub = Publisher(s, kexpr\"demo/example/temp\")\nput(pub, \"22.0\"; encoding = \"text/plain\")\nclose(pub)   # undeclare; idempotent\n\nPublish & Subscribe covers QoS keywords, the QoS singletons, and delete! (publishing a tombstone sample).","title":"Publish: put a value"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Subscribe:-callback-form","page":"Getting Started","text":"A subscriber registers interest in every change to keys matching a key expression and receives a Sample per put/delete. The callback form runs your function on a dedicated task for each sample:\n\nsub = open(s, kexpr\"demo/example/**\") do smpl::Sample\n    println(keyexpr(smpl), \" => \", String(payload(smpl)))\nend\n\n# ... later, when done:\nclose(sub)   # REQUIRED — a callback subscriber has no GC finalizer\n\nA slow callback sees only the most recent message: the handoff is a single latest-wins cell, so a sample arriving before the previous one is consumed overwrites it. A callback subscriber must be closed explicitly — it has no GC finalizer and leaks until close(sub).","title":"Subscribe: callback form"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Subscribe:-channel-form","page":"Getting Started","text":"The channel form returns a buffered handler you iterate or poll for samples:\n\nbuf = open(s, kexpr\"demo/example/**\"; channel = :ring, capacity = 64)\nfor smpl in buf\n    @show keyexpr(smpl) payload(smpl)\nend\nclose(buf)\n\nwarning: `:fifo` is drop-oldest, not lossless\nchannel = :fifo (the default), :ring, and the unnamed default all resolve to the same bounded keep-last-capacity ring: on overflow the oldest buffered sample is dropped. The producer never blocks. For lossless delivery bounded only by memory, use channel = :keep_all. See Publish & Subscribe for the full delivery-policy table and dropped_count.\n\nIterating a :fifo/:ring handler reuses one buffer per step for zero per-sample allocation, so a yielded Sample is valid only until the next iteration — do not stash or collect it. To hold a sample past the loop step, choose one:\n\ntake! returns an owned sample.\nrecv!(sub, ::SampleHolder) fills a caller-owned holder for a zero-allocation loop (see the recv! docstring for the SampleHolder pattern).\nchannel = :keep_all yields owned samples throughout.","title":"Subscribe: channel form"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Query:-get-replies-from-queryables","page":"Getting Started","text":"get issues a query on a key expression and returns a GetHandler over the Reply values that matching queryables send back. Iteration ends once every peer has replied or the timeout elapses, so a GetHandler needs no explicit close:\n\ngh = get(s, kexpr\"demo/example/**\", \"arg=1\"; timeout_ms = 1000)\nfor r in gh\n    if is_ok(r)\n        smpl = sample(r)\n        println(keyexpr(smpl), \" => \", String(payload(smpl)))\n    else\n        println(\"ERR: \", String(error_payload(r)))\n    end\nend\n\nget is a method of Base.get, not a new export, so get(s, ...) resolves through Base like any other get call. The server side, Queryable, and the full set of query options (target, consolidation, cancellation, and more) live on the Queries page.","title":"Query: get replies from queryables"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Clean-shutdown","page":"Getting Started","text":"close shuts a session down gracefully and releases its resources deterministically on your task. After close the session throws on any further use. Wrap the lifecycle in try/finally so teardown runs even on error:\n\ns = open(Config())\ntry\n    put(s, kexpr\"demo/example/temp\", \"21.5\")\n    # ... declare publishers/subscribers/queryables, do work ...\nfinally\n    close(s)   # idempotent; renders s unusable afterward\nend\n\nClose declared entities (publishers, subscribers, queryables) on their own; their lifetime is independent of the session's. The callback Subscriber in particular has no finalizer and must be closed; buffered handlers and publishers carry a finalizer safety net but close remains the deterministic path.","title":"Clean shutdown"},{"category":"section","location":"getting-started/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Getting Started","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nConfig Config zenoh::config::Config z_owned_config_t (z_config_default / zc_config_from_env / zc_config_from_file / zc_config_from_str)\nopen(c::Config) open a session zenoh::open z_open\nSession Session zenoh::session::Session z_owned_session_t\nclose(s::Session) — Session::close z_close + z_session_drop\nzid / router_zids / peer_zids ZenohId SessionInfo::zid/routers_zid/peers_zid z_info_zid / z_info_routers_zid / z_info_peers_zid\nto_le_bytes ZenohId ZenohId::to_le_bytes the raw z_id_t.data little-endian bytes\nput Publisher / put Session::put / Publisher::put z_put / z_publisher_put\nPublisher Publisher zenoh::pubsub::Publisher z_owned_publisher_t (z_declare_publisher)\nopen(f, s, k) / open(s, k; channel) Subscriber zenoh::pubsub::Subscriber z_declare_subscriber + z_closure_sample\nget → GetHandler Queryable / get Session::get z_get + z_closure_reply\n\nEach Zenoh.jl call is the eagerly-resolved equivalent of the named Rust and C operation, with these named divergences:\n\nNo builder/Resolvable layer. Rust returns Resolvable builders finished with .wait()/.await; Zenoh.jl's open, put, Publisher(s,k), and get execute immediately and return their result or throw ZenohError. This matches the already-resolved C API (z_open, z_put, …).\nopen copies the config. open(c::Config) clones the config before handing it off, so one Config opens many sessions — unlike a raw z_open, which consumes (moves) it.\nclose is explicit and deterministic. Rust auto-closes when the last Session clone drops; Zenoh.jl runs z_close then z_session_drop on your task, with the finalizer only as a safety net.\nNo SessionInfo. Rust groups zid/routers_zid/peers_zid under Session::info(); Zenoh.jl exposes three free functions directly on the session.\n\nwarning: `channel = :fifo` is keep-last, not Rust's FifoChannel\nThe buffered subscriber's :fifo/:ring options implement RingChannel drop-oldest semantics, not the lossless backpressure of Rust's FifoChannel. Delivery runs on a Julia-side ring rather than the native z_fifo_channel_* / z_ring_channel_* handlers. Use :keep_all for lossless delivery. Details on Publish & Subscribe.\n\nThe ownership prefixes carry meaning: z_ is the core API shared with zenoh-pico, zc_ is zenoh-c-specific (the config from_env/from_file/ from_str/to_string calls), and ze_ is non-core (zenoh-ext). The owned/loaned/moved/view type model and the zenoh-c API index describe the C surface Zenoh.jl wraps.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Publish-and-Subscribe","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"Publish/subscribe is Zenoh's primary data-flow primitive. A publisher declares intent to update values under a key expression and moves data with put (an update) or delete! (a tombstone); every matching subscriber receives one Sample per call. In Zenoh's own words a publisher is \"an entity declaring that it will be updating the key/value with keys matching a given key expression,\" and a subscriber is \"an entity registering interest for any change (put or delete) to a value associated with a key matching the specified key expression.\"\n\nEvery option is a keyword argument on Publisher, put, open, or get. The two routing factories Publisher(s, k; …) and open(s, k; …) declare the long-lived endpoints; put(s, k, payload) and delete!(s, k) give a one-shot path that skips declaration entirely. Subscribers come in two delivery models: a callback on a dedicated task, and a buffered handler you iterate or poll.","title":"Publish & Subscribe"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Publishing","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"A Publisher is a long-lived handle declared once and reused for many put/delete! calls. Its quality-of-service is fixed at declare time, so each put carries only timestamp, encoding, and attachment.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\ns = Zenoh.open(Config())                       # a Session — see [Sessions & Configuration](@ref)\n\npub = Publisher(s, kexpr\"demo/temp\";\n                congestion_control = CongestionControls.BLOCK,\n                priority           = Priorities.REAL_TIME)\n\nput(pub, \"21.5\"; encoding = \"text/plain\")       # an update sample\ndelete!(pub)                                    # a tombstone on demo/temp\nclose(pub)                                      # undeclare\n\nThe QoS keywords (congestion_control, priority, express, reliability, allowed_destination) accept the typed singletons from Quality of Service and are baked into the publisher at declare time. put(pub, …) cannot override them — see the divergence below.","title":"Publishing"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Session-one-shot-publish","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"When you publish to a key expression only once, put(s, k, payload) and delete!(s, k) send a single sample without declaring a publisher. The session forms carry QoS inline on each call, since there is no long-lived publisher to hold it:\n\nput(s, kexpr\"demo/temp\", \"22.0\";\n    priority           = Priorities.DATA,\n    congestion_control = CongestionControls.DROP)\ndelete!(s, kexpr\"demo/temp\")\n\nReach for a declared Publisher when you publish repeatedly on one key (it amortizes route resolution); reach for the session form for occasional or one-off updates.","title":"Session one-shot publish"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Subscribing","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"open(s, k; …) registers interest in every put/delete! matching key expression k. Two delivery models are available, chosen by call shape.","title":"Subscribing"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Callback-subscriber","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"open(f, s, k) runs f(::Sample) on a dedicated Julia task. Delivery is latest-wins through a single inline cell: the Zenoh I/O thread stashes each sample in a capacity-1 slot and wakes the task; a sample arriving while the previous one is unconsumed overwrites it. A slow callback therefore sees only the most recent message, and older ones are dropped silently.\n\nsub = open(s, kexpr\"demo/**\") do smpl::Sample\n    println(keyexpr(smpl), \" = \", payload(smpl))\nend\n\n# ... later, REQUIRED:\nclose(sub)\n\nAlways pair open(f, …) with close(sub): a callback Subscriber has no automatic cleanup, so it and its consume task leak until you close it explicitly.","title":"Callback subscriber"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Buffered-subscriber","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"open(s, k; channel=…, capacity=N) returns a handler you drive yourself — iterate it, or pull with take!, tryrecv!, or recv!. The channel keyword selects the buffering policy:\n\n:fifo / :ring (the default) — a bounded, drop-oldest ring of capacity slots: ROS2 KEEPLAST(capacity). Returns a SubscriberHandler. `droppedcount(sub)` reports evictions.\n:keep_all — a consume task drains into an unbounded, heap-backed buffer: ROS2 KEEP_ALL, bounded only by memory. Returns a KeepAllSubscriber. Here capacity is a floor on the internal handoff ring, not a bound on the backlog.\n\nbuf = open(s, kexpr\"demo/**\"; channel = :ring, capacity = 64)\nfor smpl in buf                 # valid only until the next iteration\n    @show keyexpr(smpl) payload(smpl)\nend\n@show dropped_count(buf)\nclose(buf)\n\nNeither model blocks the Zenoh I/O thread: all buffered delivery is a Julia-side ring filled on the I/O thread and drained on a Julia task. Closing undeclares the subscriber; iteration ends once the buffer drains.\n\nwarning: `channel=:fifo` is drop-oldest, not lossless backpressure\nDespite the name, :fifo (like :ring and the default) keeps the last capacity samples and drops the oldest on overflow; it never blocks the producer. A reader who picks :fifo expecting no data loss loses data silently under a slow consumer. For lossless delivery use channel=:keep_all, which trades memory for losslessness and OOMs (rather than deadlocks) under sustained overload.","title":"Buffered subscriber"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Iteration-sample-lifetime","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"for s in sub and the in-place receives recycle their storage for zero per-sample allocation, so a yielded Sample is valid only until the next iteration. Stashing it across iterations or collecting the handler is a use-after-free.\n\nTo hold a sample beyond the current step, use take! (returns a Sample you can keep) or a :keep_all subscriber (yields samples you can keep). For an allocation-free receive loop, reuse one SampleHolder with recv!:\n\nh = SampleHolder()\nwhile (smpl = recv!(buf, h)) !== nothing\n    process(smpl)               # valid only until the next recv!; don't stash it\nend\n\ntake! blocks for the next sample; tryrecv! is the non-blocking variant, returning nothing when the buffer is empty or the subscriber is closed.","title":"Iteration sample lifetime"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Locality-filtering","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"allowed_origin on a subscriber and allowed_destination on a publisher (or session put/get) restrict which peers participate, using the Localities singletons from Quality of Service:\n\nlocal_only = open(s, kexpr\"demo/**\"; allowed_origin = Localities.SESSION_LOCAL) do smpl\n    handle(smpl)\nend","title":"Locality filtering"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Routing-constructors-and-advanced-features","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"Publisher(s, k; …) and open(…) are routing factories: passing an advanced feature keyword changes the returned type to the corresponding Advanced* variant. For publishers the advanced keywords are cache, miss_detection, and detection; for subscribers they are history, recovery, query_timeout_ms, and detection. Routing keys on keyword presence (a type-level property), so the return type stays inference-stable. A caller needing a guaranteed concrete return type should construct the Advanced* type directly. History replay and sample-miss recovery are covered in Advanced Pub/Sub.","title":"Routing constructors and advanced features"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Queries-share-the-delivery-machinery","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"get, Reply, and GetHandler reuse the buffered subscriber's callback-ring delivery, so the reply types share the machinery on this page even though queries are a distinct abstraction documented in Queries. A query returns a GetHandler over Reply values; discriminate each with is_ok, then read sample on the ok branch or error_payload / error_encoding on the error branch. See Queries for the full query semantics.\n\nfor rep in get(s, kexpr\"demo/**\")\n    if is_ok(rep)\n        @show payload(sample(rep))\n    else\n        @show error_payload(rep)\n    end\nend","title":"Queries share the delivery machinery"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#API","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Publishers","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"","title":"Publishers"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Subscribers","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"","title":"Subscribers"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nPublisher(s, k; …) / close(p) Publisher Session::declare_publisher z_declare_publisher / z_undeclare_publisher\nput(p, payload; …) put Publisher::put z_publisher_put\nput(s, k, payload; …) put Session::put z_put\ndelete!(p) / delete!(s, k) delete Publisher::delete / Session::delete z_publisher_delete / z_delete\nopen(f, s, k) → Subscriber Subscriber SubscriberBuilder + Callback handler z_declare_subscriber + z_closure_sample\nopen(s, k; channel=:fifo|:ring) → SubscriberHandler Subscriber handlers::RingChannel z_declare_subscriber (Julia-side ring)\nopen(s, k; channel=:keep_all) → KeepAllSubscriber Subscriber (no native handler) (composed in Julia)\nSample / SampleHolder Sample Sample z_loaned_sample_t / z_owned_sample_t\nget(…) → GetHandler; Reply (query side) Session::get + Reply z_get + z_closure_reply + z_reply_*\nallowed_origin / allowed_destination Locality Locality z_subscriber_options_t / *_put_options_t\n\nZenoh.jl's keyword options fold down Rust's fluent builders: each keyword on Publisher, put, open, or get sets a field the Rust builder methods would set. Declaring a publisher maps to z_declare_publisher (Rust Session::declare_publisher, returning a PublisherBuilder); close(p) maps to z_undeclare_publisher, with a finalizer calling z_publisher_drop as a GC safety net. put(p, payload) maps to z_publisher_put and put(s, k, payload) to z_put; delete! publishes a delete-kind sample via z_publisher_delete or z_delete. The callback subscriber installs a z_closure_sample closure, corresponding to Rust's Callback handler; the buffered handler implements RingChannel (keep-last-N / drop-oldest) semantics. The query side (get, Reply, GetHandler) maps to Rust's zenoh::query module and Session::get, distinct from zenoh::pubsub. Locality filtering maps directly onto Rust's Locality on the respective options structs.\n\nSeveral divergences from core Zenoh are deliberate and load-bearing:\n\nwarning: `:fifo` is not Rust's FifoChannel\nThe buffered :fifo/:ring/default subscriber implements RingChannel (drop-oldest keep-last-N), not Rust's FifoChannel (which blocks the producer for losslessness). The native C handlers (z_fifo_channel_sample_new, z_ring_channel_sample_new, and the reply variants) exist in the bindings but no buffered endpoint routes to them by default. All buffered delivery runs through a Julia-side ring filled on the I/O thread, chosen because the native FIFO handler exposes no push notification to drive a slot-free drain and to avoid exhausting the @threadcall restrictor. Lossless backpressure awaits a Rust-side notifying FIFO handler; until then, use :keep_all.\n\nwarning: Callback delivery is latest-wins single-slot\nopen(f, s, k) uses a capacity-1 inline cell: a sample arriving while the previous is unconsumed overwrites it, so a slow callback sees only the latest message. This is a Zenoh.jl delivery policy — Rust's Callback handler invokes the callback for every sample. The callback Subscriber also carries no GC finalizer and leaks until close() is called: its FFI context and consume task form a reference cycle, and teardown must wait the task — work a finalizer cannot do. The buffered handlers on this page carry a finalizer, and Rust's drop auto-undeclares.\n\nnote: KEEP_ALL has no native equivalent\nchannel=:keep_all is composed in Julia: a consume task drains the bounded ring into an unbounded Channel{Sample}. There is no single Rust or C handler that provides this. Under sustained overload it OOMs rather than deadlocks (ROS2 KEEP_ALL semantics).\n\nTwo further contracts to honor. Publisher QoS is declare-time-only: put(p, …) accepts only timestamp/encoding/attachment because z_publisher_put_options_t carries no QoS fields — congestion_control/priority/express/reliability/allowed_destination are fixed when the Publisher is declared, and only the session-level put(s, k, …) accepts them per call. And under iteration a yielded Sample is valid only until the next step (the loop reuses one owned box); use take!, :keep_all, or recv!(sub, holder) to retain a sample. This zero-allocation box reuse is a Zenoh.jl contract with no Rust analogue, since Rust handlers yield owned samples.\n\nThe Zenoh.jl ownership model mirrors zenoh-c: _move transfers an owned value to the callee (put moves the payload ZBytes and any owned encoding/attachment), _loan borrows, and _drop releases. The C symbols above are confirmed present in the generated LibZenohC bindings.\n\nSee also: Samples, Key Expressions, Quality of Service, Queries, Advanced Pub/Sub, Matching.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.AbstractPublisher","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"abstract type AbstractPublisher\n\nSupertype of the plain Publisher and the AdvancedPublisher. Each subtype stays concrete, so a client that holds either kind parameterizes on P<:AbstractPublisher (struct Foo{P<:AbstractPublisher}; pub::P; end) and keeps its field type-stable.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AbstractPublisher"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.Publisher","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"Publisher <: AbstractPublisher\n\nLong-lived publisher declared on a Keyexpr, wrapping an owned z_owned_publisher_t (the keyexpr field pins the key expression alive for the C handle's lifetime). QoS — congestion control, priority, express, reliability, allowed destination — is fixed at declare time, so put and delete! on a publisher carry only per-call timestamp, encoding, and attachment.\n\nBuild one with Publisher(s::Session, k::Keyexpr; …), publish with put(p, payload; …), and release the C handle with close(p) (a finalizer drops the handle as a GC safety net). For the convenience one-shot path that publishes without a long-lived handle, see put(s::Session, k, payload; …).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Publisher"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.put","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"put(p::Publisher, payload; shm=nothing, timestamp, encoding, attachment)\n\nPublish payload (an update Sample) through a declared publisher via z_publisher_put. The publisher's declare-time QoS applies, so the only per-call options are timestamp, encoding, and attachment; an SHM-backed payload is selected by passing an SHM provider as shm.\n\nFor a one-shot publish without declaring a publisher — and with per-call QoS — use put(s::Session, k, payload; …).\n\n\n\n\n\nput(s::Session, k::Keyexpr, payload; shm=nothing, congestion_control, priority,\n    express, reliability, allowed_destination, timestamp, encoding, attachment)\n\nPublish payload on keyexpr k in one shot via z_put, the lightweight path that needs no declared Publisher. Because there is no long-lived handle to bake QoS into, this form accepts the full per-call QoS set (congestion_control, priority, express, reliability, allowed_destination) alongside the shared timestamp/encoding/attachment options; pass an SHM provider as shm for an SHM-backed payload.\n\nReach for Publisher plus put(p, payload; …) when publishing repeatedly on the same key.\n\n\n\n\n\nput(ap::AdvancedPublisher, payload; shm=nothing, timestamp, encoding, attachment)\n\nPublish payload through advanced publisher ap via ze_advanced_publisher_put, caching it and stamping the configured per-source sequence number. The declare-time QoS applies, so the per-call options match the plain put(::Publisher, …) form (timestamp, encoding, attachment, and an SHM provider as shm).\n\n\n\n\n\nput(p::Publisher, r::ZRef; kwargs...)\nput(s::Session, k::Keyexpr, r::ZRef; congestion_control, priority, express, allowed_destination, kwargs...)\n\nPublish the value held by ZRef r. A Julia-backed handle is borrowed (pinned for the lifetime of the payload); an SHM-backed handle is moved into the payload zero-copy. Either way the backing becomes the published bytes and r is marked consumed — a second put (or any access) on it throws.\n\nkwargs set per-put options such as encoding, attachment, and timestamp.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.put"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Base.delete!","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"delete!(s::Session, k::Keyexpr; timestamp, congestion_control, priority,\n        express, reliability, allowed_destination)\n\nPublish a delete (tombstone) sample on keyexpr k.\n\n\n\n\n\ndelete!(p::Publisher; timestamp)\n\nPublish a delete (tombstone) sample on the publisher's keyexpr.\n\n\n\n\n\ndelete!(ap::AdvancedPublisher; timestamp)\n\nPublish a delete (tombstone) sample on the advanced publisher's keyexpr.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.delete!"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.Subscriber","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"Subscriber\n\nCallback-form subscriber returned by Base.open(f, s, k). The Zenoh I/O thread stashes each sample in a single inline cell (overwriting the previous one if not yet consumed) and wakes a Julia task; slow consumers see only the latest message. Use open(s, k; channel=:fifo) for queued semantics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Subscriber"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.SubscriberHandler","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"SubscriberHandler\n\nBuffered subscriber returned by Base.open(s, k; channel=:fifo, capacity=N). Iterate or use take!/tryrecv! to consume Samples. Iteration terminates once the subscriber is closed and the buffer is drained.\n\nDelivery is the slot-free callback ring: samples land in a Julia-side capacity-N ring on libzenohc's I/O thread and are pulled here on the consuming task. When the consumer falls behind, the oldest buffered sample is dropped (dropped_count(sub) counts evictions). Other Julia tasks — including close(sub) from a sibling task — run concurrently while iteration waits.\n\nnote: Iteration lifetime\nfor s in sub reuses one buffer per loop for zero per-sample allocation, so a yielded Sample is valid only until the next iteration — don't stash it across iterations or collect it. Use take! (or a :keep_all subscriber) when you need to hold a sample beyond the current step.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SubscriberHandler"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.KeepAllSubscriber","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"KeepAllSubscriber\n\nLossless buffered subscriber returned by Base.open(s, k; channel=:keep_all). Iterate or use take!/tryrecv! to consume Samples; iteration terminates once the subscriber is closed and the backlog is drained.\n\nKeeps every matching sample (ROS KEEP_ALL): a consume task drains the slot-free callback ring into an unbounded, heap-backed Channel{Sample}, so the ring stays near-empty and the I/O thread never blocks. The backlog accumulates on the Julia heap, bounded only by memory — sustained overload exhausts memory rather than deadlocking. Yielded samples are owned and safe to hold across iterations, unlike the per-step samples of a drop-oldest SubscriberHandler.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.KeepAllSubscriber"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Base.take!-Tuple{Zenoh.AbstractSubscriberHandler}","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"take!(sh::AbstractSubscriberHandler) -> Sample\n\nBlock until the next buffered sample arrives and return it as an owned Sample. Throws ZenohError once the subscriber is closed and its buffer is drained. tryrecv! is the non-blocking counterpart; recv! with a SampleHolder is the allocation-free loop.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.take!"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.recv!","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"recv!(sub, holder::SampleHolder) -> holder | nothing\n\nZero-allocation receive: block for the next sample and fill holder in place (dropping its previous occupant), returning holder, or nothing once the subscriber is closed and drained. Reuse one holder across calls for an allocation-free receive loop:\n\nh = SampleHolder()\nwhile (s = recv!(sub, h)) !== nothing\n    # process s now — it (and its payload/keyexpr/…) is valid only until the\n    # next recv!; don't stash it\nend\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.recv!"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/publish-subscribe/#Zenoh.tryrecv!-Tuple{Zenoh.AbstractSubscriberHandler}","page":"Publish & Subscribe","text":"tryrecv!(sub) -> Sample | Reply | nothing\ntryrecv!(sub::AbstractSubscriberHandler, h::SampleHolder) -> h | nothing\n\nNon-blocking receive: returns the next buffered item — a Sample from a buffered subscriber, a Reply from a GetHandler — or nothing when nothing is buffered (or the endpoint is closed and drained). The SampleHolder method fills h in place (dropping its previous occupant) for an allocation-free poll loop, returning h or nothing.\n\nThe non-blocking counterpart to take! / recv!: poll it when you want to do other work rather than park waiting for an item.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.tryrecv!"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Sessions-and-Configuration","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"A Session is the main component of Zenoh: it holds the Zenoh runtime and maintains the node's connection state to the rest of the network (Zenoh Session docs). Every publisher, subscriber, querier, and queryable is declared on a session, and every put, get, and delete! routes through one. You obtain a session by calling open on a Config.\n\nA Config holds all the parameters that shape a session: the node's role, the endpoints it connects to and listens on, scouting and transport tuning, QoS rules, and more (Zenoh Config docs). Zenoh treats the config's fields as unstable, so you mutate and read it only through JSON5, addressing values by dotted key. Zenoh.jl exposes that raw surface directly through Config and layers a typed, idiomatic builder — ZenohConfig and the ConfigSection family — on top of it.","title":"Sessions & Configuration"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Configuring-a-session","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Configuration comes in two layers. The lower layer is Config: a thin wrapper over Zenoh's own config object, where every value flows through Zenoh's JSON5 parser. The upper layer is ZenohConfig: typed Julia structs whose field names mirror Zenoh's config keys, flattened to dotted key paths and applied on top of a base config. Reach for the typed layer for everything you commonly set, and drop to raw keys for anything it does not model.","title":"Configuring a session"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#The-typed-builder","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"ZenohConfig describes a configuration with named, nested structs. Only the fields you set are applied; everything else keeps Zenoh's defaults. Build a Config from it by passing it to the Config constructor:\n\nusing Zenoh\n\ncfg = Config(ZenohConfig(\n    mode      = :peer,\n    connect   = Connect(endpoints = [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"]),\n    scouting  = Scouting(multicast = Multicast(enabled = true)),\n    transport = Transport(shared_memory = SharedMemory(enabled = true)),\n    overrides = Dict(\"transport/link/tx/threads\" => 4),  # escape hatch for unmodeled keys\n))\n\nmode is the node's role in the network — :peer, :router, or :client (Zenoh WhatAmI). Symbols are validated against those three values; an unknown symbol throws immediately.\n\nEach section maps to a Zenoh config block. Connect and Listen hold endpoint lists (tcp/localhost:7447 and the like); Scouting nests Multicast and Gossip discovery; Transport nests Unicast, TransportMulticast, Link, SharedMemory, and Auth; Qos carries rule lists. See ZenohConfig and the individual section docstrings for the full set.\n\nThe overrides field is the escape hatch: a dict mapping raw dotted keys to values, applied last so it wins over the typed fields. It reaches any key the typed sections do not model.\n\nApply more settings to a config you already built with configure!:\n\ncfg = Config()                                   # built-in defaults\nconfigure!(cfg, ZenohConfig(mode = :client))     # mutate in place, returns cfg\n\nwarning: The `open` section serializes to `open/return_conditions`\nOpen is the one section whose dotted path differs from its field name: Open(connect_scouted = true) writes to open/return_conditions/connect_scouted, matching Zenoh's config layout. Every other section's path is its field name.","title":"The typed builder"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#The-raw-config-layer","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Config constructs from one of four sources, selected by mutually exclusive keywords:\n\nConfig()                          # Zenoh's built-in defaults\nConfig(from_env = true)           # parse the file named by the ZENOH_CONFIG env var\nConfig(file = \"zenoh.json5\")      # load a JSON5 file\nConfig(str = \"{ mode: 'peer' }\")  # parse a JSON5 string\n\nRead and write individual keys by dotted path. getindex returns the JSON-serialized value; setindex! inserts a value at a key:\n\ncfg[\"mode\"]                       # => \"null\" on a default config; \"\\\"peer\\\"\" once mode is set\ncfg[\"connect/endpoints\"] = [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"]   # serialized to JSON5, then inserted\n\nwarning: `setindex!` inserts `String` values verbatim as JSON5\nA String value is inserted verbatim as pre-formatted JSON5, so it must already be valid JSON5. Every other value type is serialized first. So cfg[\"mode\"] = \"peer\" inserts the bareword peer, which Zenoh rejects. Write cfg[\"mode\"] = :peer (a Symbol is serialized to the quoted string \"peer\") or hand-quote it as cfg[\"mode\"] = \"\\\"peer\\\"\". The typed builder serializes every value through _to_json5, so a symbol or string always reaches Zenoh correctly quoted.\n\nEvery value round-trips through Zenoh's own JSON5 parser on insert, which validates and canonicalizes it. So a Config holds no parsed state and needs no JSON dependency.","title":"The raw config layer"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Opening-and-closing-a-session","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"open takes a Config and returns a live Session. It copies the config before opening, so the same Config stays valid and reusable across multiple open calls.\n\nclose gracefully shuts the session down and frees its handle, deterministically on the calling task. It is idempotent: a second close is a no-op. After close the session is unusable and any operation on it throws. Pair open with close in a try/finally:\n\ns = open(cfg)                     # copies cfg; cfg stays reusable\ntry\n    @assert isopen(s)\n    # declare publishers/subscribers, put/get here\nfinally\n    close(s)                      # graceful shutdown + free; idempotent\nend\n\nCall close explicitly: the graceful shutdown drains Zenoh's async runtime, work that should run on your task where ordering is predictable. A GC finalizer frees an unclosed session as a safety net, and skips a session you closed yourself.","title":"Opening and closing a session"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Session-identity-and-connectivity","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Every session has a globally unique 16-byte Zenoh ID. zid returns this session's ID. A valid session always yields a non-zero ID; an all-zero 16-byte array signals an invalid session. router_zids and peer_zids return the IDs of the routers and peers this session is currently connected to.\n\nid = zid(s)                       # this session's Zenoh ID\nto_le_bytes(id)                   # raw 16-byte little-endian tuple (NTuple{16,UInt8})\nrouter_zids(s)                    # IDs of connected routers\npeer_zids(s)                      # IDs of connected peers\n\nwarning: `to_le_bytes` and the printed string have opposite byte order\nto_le_bytes returns the ID's raw little-endian bytes — the form Zenoh hashes and serializes. The show representation renders those same bytes reversed (most-significant first) with leading zero bytes elided. Use to_le_bytes whenever you need the canonical byte order; use the string only for display.","title":"Session identity and connectivity"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Shared-memory","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"open accepts a shm_clients keyword (plus on_shm_alloc_error, wait_for_shm, and shm_wait_timeout) to open the session with shared-memory transport support. These are a Zenoh.jl-specific layer over Zenoh's SHM support; see Shared Memory for the full story, including default_shm_clients, shm_state, and shm_ready.","title":"Shared memory"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#The-admin-space","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Setting the AdminSpace section enables Zenoh's admin space — the key space dedicated to administering a router and its plugins, accessible under @/router/<router-id> (admin space docs). Zenoh.jl exposes the config switch that turns it on; querying it afterward is ordinary get and put against those key expressions, not a dedicated API.","title":"The admin space"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Sessions-API","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"","title":"Sessions API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Configuration-API","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"","title":"Configuration API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nSession Session zenoh::session::Session z_owned_session_t\nopen(::Config) open a session zenoh::open z_open (z_open_with_custom_shm_clients with shm_clients)\nclose close a session Session::close z_close + z_session_drop\nisopen session liveness !Session::is_closed !z_session_is_closed\nzid session Zenoh ID SessionInfo::zid z_info_zid\nrouter_zids / peer_zids connected routers/peers SessionInfo::routers_zid / peers_zid z_info_routers_zid / z_info_peers_zid\nto_le_bytes Zenoh ID bytes ZenohId::to_le_bytes z_id_t.data\nConfig Config zenoh::config::Config z_owned_config_t\nConfig(; from_env, file, str) config sources Config::default / from_env / from_file / from_json5 z_config_default / zc_config_from_env / zc_config_from_file / zc_config_from_str\ncfg[key] read a config value Config::get_json zc_config_get_from_str\ncfg[key] = value write a config value Config::insert_json5 zc_config_insert_json5\ncfg.mode / ZenohConfig.mode node role WhatAmI mode JSON5 key\nAdminSpace admin space adminspace config adminspace JSON5 key\nZenohConfig / ConfigSection family (none) zenoh-config serde structs (none)\n\nSession is a thin owner of zenoh-c's z_owned_session_t, equivalent to Rust's zenoh::session::Session, with extra cells tracking close-state and discovered SHM capability. open corresponds to zenoh::open / z_open. zid, router_zids, and peer_zids cover the same ground as Rust's SessionInfo::zid/routers_zid/peers_zid (z_info_zid/z_info_routers_zid/z_info_peers_zid). The raw Config mirrors Rust's zenoh::config::Config exactly: fields are unstable, so JSON5 round-tripping is the only surface on both sides.\n\nSeveral divergences are worth naming precisely:\n\nNo SessionInfo type. Rust groups zid/routers_zid/peers_zid under Session::info() -> SessionInfo. Zenoh.jl flattens them into three free functions on Session; there is no info() and no SessionInfo struct.\nopen returns a live session directly. Rust's zenoh::open returns an awaitable OpenBuilder that yields a Session once awaited. Zenoh.jl's open returns the live Session directly.\nclose is explicit and deterministic. Rust auto-closes when the last Session clone drops. Zenoh.jl's close performs z_close then z_session_drop on the calling task; the GC finalizer is only a safety net that skips already-closed sessions.\nopen copies the config. A raw z_open moves and consumes the config. Zenoh.jl's open clones it first (z_config_clone) and moves the copy, so the caller's Config stays usable across multiple open calls.\nSHM open keywords are Zenoh.jl-only. on_shm_alloc_error, wait_for_shm, and shm_wait_timeout have no zenoh-c counterpart; only shm_clients maps to a C function (z_open_with_custom_shm_clients). See Shared Memory.\n\nnote: Zenoh.jl extension: the typed config builder\nZenohConfig and the ConfigSection family are a pure Julia layer with no Zenoh equivalent. Zenoh exposes config only as JSON5; these typed @kwdef structs track the zenoh-config serde key names by hand and flatten to dotted keys on apply. Upstream renames to those keys would silently break the typed layer, so the overrides escape hatch always reaches the raw keys directly.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Session","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Session\n\nThe central Zenoh runtime handle, holding the connection state of this node to the Zenoh network. Wraps an owned z_owned_session_t and is the object every put, get, and declaration (Publisher, Subscriber, Queryable) routes through — internally via a _loan chokepoint that throws once the session is closed, so a use-after-free can never reach the dropped handle.\n\nOpen one with open(::Config) and release it with close, which runs the graceful shutdown and frees the handle deterministically on the calling task. A GC finalizer drops the handle as a safety net for sessions that were never explicitly closed.\n\nThe struct stays immutable; close state and discovered shared-memory capability live in mutable cells so they can be updated in place. Query identity and topology with zid, router_zids, and peer_zids.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Session"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Base.open-Tuple{Config}","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Opens a new Zenoh session with a given Zenoh config. Copies the config.\n\nPass shm_clients=default_shm_clients() (or a custom ShmClientStorage) to open the session with shared-memory client support enabled. When unset, the session is opened without SHM clients — same behavior as zenoh-c's z_open.\n\non_shm_alloc_error registers a callback invoked when zref(::Session, T) fails to allocate from the session's SHM provider (a ShmAllocError — segment full or needing defragmentation) and is about to fall back to Julia memory. The callback receives the ShmAllocError; return normally to allow the (silent) fallback, or throw to escalate the failure out of zref. When unset, the fallback is silent (a @debug is still emitted).\n\nwait_for_shm blocks until the session's SHM provider is ready before returning (only meaningful with shm_clients). true waits up to shm_wait_timeout seconds; a number waits up to that many seconds; false (default) returns immediately. Waiting only applies while the provider is :initializing — terminal states (:unavailable/:disabled/:error) return at once. Inspect shm_state(s) / shm_ready(s) afterwards to see the outcome.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.open"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Base.close-Tuple{Session}","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Closes a Zenoh session: gracefully shuts it down (z_close) and frees the handle (z_session_drop), deterministically on the calling task. The handle is freed even if the graceful z_close reports an error, so a transient shutdown/runtime error can't leak the session. Idempotent — a second close is a no-op, and the GC finalizer skips an already-closed session. After close the session is unusable; operations on it throw.\n\nwarning: Warning\nclose must not run concurrently with in-flight operations on the same session from other tasks. It frees the handle, so an operation parked in a C call holding a pointer loaned from this session (the _loan chokepoint checks closed but does not hold a lock across the call) could touch freed memory. Quiesce a shared session — join its publisher/subscriber tasks — before closing it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.close"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Base.isopen-Tuple{Session}","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Checks if zenoh session is open.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.isopen"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.zid","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Returns the session’s Zenoh ID.\n\nA valid session always yields a non-zero ID; an all-zero 16-byte array means the session was invalid.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.zid"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.router_zids","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Fetches the Zenoh IDs of all connected routers.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.router_zids"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.peer_zids","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Fetches the Zenoh IDs of all connected peers.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.peer_zids"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.to_le_bytes","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"to_le_bytes(id::z_id_t) -> NTuple{16, UInt8}\n\nThe Zenoh id as its raw 16-byte little-endian array — the form zenoh hashes and serializes (the Rust ZenohId::to_le_bytes). Note this is not the byte order of the printed/shown string: the string renders these bytes reversed (most-significant first) with leading zero bytes elided.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.to_le_bytes"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.ZenohError","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"ZenohError <: Exception\n\nThe exception raised when a Zenoh C call returns a non-Z_OK result.\n\nThe code field holds the LibZenohC.z_result_t status code returned by the failed call.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZenohError"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Config","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"A Zenoh configuration. Can be constructed as Config(; fromenv=[should load from ZENOHCONFIG env var], file=\"filename\", str=\"json string\"). At most one of these options may be set. With none set (the default), the configuration is initialized from Zenoh's built-in defaults.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Config"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.configure!","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"configure!(c::Config, zc::ZenohConfig) -> Config\n\nApply every set field of zc onto the existing config c (in place), then apply zc.overrides last. Returns c.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.configure!"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.ZenohConfig","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"ZenohConfig(; mode, connect, listen, scouting, transport, qos, …, overrides)\n\nIdiomatic, typed description of a Zenoh configuration. Only the fields you set are applied; everything else keeps Zenoh's defaults. Apply it by constructing a Config from it:\n\nc = Config(ZenohConfig(\n    mode = :peer,\n    connect = Connect(endpoints = [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"]),\n    scouting = Scouting(multicast = Multicast(enabled = true)),\n    overrides = Dict(\"transport/link/tx/threads\" => 4),\n))\n\nmode accepts :peer, :router, :client (or the equivalent strings). overrides is an escape hatch mapping raw dotted config keys to values, applied last (so they win over the typed fields); it reaches anything not modeled as a typed section.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ZenohConfig"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.ConfigSection","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"ConfigSection\n\nInternal marker supertype for every typed config section. The apply machinery dispatches on it: a bare ConfigSection is recursed into (flattened to dotted leaf paths), while a Vector{<:ConfigSection} is a leaf inserted whole as a JSON array-of-objects.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ConfigSection"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Connect","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Connect(; endpoints, timeout_ms, exit_on_failure, retry)\n\nEndpoints to actively connect to (connect/…). endpoints is a vector of locator strings, e.g. [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"].\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Connect"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Listen","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Listen(; endpoints, timeout_ms, exit_on_failure, retry)\n\nEndpoints to listen on (listen/…). Same shape as Connect.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Listen"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Scouting","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Scouting(; timeout, delay, multicast, gossip)\n\nPeer/router discovery (scouting/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Scouting"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Multicast","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Multicast(; enabled, address, interface, ttl)\n\nUDP multicast discovery settings (scouting/multicast/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Multicast"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Gossip","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Gossip(; enabled, multihop)\n\nGossip-based discovery settings (scouting/gossip/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Gossip"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Open","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Open(; connect_scouted, declares)\n\nConditions controlling when open returns (open/return_conditions/…): connect_scouted waits for scouted peers, declares waits for initial declarations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Open"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Timestamping","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Timestamping(; enabled, drop_future_timestamp)\n\nData message timestamp management (timestamping/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Timestamping"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Transport","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Transport(; unicast, multicast, link, shared_memory, auth)\n\nTransport-layer configuration (transport/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Transport"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Unicast","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Unicast(; open_timeout, accept_timeout, max_sessions, max_links, lowlatency)\n\nUnicast transport settings (transport/unicast/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Unicast"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.TransportMulticast","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"TransportMulticast(; join_interval, max_sessions)\n\nMulticast transport settings (transport/multicast/…). Distinct from scouting's Multicast.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.TransportMulticast"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Link","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Link(; protocols, tx, rx)\n\nLink-layer settings (transport/link/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Link"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.LinkTx","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"LinkTx(; threads, batch_size, lease, keep_alive, sequence_number_resolution)\n\nLink transmission settings (transport/link/tx/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LinkTx"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.LinkRx","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"LinkRx(; buffer_size, max_message_size)\n\nLink reception settings (transport/link/rx/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LinkRx"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.SharedMemory","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"SharedMemory(; enabled)\n\nShared-memory transport optimization (transport/shared_memory/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SharedMemory"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Auth","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Auth(; usrpwd)\n\nTransport authentication (transport/auth/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Auth"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.UsrPwd","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"UsrPwd(; user, password, dictionary_file)\n\nUsername/password authentication (transport/auth/usrpwd/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.UsrPwd"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Qos","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Qos(; publication, network)\n\nQoS message overwrite rules (qos/…). Each field is a vector of rule structs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Qos"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.PublicationRule","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"PublicationRule(; key_exprs, congestion_control, priority, express, reliability, allowed_origin)\n\nA single per-keyexpr publication QoS rule (an entry in qos/publication).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.PublicationRule"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.QosOverwrite","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"QosOverwrite(; messages, key_exprs, flows, overwrite)\n\nA single network QoS overwrite rule (an entry in qos/network).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QosOverwrite"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.QosOverwriteValues","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"QosOverwriteValues(; congestion_control, priority, express, reliability)\n\nThe QoS values applied by a QosOverwrite rule (its overwrite field).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QosOverwriteValues"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Aggregation","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Aggregation(; subscribers, publishers)\n\nDeclaration aggregation strategy (aggregation/…). Each field is a vector of key expression strings.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Aggregation"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.AdminSpace","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"AdminSpace(; enabled, permissions)\n\nAdmin space configuration (adminspace/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AdminSpace"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/sessions-and-configuration/#Zenoh.Permissions","page":"Sessions & Configuration","text":"Permissions(; read, write)\n\nAdmin space permissions (adminspace/permissions/…).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Permissions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Key-Expressions","page":"Key Expressions","text":"A key expression denotes a set of keys. A Zenoh key is a /-joined list of UTF-8 chunks — organizationA/building8/room275/sensor3/temperature — where / is the hierarchical separator, just like a Unix path. A key expression adds wildcards over that hierarchy: * matches any characters within one chunk (never crossing /), $* matches within a chunk, and ** matches zero or more chunks. So demo/** denotes every key under demo, and demo/*/temperature denotes the temperature of every direct child of demo. Key expressions are the addressing layer underneath every Zenoh operation — publishers, subscribers, queries, and queryables all name their data with one.\n\nIn Zenoh.jl a key expression is a Keyexpr: a validated value whose memory the garbage collector reclaims for you. Build one from a string literal with the kexpr\"…\" macro or from a runtime String with the Keyexpr constructor; both validate the syntax eagerly, so an ill-formed expression fails the moment you construct it. Once you hold two Keyexpr values, the set predicates (includes, intersects, relation_to) tell you how their key-sets relate, and the composition functions (concat, join) build longer keys from shorter ones.","title":"Key Expressions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Constructing-a-key-expression","page":"Key Expressions","text":"There are two construction paths. Reach for the macro when the expression is a literal known at parse time; reach for the constructor when the bytes arrive at runtime.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\na = kexpr\"demo/**\"                       # literal, validated when the macro expands\nb = Keyexpr(\"demo/example/zenoh-jl\")     # runtime String\n\nThe kexpr\"…\" macro additionally interpolates $name and $(expr) pieces, splicing Keyexpr or AbstractString values into the result:\n\nroom = \"room275\"\nk = kexpr\"building8/$room/sensor3\"       # building8/room275/sensor3\n\nprefix = kexpr\"building8/$room\"\nfull = kexpr\"$prefix/sensor3\"            # Keyexpr pieces splice in directly\n\nThe interpolating form splices Keyexpr and AbstractString pieces directly into the result, without an extra copy through a Julia String.","title":"Constructing a key expression"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Canonicalization","page":"Key Expressions","text":"A key expression has a canonical form: **/** reduces to **, **/* reorders to */**, $*$* collapses to $*, and so on (see the canonical-form rules). Construction requires canonical input by default — a non-canonical expression throws a ZenohError, so a typo surfaces at construction. Construction never rewrites your input.\n\nOpt into canonicalization with the c flag on the macro or autocanonize=true on the constructor:\n\nkexpr\"a/**/**\"c                       # canonized → a/**\nKeyexpr(\"a/**/**\"; autocanonize=true) # same, runtime form\n\nCanonicalization reduces redundant wildcard runs on otherwise-valid expressions; it does not repair structurally invalid syntax. An empty chunk such as the // in a//b is invalid, and both the plain and the autocanonizing paths throw a ZenohError on it.\n\nTo canonicalize or test plain strings before they become a Keyexpr, use canonize and is_canon. These operate on AbstractString, not on Keyexpr (a constructed Keyexpr is already canonical):\n\nis_canon(\"a/**/**\")    # false\ncanonize(\"a/**/**\")    # \"a/**\"\nis_canon(\"a/**\")       # true\ncanonize(\"a//b\")       # throws ZenohError — the empty chunk in a//b is invalid syntax","title":"Canonicalization"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Set-relations","page":"Key Expressions","text":"Key expressions denote sets, so the natural questions are about set membership and overlap. relation_to answers all of them at once, returning the full lattice relationship as one of four typed singletons from IntersectionLevels:\n\nrelation_to(kexpr\"demo/**\", Keyexpr(\"demo/example/zenoh-jl\"))  # IntersectionLevels.INCLUDES\n\nLevel Meaning\nIntersectionLevels.DISJOINT no key in common\nIntersectionLevels.INTERSECTS some keys shared, neither set contains the other\nIntersectionLevels.INCLUDES a ⊇ b\nIntersectionLevels.EQUALS identical key-sets\n\nThe boolean predicates are projections of that lattice. includes(a, b) tests a ⊇ b; intersects(a, b) tests overlap. Julia's standard set operators work too: issubset (⊆) is the dual of includes, and isdisjoint is the negation of intersects, so both are computed in Julia from the same two calls.\n\na = kexpr\"demo/**\"\nb = Keyexpr(\"demo/example/zenoh-jl\")\n\nincludes(a, b)                  # true:  demo/** ⊇ demo/example/zenoh-jl\nb ⊆ a                           # true:  same fact, dual direction (issubset)\nintersects(a, b)                # true\nisdisjoint(a, kexpr\"other/**\")  # true","title":"Set relations"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#and-set-equality-coincide","page":"Key Expressions","text":"A Keyexpr is stored in canonical form, and == compares that canonical text. relation_to(a, b) == IntersectionLevels.EQUALS asks the set question — do a and b match the same keys. For any two constructed Keyexpr values the two agree: canonicalization normalizes set-equal expressions to identical text, so a/**/** becomes a/** at construction and compares equal to a directly-built a/**.\n\nx = Keyexpr(\"a/**\")\ny = Keyexpr(\"a/**/**\"; autocanonize=true)       # canonized to \"a/**\" on construction\n\nx == y                                          # true (same canonical text)\nrelation_to(x, y) == IntersectionLevels.EQUALS  # true (same key-set)\n\nUse == (and the consistent hash) for identity in dictionaries and sets; use relation_to/includes/intersects to ask whether one expression matches another.","title":"== and set equality coincide"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Composing-key-expressions","page":"Key Expressions","text":"join and concat build a longer key expression from parts. They differ in one place: join inserts a / separator, concat appends verbatim.\n\njoin(Keyexpr(\"demo\"), Keyexpr(\"sensor\"))    # Keyexpr(\"demo/sensor\")    — separator inserted\nconcat(Keyexpr(\"demo/sensor\"), \"-temp\")     # Keyexpr(\"demo/sensor-temp\") — no separator\n\nUse join to descend the hierarchy and concat to extend the final chunk.","title":"Composing key expressions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Reading-a-key-expression-back","page":"Key Expressions","text":"String, string, print, and show all return the canonical text of a Keyexpr:\n\nString(kexpr\"demo/**\")    # \"demo/**\"","title":"Reading a key expression back"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#API","page":"Key Expressions","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Key Expressions","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nKeyexpr Key expression keyexpr / OwnedKeyExpr / KeyExpr z_owned_keyexpr_t\nkexpr\"…\" key-expression literal KeyExpr::new z_keyexpr_from_str / z_keyexpr_from_substr\nKeyexpr(s; autocanonize) key-expression literal KeyExpr::autocanonize z_keyexpr_from_str{,_autocanonize}\nincludes / issubset set inclusion keyexpr::includes z_keyexpr_includes\nintersects / isdisjoint set intersection keyexpr::intersects z_keyexpr_intersects\nrelation_to + IntersectionLevels set-intersection relation KeyExpr::relation_to → SetIntersectionLevel z_keyexpr_relation_to / z_keyexpr_intersection_level_t\n== / hash — — z_keyexpr_equals\nconcat — KeyExpr::concat z_keyexpr_concat\njoin — keyexpr::join z_keyexpr_join\ncanonize / is_canon canonical form Canonize z_keyexpr_canonize / z_keyexpr_is_canon\n\nKeyexpr wraps the C z_owned_keyexpr_t handle with a z_keyexpr_drop finalizer, so it is the owned form and the bytes are always copied into owned storage. The constructor calls z_keyexpr_from_str{,_autocanonize}; the interpolating macro path assembles one buffer and calls z_keyexpr_from_substr{,_autocanonize}. relation_to maps z_keyexpr_intersection_level_t one-for-one onto the four IntersectionLevels singletons, which mirror Rust's SetIntersectionLevel variants. includes, intersects, concat, join, canonize, and is_canon each wrap their z_keyexpr_* counterpart directly; issubset and isdisjoint are Julia-side derivations (includes(b, a) and !intersects(a, b)) with no dedicated C entry point.\n\nnote: One Julia type for three Rust forms\nZenoh.jl exposes one form — the owned, GC-finalized Keyexpr, which always owns its bytes. Rust splits the concept into the borrowed keyexpr (a str newtype), OwnedKeyExpr (an Arc<str>), and KeyExpr (a possibly-declared form that can carry a Session optimization); the C z_view_keyexpr_t borrowed view rounds out the set. The borrowed variants have no Julia equivalent; Rust's declared KeyExpr maps to DeclaredKeyexpr (see the warning below).\n\nnote: relation_to is stable here, unstable in Rust\nOn Rust's borrowed keyexpr, relation_to is gated behind the crate's unstable feature flag (it is stable on KeyExpr). Zenoh.jl exposes relation_to unconditionally.\n\nwarning: Declared key expressions carry no wire benefit here\nz_declare_keyexpr / z_undeclare_keyexpr are wrapped as DeclaredKeyexpr (via declare_keyexpr) for API parity with upstream Zenoh, but in this libzenohc they provide no on-wire optimization: session-level put/get send the full key string on every call regardless of declaration. This was confirmed by profiling and a pure-C repro — it is a libzenohc/zenoh-core behavior, not a binding limitation (the full investigation and repro live under docs/design/). The path that does reduce key bytes on the wire is a Publisher (or Querier), which declares its own key — so for repeated operations on a fixed key, use those, not DeclaredKeyexpr.\n\nnote: Interpolation is a Zenoh.jl extension\nThe $name / $(expr) template assembly in kexpr\"…\" is specific to Zenoh.jl. Rust constructs key expressions from string literals through KeyExpr::new; the single-buffer $-interpolation has no Rust or C analogue.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.AbstractKeyexpr","page":"Key Expressions","text":"Common supertype for the plain Keyexpr and the network-optimized DeclaredKeyexpr (types/declaredkeyexpr.jl). Both wrap an owned `zownedkeyexprtin a.kfield and answer_loan, so either flows through every operation that loans a key expression.Keyexprstays the concrete default;DeclaredKeyexpr` is the opt-in id-backed form.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.AbstractKeyexpr"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.Keyexpr","page":"Key Expressions","text":"Keyexpr(s::AbstractString; autocanonize=false) -> Keyexpr\n\nOwned, validated handle denoting a set of keys. A key is a /-separated list of UTF-8 chunks (/ is the hierarchical separator); a key expression adds the wildcards * (any chunk), $* (any run within a chunk), and ** (zero or more chunks). See the key-expression language for the full grammar and canonical-form rules.\n\nBuild one from a literal with @kexpr_str (which also supports $name/$(expr) interpolation), or from a runtime string with this constructor. The input is copied into Zenoh-owned storage and freed when the Keyexpr is garbage-collected. Pass autocanonize=true to reduce redundant wildcard runs while constructing; otherwise a non-canonical input throws ZenohError rather than being silently rewritten.\n\nThe set-relation API (relation_to, includes, intersects, issubset, isdisjoint) and the composition functions concat and join all operate on Keyexpr values. Textual read-back is available through String, string, and print.\n\n== and hash use canonical-string equality. This differs from set equality: relation_to(a, b) == IntersectionLevels.EQUALS can hold for keyexprs that are not == (e.g. a/** and a/**/** denote the same key-set but differ as text).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Keyexpr"},{"category":"macro","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.@kexpr_str","page":"Key Expressions","text":"kexpr\"key/expr\"\nkexpr\"key/**/**\"c\nkexpr\"prefix/$inner/suffix\"\nkexpr\"$a/$(b)\"c\n\nString macro for Keyexpr. Supports $name and $(expr) interpolation of Keyexpr or AbstractString values.\n\nThe interpolating form assembles the result in a single byte buffer with one z_keyexpr_from_substr call — Keyexpr pieces are read via z_keyexpr_as_view_string directly out of their canonical-storage bytes, splicing in their bytes without a per-interpolation Julia String.\n\nThe c flag opts into autocanonicalization, reducing redundant wildcard runs (**/** → **, **/* → */**). Without it, the assembled result must already be canonical or the call throws ZenohError.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.@kexpr_str"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.includes","page":"Key Expressions","text":"includes(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> Bool\n\ntrue when every key matched by b is also matched by a — i.e. a is a superset (or equal). Wildcard ** includes any concrete key under it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.includes"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.intersects","page":"Key Expressions","text":"intersects(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> Bool\n\ntrue when at least one key is matched by both.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.intersects"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.relation_to","page":"Key Expressions","text":"relation_to(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> IntersectionLevel\n\na's key-set relationship to b's, as an IntersectionLevel: DISJOINT (no shared key), INTERSECTS (overlap, neither contains the other), INCLUDES (a ⊇ b), or EQUALS (same key-set). This is the lattice level behind includes, intersects, issubset, and isdisjoint.\n\nEQUALS is set equality. For constructed Keyexpr values it coincides with ==, since every Keyexpr is stored canonical and == compares that canonical text.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.relation_to"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.IntersectionLevel","page":"Key Expressions","text":"IntersectionLevel\n\nAbstract supertype of the four set-relation singletons in IntersectionLevels and the declared return type of relation_to.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.IntersectionLevel"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.IntersectionLevels","page":"Key Expressions","text":"IntersectionLevels\n\nNamespace holding the four set-relation singletons returned by relation_to: DISJOINT (no key in common), INTERSECTS (some keys shared, neither key-set contains the other), INCLUDES (the first key-set contains the second), and EQUALS (identical key-sets). They mirror Zenoh's SetIntersectionLevel lattice, where equality implies inclusion implies intersection. Each constant is an instance of a like-named singleton type (Disjoint, Intersects, Includes, Equals), all subtypes of IntersectionLevel.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.IntersectionLevels"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.concat","page":"Key Expressions","text":"concat(a::Keyexpr, suffix::AbstractString) -> Keyexpr\n\nAppend a raw string suffix to a. The suffix is concatenated verbatim — no / is inserted. Use join to join two keyexprs with a separator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.concat"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Base.join-Tuple{Keyexpr, Keyexpr}","page":"Key Expressions","text":"join(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> Keyexpr\n\nJoin two keyexprs with a / separator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.join"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Base.issubset-Tuple{Keyexpr, Keyexpr}","page":"Key Expressions","text":"issubset(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> Bool\n\ntrue when every key matched by a is also matched by b (a ⊆ b); the ⊆ operator works too. Dual of includes (a ⊆ b ⟺ b ⊇ a).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.issubset"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Base.isdisjoint-Tuple{Keyexpr, Keyexpr}","page":"Key Expressions","text":"isdisjoint(a::Keyexpr, b::Keyexpr) -> Bool\n\ntrue when no key is matched by both — the negation of intersects.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.isdisjoint"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.canonize","page":"Key Expressions","text":"canonize(s::AbstractString) -> String\n\nReturn the canonical form of keyexpr string s, reducing redundant wildcard runs (**/** → **, **/* → */**, $*$* → $*). Throws ZenohError if s is not a valid key expression; an empty chunk such as the // in a//b is invalid and throws rather than collapsing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.canonize"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.is_canon","page":"Key Expressions","text":"is_canon(s::AbstractString) -> Bool\n\ntrue if s is already in canonical form.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.is_canon"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.DeclaredKeyexpr","page":"Key Expressions","text":"DeclaredKeyexpr <: AbstractKeyexpr\n\nA key expression registered with the session via z_declare_keyexpr. Construct with declare_keyexpr; use it like any Keyexpr (it loans the same way). Call close (or use the scoped declare_keyexpr(f, s, k) form) to undeclare it; a finalizer is the GC safety net.\n\nwarning: No performance benefit in this libzenohc\nSession-level put/get do not use a declared keyexpr's numeric id on the wire (verified by profiling and a pure-C repro — a libzenohc/zenoh-core behavior, see docs/design/declared-keyexpr.md). For repeated operations on a fixed key, use a Publisher or Querier, which do optimize their key. This type is provided for API parity only.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.DeclaredKeyexpr"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/key-expressions/#Zenoh.declare_keyexpr","page":"Key Expressions","text":"declare_keyexpr(s::Session, k::AbstractKeyexpr) -> DeclaredKeyexpr\ndeclare_keyexpr(s::Session, k::AbstractString; autocanonize=false) -> DeclaredKeyexpr\n\nRegister k with the session (z_declare_keyexpr) and return a DeclaredKeyexpr. Release with close.\n\nwarning: No performance benefit in this libzenohc\nSession-level put/get do not use the declared id on the wire (see DeclaredKeyexpr). For repeated operations on a fixed key, use a Publisher or Querier instead — they optimize their key.\n\n\n\n\n\ndeclare_keyexpr(f::Function, s::Session, k; …)\n\nScoped form: declare k, call f(d::DeclaredKeyexpr), and undeclare on exit (even if f throws).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.declare_keyexpr"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Quality-of-Service","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Quality of Service (QoS) settings tune how Zenoh's transport moves a message: which transmission queue it rides (Priority), what happens when that queue fills (CongestionControl), whether the network layer retransmits losses (Reliability), and which peers it reaches (Locality). Zenoh.jl also folds the query-shaping options (QueryTarget, QueryConsolidation, ReplyKeyexpr) and two read-side singleton families (SampleKind, WhatAmI) into the same module.\n\nThat shared design is the page's organizing idea: every one of these is a strongly-typed singleton sum type. Zenoh.jl gives each level its own zero-field type under an abstract supertype and exposes one instance constant per level (Priorities.REAL_TIME, CongestionControls.BLOCK, …), where Rust and C expose a single bounded enum. The constants are the user-facing API. Three properties follow directly:\n\nMethod signatures dispatch on the abstract type (priority::Union{Nothing, Priority}), so a bogus value raises a method error at the call site.\nIdentity comparison is free: priority(sample) === Priorities.REAL_TIME is a pointer compare, no field unpack.\nDownstream code can add a method per level (handle(::Priorities.RealTime, msg) = …).\n\nEach setting matches the Zenoh data-plane abstraction one-to-one; the Mapping section states the correspondences precisely and names every divergence.","title":"Quality of Service"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Sender-side-QoS:-priority,-congestion-control,-reliability,-locality","page":"Quality of Service","text":"These travel with each outgoing message. Set them when you create a Publisher, inline on a session put, or on a get request.\n\nPriority selects the transmission queue. With QoS enabled in the Config (transport.<type>.qos), Zenoh keeps one queue per priority and services them highest-first. The seven levels run from Priorities.REAL_TIME (highest) to Priorities.BACKGROUND (lowest), with Priorities.DATA as the default.\n\nCongestionControl decides what happens when the target queue is full. CongestionControls.DROP (the default) discards the message; CongestionControls.BLOCK makes the sender wait for the queue to drain.\n\nReliability chooses whether the network layer retransmits lost messages. Reliabilities.RELIABLE (the default) guarantees delivery; Reliabilities.BEST_EFFORT delivers once and drops losses. You fix this on the sender: a publisher sets its reliability at declare time, and a session put sets it per call.\n\nLocality scopes the destination set. Localities.ANY (the default) reaches both session-local and remote subscribers; Localities.SESSION_LOCAL stays within the same session; Localities.REMOTE reaches only remote peers. It surfaces as allowed_destination= on publishers, put, and get, and as allowed_origin= on subscribers.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nsession = open(Config())\n\n# A publisher bakes its QoS in at declare time.\npub = Publisher(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/qos\");\n    priority            = Priorities.REAL_TIME,\n    congestion_control  = CongestionControls.BLOCK,\n    reliability         = Reliabilities.RELIABLE,\n    express             = true,\n    allowed_destination = Localities.ANY)\n\nput(pub, \"hello\")   # uses the publisher's fixed reliability; no per-put override\n\n# A session put can set the same QoS inline, including reliability.\nput(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/qos\"), \"once\";\n    priority            = Priorities.DATA_HIGH,\n    congestion_control  = CongestionControls.DROP,\n    reliability         = Reliabilities.BEST_EFFORT)\n\nwarning: A publisher's reliability cannot be overridden per `put`\nA Publisher fixes Reliability at declare time; a per-put call on that publisher carries no reliability of its own. To vary reliability per message, publish through a session put, which accepts reliability=.\n\nThe express=true keyword above is a Bool flag: it bypasses transport batching to cut latency.","title":"Sender-side QoS: priority, congestion control, reliability, locality"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Query-shaping-QoS:-target,-consolidation,-reply-key-expressions","page":"Quality of Service","text":"These shape a get on the requester side. target= and consolidation= also apply to a long-lived Querier; accept_replies= is a session-get keyword with no Querier equivalent.\n\nQueryTarget selects which matching queryables the query reaches: QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING (the default, chosen by the routing strategy), QueryTargets.ALL (every match), or QueryTargets.ALL_COMPLETE (every queryable declared complete).\n\nQueryConsolidation sets the reply de-duplication strategy: QueryConsolidations.AUTO (the default, deferring to the queryable's preference), NONE (forward everything, duplicates allowed), MONOTONIC (forward immediately unless a same-or-newer timestamp already went out for the key), or LATEST (hold back to send only the highest-timestamp set per key).\n\nReplyKeyexpr constrains reply keys via accept_replies= on a session get: ReplyKeyexprs.MATCHING_QUERY (the default) requires replies to match the query key expression; ReplyKeyexprs.ANY admits any key.\n\nfor reply in get(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/**\");\n        target         = QueryTargets.ALL,            # or the :all shorthand\n        consolidation  = QueryConsolidations.LATEST,  # or the :latest shorthand\n        accept_replies = ReplyKeyexprs.MATCHING_QUERY)\n    if is_ok(reply)\n        smp = sample(reply)\n        @show priority(smp) congestion_control(smp) reliability(smp) kind(smp)\n    end\nend\n\ntarget= and consolidation= accept either the typed singleton or a Symbol shorthand (:best_matching/:all/:all_complete and :auto/:none/:monotonic/:latest), on both get and a Querier.\n\nnote: Symbol shorthands are limited to `target` and `consolidation`\nThe :all/:latest-style shorthands exist only for target= and consolidation=. priority, congestion_control, reliability, allowed_destination, and accept_replies are typed Union{Nothing, ...} against their abstract supertypes, so passing a Symbol there is a method error. Use the typed singleton (Priorities.REAL_TIME, ReplyKeyexprs.ANY, …).","title":"Query-shaping QoS: target, consolidation, reply key expressions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Read-side-metadata:-sample-kind-and-discovery-roles","page":"Quality of Service","text":"SampleKind reports whether an inbound Sample carries a value or signals a key deletion: SampleKinds.PUT (issued by a put) or SampleKinds.DELETE (issued by a delete). Read it with kind(::Sample).\n\nThe sender-side QoS that round-trips through the transport is readable off an inbound sample with matching accessors, each returning the typed singleton:\n\npriority(smp)            === Priorities.REAL_TIME\ncongestion_control(smp)  === CongestionControls.DROP\nreliability(smp)         === Reliabilities.RELIABLE\nkind(smp)                === SampleKinds.PUT\n\nWhatAmI names the role a node announces during scouting: WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER, or WhatAmIs.CLIENT. It names a node's scouting role. You read it off a Hello returned by scout and render it with whatami_string; the scout(...; what=...) filter takes Symbols (:router, :peer, :client). See the discovery documentation for scouting in full.","title":"Read-side metadata: sample kind and discovery roles"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Setting-QoS-in-static-configuration","page":"Quality of Service","text":"A static Config can fix reliability for a whole deployment: a Reliabilities singleton drops into a publication-rule / QoS-overwrite config section. It is the one QoS here with a config-builder bridge; congestion control, priority, and express reach config as their own keyword fields.","title":"Setting QoS in static configuration"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Public-API","page":"Quality of Service","text":"","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nPriority / Priorities.* Priority zenoh::qos::Priority z_priority_t\nCongestionControl / CongestionControls.* CongestionControl zenoh::qos::CongestionControl z_congestion_control_t\nReliability / Reliabilities.* Reliability zenoh::qos::Reliability z_reliability_t\nLocality / Localities.* Locality zenoh::sample::Locality z_locality_t\nQueryTarget / QueryTargets.* QueryTarget zenoh::query::QueryTarget z_query_target_t\nQueryConsolidation / QueryConsolidations.* ConsolidationMode zenoh::query::ConsolidationMode z_query_consolidation_t\nReplyKeyexpr / ReplyKeyexprs.* reply key expression zenoh::query::ReplyKeyExpr z_reply_keyexpr_t\nSampleKind / SampleKinds.* Sample kind zenoh::sample::SampleKind z_sample_kind_t\nWhatAmI / WhatAmIs.* WhatAmI zenoh::config::WhatAmI z_whatami_t\n\nThe zenoh-c column names each C type without a hyperlink: the zenoh-c API reference is a single concatenated page, so a bare link would land every row at the same top-of-page spot. The Rust column links to the canonical per-type docs.rs page, which resolves to the exact abstraction.\n\nEach Julia singleton maps one-to-one to its C enumerator through an unexported _raw, e.g. _raw(Priorities.REAL_TIME) == LibZenohC.Z_PRIORITY_REAL_TIME. The seven priority levels, the two congestion-control modes, the two reliability modes, the three localities, the three query targets, the two reply-keyexpr modes, the two sample kinds, and the three discovery roles each match the C enum exactly; the four consolidation modes are each built via their z_query_consolidation_t constructor rather than a bare enumerator. Priority, CongestionControl, Reliability, and SampleKind also round-trip in reverse — the priority/congestion_control/reliability/kind accessors on a Sample read the libzenoh value off the loaned sample and recover the typed singleton.\n\nThe divergences are deliberate and worth naming exactly:\n\nSingleton sum types, not an enum. Zenoh.jl models each level as a distinct zero-field type under an abstract supertype, which enables dispatch and free identity comparison. Rust and C use one bounded enum value per setting.\nCongestionControls omits BlockFirst. Only BLOCK and DROP exist; the C/Rust BlockFirst (Z_CONGESTION_CONTROL_BLOCK_FIRST, an unstable Rust feature) has no Julia equivalent. The underlying integers follow C ordering (BLOCK=0, DROP=1), reversed from Rust's discriminants; the singleton API hides the difference, so reason about behavior.\nConsolidation is a built struct. _raw on a QueryConsolidations singleton calls the libzenoh builder (z_query_consolidation_auto(), …) and returns a fully-built z_query_consolidation_t, ready to drop into the get/querier options. The signed z_consolidation_mode_t enum stays hidden, and its numbering differs both ways: the C enum is signed (AUTO=-1, NONE=0, MONOTONIC=1, LATEST=2) while Rust's ConsolidationMode discriminants run 0..3 — another reason to reason about behavior.\nModule grouping differs from Rust. Zenoh.jl folds all of these, plus ReplyKeyexpr and WhatAmI, into one qos.jl, where Rust scatters them across zenoh::qos, zenoh::query, and zenoh::sample.\nPublisher reliability is fixed at declare time. z_publisher_put_options_t carries no reliability field, so a per-put call on a publisher cannot override the reliability set when the publisher was declared. A session put carries its own reliability=.\nReliability bridges into static config. A Reliabilities singleton entering a PublicationRule / QosOverwriteValues section emits the zenoh config token \"reliable\" or \"best_effort\". The other QoS settings reach config as their own keyword fields rather than through this builder bridge.\n\nwarning: Reliability is stable here, unstable in Rust\nzenoh::qos::Reliability sits behind the unstable crate feature in Rust. Reliability is a first-class, stable part of the Zenoh.jl API — treat it as GA.\n\nnote: WhatAmI is a discovery role, only loosely QoS\nWhatAmI names a node's scouting role. It lives in qos.jl for implementation convenience and shares the singleton design, but its natural home is discovery. Unlike every other submodule here it defines no DEFAULT constant, and scout's what= filter takes Symbols rather than WhatAmI singletons.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Priority","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Priority\n\nAbstract supertype for the Priorities singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, Priority} to dispatch on priority and reject any other value at parse time. The seven concrete instances run Priorities.REAL_TIME (highest) through Priorities.BACKGROUND (lowest).\n\nSee also Priorities, priority.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Priority"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Priorities","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Priorities\n\nSingleton sum type for the seven transmission-queue priority levels, from highest to lowest: Priorities.REAL_TIME, Priorities.INTERACTIVE_HIGH, Priorities.INTERACTIVE_LOW, Priorities.DATA_HIGH, Priorities.DATA, Priorities.DATA_LOW, and Priorities.BACKGROUND.\n\nWhen QoS is enabled in the transport config, zenoh keeps one transmission queue per priority and services them highest-first. Each level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype Priority; pass an instance constant as the priority= keyword on a publisher declaration or session put, and read it back off an inbound sample with priority. Priorities.DEFAULT is DATA, mirroring libzenoh's Z_PRIORITY_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also Priority.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Priorities"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.CongestionControl","page":"Quality of Service","text":"CongestionControl\n\nAbstract supertype for the CongestionControls singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, CongestionControl} to dispatch on the strategy and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are CongestionControls.BLOCK and CongestionControls.DROP.\n\nSee also CongestionControls, congestion_control.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.CongestionControl"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.CongestionControls","page":"Quality of Service","text":"CongestionControls\n\nSingleton sum type for the strategy applied when a message hits a full transmission queue: CongestionControls.BLOCK waits for the queue to drain, while CongestionControls.DROP discards the message.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype CongestionControl. Pass an instance constant as the congestion_control= keyword on a publisher declaration or session put, and read it back off an inbound sample with congestion_control. CongestionControls.DEFAULT is DROP, mirroring libzenoh's Z_CONGESTION_CONTROL_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also CongestionControl.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.CongestionControls"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Reliability","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Reliability\n\nAbstract supertype for the Reliabilities singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, Reliability} to dispatch on reliability and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are Reliabilities.RELIABLE and Reliabilities.BEST_EFFORT.\n\nSee also Reliabilities, reliability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Reliability"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Reliabilities","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Reliabilities\n\nSingleton sum type for writer-side delivery reliability: Reliabilities.RELIABLE has the network layer retransmit lost messages, while Reliabilities.BEST_EFFORT tolerates loss.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype Reliability. Set it as the reliability= keyword at publisher declare time or per session put; it is fixed on the sender, so a Publisher has no per-put override. The chosen value is reported back on each inbound sample via reliability. The same singletons also drop into static PublicationRule/QosOverwriteValues config sections, emitting the zenoh config tokens \"reliable\" / \"best_effort\". Reliabilities.DEFAULT is RELIABLE, mirroring libzenoh's Z_RELIABILITY_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also Reliability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Reliabilities"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Locality","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Locality\n\nAbstract supertype for the Localities singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, Locality} to dispatch on locality and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are Localities.ANY, Localities.SESSION_LOCAL, and Localities.REMOTE.\n\nSee also Localities.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Locality"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.Localities","page":"Quality of Service","text":"Localities\n\nSingleton sum type for message locality, scoping which nodes a publication reaches or a query accepts: Localities.ANY (both session-local and remote), Localities.SESSION_LOCAL (the same session only), or Localities.REMOTE (remote peers only).\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype Locality. Pass the instance constants Localities.ANY, Localities.SESSION_LOCAL, or Localities.REMOTE as the allowed_destination= keyword on a publisher declaration, session put, or get. Localities.DEFAULT is ANY, mirroring libzenoh's Z_LOCALITY_DEFAULT == Z_LOCALITY_ANY.\n\nSee also Locality.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Localities"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.ReplyKeyexpr","page":"Quality of Service","text":"ReplyKeyexpr\n\nAbstract supertype for the ReplyKeyexprs singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, ReplyKeyexpr} to dispatch on the policy and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are ReplyKeyexprs.ANY and ReplyKeyexprs.MATCHING_QUERY.\n\nSee also ReplyKeyexprs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ReplyKeyexpr"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.ReplyKeyexprs","page":"Quality of Service","text":"ReplyKeyexprs\n\nSingleton sum type controlling which key expressions a query accepts on its replies: ReplyKeyexprs.MATCHING_QUERY requires each reply to match the query key expression, while ReplyKeyexprs.ANY admits replies under any key.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype ReplyKeyexpr. Pass an instance constant as the accept_replies= keyword on a get. ReplyKeyexprs.DEFAULT is MATCHING_QUERY, mirroring libzenoh's Z_REPLY_KEYEXPR_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also ReplyKeyexpr.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ReplyKeyexprs"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.QueryTarget","page":"Quality of Service","text":"QueryTarget\n\nAbstract supertype for the QueryTargets singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, QueryTarget} to dispatch on the target and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING, QueryTargets.ALL, and QueryTargets.ALL_COMPLETE.\n\nSee also QueryTargets.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QueryTarget"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.QueryTargets","page":"Quality of Service","text":"QueryTargets\n\nSingleton sum type selecting which matching queryables a get or Querier reaches: QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING follows the routing strategy, QueryTargets.ALL reaches every matching queryable, and QueryTargets.ALL_COMPLETE reaches every queryable declared complete.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype QueryTarget. Pass an instance constant as the target= keyword on a get or Querier; the matching Symbol shorthand (:best_matching, :all, :all_complete) is accepted there too. QueryTargets.DEFAULT is BEST_MATCHING, mirroring libzenoh's Z_QUERY_TARGET_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also QueryTarget.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QueryTargets"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.QueryConsolidation","page":"Quality of Service","text":"QueryConsolidation\n\nAbstract supertype for the QueryConsolidations singletons. Method signatures take Union{Nothing, QueryConsolidation} to dispatch on the strategy and reject any other value at parse time. The concrete instances are QueryConsolidations.AUTO, QueryConsolidations.NONE, QueryConsolidations.MONOTONIC, and QueryConsolidations.LATEST.\n\nSee also QueryConsolidations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QueryConsolidation"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.QueryConsolidations","page":"Quality of Service","text":"QueryConsolidations\n\nSingleton sum type for the reply de-duplication strategy applied to a get or Querier: QueryConsolidations.AUTO defers to the queryable's preferences, QueryConsolidations.NONE forwards every sample, QueryConsolidations.MONOTONIC forwards immediately unless a same-or-newer timestamp was already sent for the key, and QueryConsolidations.LATEST holds back samples to send only the highest-timestamp set per key.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype QueryConsolidation; _raw builds the libzenoh z_query_consolidation_t struct directly via the matching constructor function. Pass an instance constant as the consolidation= keyword on a get or Querier; the matching Symbol shorthand (:auto, :none, :monotonic, :latest) is accepted there too. QueryConsolidations.DEFAULT is AUTO.\n\nSee also QueryConsolidation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QueryConsolidations"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.SampleKind","page":"Quality of Service","text":"SampleKind\n\nAbstract supertype for the SampleKinds singletons. The concrete instances are SampleKinds.PUT and SampleKinds.DELETE, recovered from an inbound sample by kind.\n\nSee also SampleKinds.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SampleKind"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.SampleKinds","page":"Quality of Service","text":"SampleKinds\n\nSingleton sum type recording how a sample was produced: SampleKinds.PUT carries a value, while SampleKinds.DELETE signals a key deletion.\n\nEach level is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype SampleKind. Read it off an inbound sample with kind. SampleKinds.DEFAULT is PUT, mirroring libzenoh's Z_SAMPLE_KIND_DEFAULT.\n\nSee also SampleKind.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.SampleKinds"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.WhatAmI","page":"Quality of Service","text":"WhatAmI\n\nAbstract supertype for the WhatAmIs singletons. The concrete instances are WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER, and WhatAmIs.CLIENT, read off the Hello messages produced by scout.\n\nSee also WhatAmIs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.WhatAmI"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/quality-of-service/#Zenoh.WhatAmIs","page":"Quality of Service","text":"WhatAmIs\n\nSingleton sum type for the role a node announces during discovery: WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER, or WhatAmIs.CLIENT.\n\nEach role is a distinct zero-field type under the abstract supertype WhatAmI. It surfaces on the Hello messages delivered by scout. Discovery roles carry no settable default, so this submodule defines no DEFAULT constant.\n\nSee also WhatAmI.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.WhatAmIs"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Queries","page":"Queries","text":"A query is Zenoh's request/reply primitive: a client issues a get against a selector (a key expression plus optional parameters), the network routes it to every matching queryable — \"a computation registered at a specific key expression [that] can be triggered by a get operation\" — and each queryable answers with zero or more replies. Zenoh.jl exposes both halves: Queryable declares the server-side computation, and get (a Base.get method) issues the client-side request and surfaces the Reply stream.\n\nBoth halves come in two delivery forms, and the choice is the core of this page. The callback form runs your function per query/reply on a dedicated task through a single-slot, latest-wins handoff; the channel form buffers items in a capacity-bounded ring you drain with iteration or tryrecv!. For queryables the distinction is load-bearing: a query overwritten in the single-slot handoff is revoked, so its originating get times out. Real query workloads belong on the channel form.","title":"Queries"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#The-selector:-key-expression-plus-parameters","page":"Queries","text":"Zenoh's selector is a key expression and, after a ?, a ;-separated string of URL-encoded parameters (path/**/x?arg1=val1;arg2=value%202). Zenoh.jl keeps the two parts separate: get takes a Keyexpr and a plain String of parameters, and a served Query exposes them through keyexpr and parameters. Parameters are passed and read as raw strings — application code interprets them.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nsession = open(Config())\nke = Keyexpr(\"demo/example/zget\")","title":"The selector: key expression plus parameters"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Serving-queries:-the-Queryable","page":"Queries","text":"A Queryable declared on a key expression receives every matching query. Answer each one with reply (a successful Put-kind sample), reply_del (a Delete-kind notification), or reply_err (an error payload). A queryable may emit any number of replies per query, including none.","title":"Serving queries: the Queryable"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Channel-form-(recommended-for-real-workloads)","page":"Queries","text":"Queryable(s, k; channel=:fifo) returns a buffered queryable — also typed QueryableHandler — that you iterate to receive each Query. Reply inline and the loop continues; iteration ends after close once buffered queries drain.\n\nqable = Queryable(session, ke; channel=:fifo, capacity=16, complete=true)\n\nserver = Threads.@spawn for q in qable\n    @info \"query\" key=keyexpr(q) params=parameters(q)\n    reply(q, \"the answer\"; encoding=\"text/plain\")\nend\n\nIteration finalizes the previous Query at the start of each step, which is what releases the originating get from its wait. So the contract is: reply while you hold the query and never accumulate queries across iterations. collecting a Queryable yields queries that are already finalized.\n\nFor deferred handling, pull with take! (blocking) or tryrecv! (non-blocking, returns nothing when the buffer is empty). These hand the Query out without a follow-on finalize, so its lifetime is yours: finalize the query after replying, or the originating get blocks for its full timeout window.\n\nq = take!(qable)\ntry\n    reply(q, \"deferred answer\")\nfinally\n    finalize(q.q)   # release the query now; otherwise the get waits out its timeout\nend","title":"Channel form (recommended for real workloads)"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Callback-form","page":"Queries","text":"Queryable(f, s, k) invokes f(::Query) per query on a dedicated task and drops the Query as soon as f returns. The handoff is single-slot latest-wins: queries arriving while the slot is occupied overwrite the previous one, and an overwritten query is revoked — its client sees a timeout. The form fits low-rate, reactive servers; for sustained query traffic the channel form is the right choice.\n\nqable = Queryable(session, ke) do q\n    reply(q, \"callback answer\")\nend\n\nf must finish replying before it returns; the Query handle is gone afterward. Deferring reply work past the callback sees the query revoked.","title":"Callback form"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Lifetime-and-options","page":"Queries","text":"Both forms undeclare on close, which is idempotent. The channel form also carries a GC finalizer safety net; the callback form relies on explicit close (its consume task and context form a reference cycle that a finalizer cannot tear down safely). Two declare-time options apply to either form:\n\ncomplete — mark the queryable as holding the full data for its key expression, which QueryTargets.ALL_COMPLETE queries select for.\nallowed_origin — a Localities singleton (ANY, SESSION_LOCAL, REMOTE) restricting which sessions' queries it answers.","title":"Lifetime and options"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Replying-on-a-wildcard-key-expression","page":"Queries","text":"reply and reply_del default to borrowing the query's own key expression, which is the right choice when the queryable serves a concrete key. A query's key expression may itself be a glob; when you serve a wildcard queryable, pass an explicit per-key Keyexpr so each reply carries the concrete key it answers for.\n\nqable = Queryable(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/sensors/**\"); channel=:fifo)\nfor q in qable\n    reply(q, \"23.5\"; encoding=\"text/plain\")              # default: query's keyexpr (may be a glob)\n    reply(q, \"23.5\", Keyexpr(\"demo/sensors/temp\"))       # explicit: the concrete key answered\nend","title":"Replying on a wildcard key expression"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Issuing-queries:-get","page":"Queries","text":"get issues a query and delivers the Reply stream. It is not exported by Zenoh; it extends Base.get, so a bare get(...) already resolves to it after using Zenoh (every example below relies on that). Qualify as Zenoh.get only if another imported package's get would shadow it.","title":"Issuing queries: get"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Channel-form","page":"Queries","text":"get(s, k, params=\"\") returns a GetHandler you iterate, take!, or tryrecv!. The handler self-terminates when every peer has replied or the timeout elapses — no explicit close is needed.\n\ngh = get(session, ke, \"arg=1\";\n         target = QueryTargets.ALL,\n         consolidation = QueryConsolidations.NONE,\n         timeout_ms = 1000)\n\nfor r in gh\n    if is_ok(r)\n        smp = sample(r)\n        println(keyexpr(smp), \" => \", String(payload(smp)))\n    else\n        println(\"ERR: \", String(error_payload(r)))\n    end\nend\n\nA Reply is ok-or-error: is_ok discriminates, sample yields the success Sample, and error_payload / error_encoding read the error branch (each throws if called on the wrong branch).","title":"Channel form"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Callback-form-2","page":"Queries","text":"get(f, s, k, params=\"\") invokes f(::Reply) per reply and blocks until delivery completes (all peers replied or the timeout elapsed). Delivery is the single-slot latest-wins handoff, so a slow consumer sees only the latest reply. Pass should_close_on_error=false to keep consuming after f throws.\n\nget(session, ke, \"arg=1\"; timeout_ms=1000) do r\n    is_ok(r) && println(String(payload(sample(r))))\nend","title":"Callback form"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Query-routing-and-consolidation","page":"Queries","text":"get folds Zenoh's query options into keyword arguments:\n\ntarget — which matching queryables receive the query: QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING / ALL / ALL_COMPLETE (or the :best_matching / :all / :all_complete symbol shorthand).\nconsolidation — the reply de-duplication strategy: QueryConsolidations.AUTO / NONE / MONOTONIC / LATEST (or :auto / :none / :monotonic / :latest).\naccept_replies — which reply key expressions are accepted: ReplyKeyexprs.ANY or MATCHING_QUERY (the default).\ntimeout_ms — request timeout in milliseconds; 0 means no timeout.\npayload, encoding, attachment — request data sent to the queryable (read there with payload, encoding, attachment).\ncongestion_control, priority, express, allowed_destination — the shared QoS controls (see Quality of Service).\ncancellation — a CancellationToken; see below.","title":"Query routing and consolidation"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Cancelling-an-in-flight-get","page":"Queries","text":"A CancellationToken bounds a running get independently of its timeout. Hand it to a get and call cancel to abort: the get's reply stream ends promptly. The token you hold stays valid to cancel through after the get starts, and clones of a token share one cancellation flag.\n\ntok = CancellationToken()\ngh = get(session, ke; cancellation=tok)\nThreads.@spawn (sleep(0.5); cancel(tok))   # abort from a deadline timer\nforeach(_ -> nothing, gh)                   # stream ends when the get is cancelled\n@show is_cancelled(tok)\n\nFor a Querier get, the cancellation token is the only per-call bound, since querier get options carry no timeout. It is the abort path, separate from timeout_ms, and it is safe to cancel after the operation already finished.","title":"Cancelling an in-flight get"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Reusable-queries:-the-Querier","page":"Queries","text":"A Querier is a long-lived query handle declared once for a key expression with baked-in target, consolidation, QoS, and timeout_ms. Each get(querier, params) reuses those defaults, returning a GetHandler (channel form) or running a callback (callback form) just as a Session get does. Declaring once resolves the key expression and query settings a single time and reuses them across every get, so a stream of queries to the same key amortizes that setup.\n\nq = Querier(session, ke;\n            target = QueryTargets.ALL,\n            consolidation = QueryConsolidations.LATEST,\n            timeout_ms = 5_000)\n\n@show querier_id(q)                 # (; zid, eid) — the querier's global entity id\n\nfor r in get(q, \"arg=1\")            # channel form, reusing the baked-in defaults\n    is_ok(r) && println(String(payload(sample(r))))\nend\n\nget(q, \"arg=2\"; payload=\"hello\", encoding=\"text/plain\") do r   # callback form\n    @show r\nend\n\nclose(q)                            # undeclare; idempotent\n\ntimeout_ms is declare-time only on a querier; express a per-call deadline by wiring a timer to cancel(tok) on a cancellation token. The querier's declared key expression is fixed; the positional parameters string is the only per-call selector part. See the Querier reference below for querier_id and the full keyword set.","title":"Reusable queries: the Querier"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#API","page":"Queries","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Queryable-side","page":"Queries","text":"","title":"Queryable side"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Get-side","page":"Queries","text":"","title":"Get side"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Cancellation","page":"Queries","text":"","title":"Cancellation"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Querier","page":"Queries","text":"","title":"Querier"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Reusable,-allocation-free-gets","page":"Queries","text":"A ReusableGet wraps a Querier for the request/reply hot path: it allocates its whole apparatus once, and each call! re-arms it in place and blocks until the first reply, so a steady-state call allocates nothing on the Zenoh.jl side. The reply lands in a pooled ReplyHolder — read it, and copy out anything you need, before the next call! reuses the slot. A ReusableGet is single-in-flight: a concurrent call! throws ConcurrentUseError, so use one per task or a small pool.","title":"Reusable, allocation-free gets"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/queries/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Queries","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nQueryable (+ both constructors) Queryable zenoh::query::Queryable / Session::declare_queryable z_declare_queryable / z_owned_queryable_t\nQuery + accessors Query zenoh::query::Query z_query_keyexpr / z_query_parameters / z_query_payload / z_query_encoding / z_query_attachment / z_query_accepts_replies\nreply / reply_del / reply_err reply to a Query Query::reply / reply_del / reply_err z_query_reply / z_query_reply_del / z_query_reply_err\nget(s, k, params; ...) / get(f, s, k, params) get / query Session::get (SessionGetBuilder) z_get\nGetHandler reply handler get handler (recv_async) reply closure + ring\nReply + is_ok/sample/error_payload/error_encoding Reply / ReplyError zenoh::query::Reply z_reply_is_ok / z_reply_ok / z_reply_err\nQueryTargets.{BEST_MATCHING,ALL,ALL_COMPLETE} query target QueryTarget Z_QUERY_TARGET_*\nQueryConsolidations.{AUTO,NONE,MONOTONIC,LATEST} reply consolidation ConsolidationMode z_query_consolidation_auto/none/monotonic/latest\nReplyKeyexprs.{ANY,MATCHING_QUERY} reply key expression ReplyKeyExpr Z_REPLY_KEYEXPR_*\nCancellationToken / cancel / is_cancelled CancellationToken zenoh::cancellation::CancellationToken z_cancellation_token_new/clone/cancel/is_cancelled/drop\nQuerier / querier_id querier zenoh::query::Querier / Session::declare_querier z_declare_querier / z_querier_get_with_parameters_substr / z_querier_id\n\nThe Query accessors, the three reply functions, the Reply discriminants, and the QueryTarget / QueryConsolidation / ReplyKeyExpr selectors are 1:1 with their Rust methods and z_* C calls. complete and allowed_origin map to z_queryable_options_t.complete / .allowed_origin; Localities.{ANY,SESSION_LOCAL,REMOTE} map 1:1 to Z_LOCALITY_*. The two get forms and both Querier get forms wrap z_get / z_querier_get_with_parameters_substr; the Querier uses the _substr entrypoint (pointer + length) so a SubString of parameters threads through without a copy.\n\nSeveral Zenoh constructs are deliberately reshaped or absent in Zenoh.jl:\n\nnote: Builders are folded into keyword arguments\nRust's SessionGetBuilder, QueryableBuilder, QuerierBuilder/QuerierGetBuilder, and the ReplyBuilder* family are all collapsed into keyword arguments on get / Queryable / Querier / reply / reply_err / reply_del. There is no chained-builder API.\n\nnote: No Selector, Parameters, or ReplyError type\nRust's Selector (key expression + Parameters) is split into a separate Keyexpr argument and a raw parameters String. Rust's ReplyError struct is folded into Reply, surfaced only through error_payload / error_encoding guarded by is_ok.\n\nwarning: Single-slot callback delivery has no Rust analog\nThe callback get and callback Queryable use a single-slot, latest-wins handoff: an item arriving while the slot is occupied overwrites the previous one. For queryables an overwritten query is revoked, so its client sees a timeout. This is a Zenoh.jl delivery choice; prefer the channel form for real query workloads.\n\nwarning: Query lifetime is an explicit contract in the channel form\nDropping an owned Query (z_query_drop) is what sends the final-ack the originating get awaits. Iteration finalizes the previous query at each step, so reply inline and never stash queries across iterations; take! / tryrecv! hand out the query without that follow-up, so you must call finalize(q.q) after replying. Rust handles this through Drop scope.\n\nwarning: Cancellation is unstable upstream\nCancellationToken wraps zenoh's unstable cancellation API (it requires the Rust unstable crate feature). It is the abort path, distinct from timeout_ms. z_get consumes (moves) the token it is given, so get passes it a z_cancellation_token_clone and keeps the caller's handle valid; clones share one flag (z_cancellation_token_cancel / z_cancellation_token_is_cancelled).\n\nnote: channel=:fifo and :ring deliver identically\nFor get, Queryable, and Querier replies, channel=:fifo and channel=:ring both route through the same capacity-bounded callback ring (drop-oldest on overflow, ROS KEEP_LAST). The symbol exists for API symmetry; lossless backpressure would require a Rust-side notifying FIFO handler.\n\nnote: Background queryables are not yet wrapped\nz_declare_background_queryable exists in the C bindings but has no Zenoh.jl wrapper (there is a source TODO(background-queryable)). Fire-and-forget, session-lifetime queryables are unavailable today. The Querier likewise omits the matching-status / matching-listener API and accept_replies.\n\nSee also Quality of Service, Key Expressions, and Samples.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.Queryable","page":"Queries","text":"Queryable\n\nThe server side of get/reply, in two forms chosen by how it's declared:\n\ncallback — Queryable(f, s, k) invokes f(::Query) on a dedicated Julia task per query. Single-slot latest-wins: queries arriving while the slot is still occupied overwrite the previous one. For real query workloads prefer the channel form — overwriting an in-flight query means the client gets a timeout, not a reply.\nchannel — Queryable(s, k; channel=:fifo|:ring) buffers queries; iterate or take!/tryrecv! to consume them. Also reachable as QueryableHandler.\n\nCall close(q) to undeclare; idempotent in both forms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Queryable"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.QueryableHandler","page":"Queries","text":"QueryableHandler\n\nThe channel form of Queryable: the buffered, ring-backed Queryable{RingBacking} returned by Queryable(s, k; channel=…). iterate / take! / tryrecv! consume the buffered Querys.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.QueryableHandler"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.Query","page":"Queries","text":"Query\n\nA single inbound query handed to a queryable handler. Use the accessors (keyexpr, parameters, payload, encoding, attachment, accepts_replies) to inspect it, then reply(q, payload) / reply_err(q, err) / reply_del(q) to respond.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Query"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.reply","page":"Queries","text":"reply(q::Query, payload, k::Keyexpr=<query's keyexpr>; kwargs...)\n\nSend a successful reply to query q. payload is anything ZBytes accepts. The keyexpr defaults to the query's own — pass an explicit one when serving wildcard keyexprs with per-key resolution.\n\nKeyword arguments: encoding, timestamp, attachment, congestion_control, priority, express.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.reply"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.reply_err","page":"Queries","text":"reply_err(q::Query, payload; encoding=nothing)\n\nSend an error reply to query q. payload is anything ZBytes accepts.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.reply_err"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.reply_del","page":"Queries","text":"reply_del(q::Query, k::Keyexpr=<query's keyexpr>; kwargs...)\n\nSend a delete-notification reply to query q.\n\nKeyword arguments: timestamp, attachment, congestion_control, priority, express.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.reply_del"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.parameters","page":"Queries","text":"parameters(q::Query) -> String\n\nThe selector parameters of query q — the URL-query-style key/value part following ? in the selector that issued the query (e.g. \"arg1=val1;arg2=val2\"), empty when the get carried none.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.parameters"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.accepts_replies","page":"Queries","text":"accepts_replies(q::Query) -> Bool\n\nWhether query q accepts replies. When false, the originating get wants no data, so reply / reply_err / reply_del calls are wasted.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.accepts_replies"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/queries/#Base.get-Tuple{Function, Session, Keyexpr, AbstractString}","page":"Queries","text":"get(f, s::Session, k::Keyexpr, parameters=\"\"; kwargs...)\n\nIssue a query on key expression k and invoke f(::Reply) on a dedicated Julia task for each reply that fits through the single-slot handoff. Replies that arrive while the cell still holds an unconsumed one overwrite it — slow consumers see only the latest reply.\n\nBlocks until libzenohc finishes delivering replies (i.e. all peers responded or the timeout elapsed). For queued semantics use the channel form: get(s, k, params; channel=:fifo|:ring, capacity=N).\n\nKeyword arguments mirror the channel-form get: target, consolidation, timeout_ms, payload, encoding, attachment, congestion_control, priority, express, allowed_destination, accept_replies. Plus should_close_on_error::Bool=true — if f throws, abandon the remaining replies.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.get"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/queries/#Base.get-Tuple{Session, Keyexpr, AbstractString}","page":"Queries","text":"get(s::Session, k::Keyexpr, parameters=\"\"; kwargs...) -> GetHandler\n\nIssue a query on key expression k, returning a GetHandler over the replies. Iterate it to consume each Reply.\n\nKeyword arguments:\n\nchannel            — accepted for compatibility; delivery is the callback                        ring either way (drop-oldest on overflow)\ncapacity           — channel buffer size (default 16)\ntarget             — QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING / ALL / ALL_COMPLETE                        (or the :best_matching / :all / :all_complete shorthand)\nconsolidation      — QueryConsolidations.AUTO / NONE / MONOTONIC / LATEST                        (or the :auto / :none / :monotonic / :latest shorthand)\ntimeout_ms         — request timeout in milliseconds (0 = no timeout)\npayload            — optional payload bytes (anything ZBytes accepts)\nencoding           — payload encoding (Encoding, MIME, or string)\nattachment         — optional attachment bytes\ncongestion_control — CongestionControls.BLOCK or DROP\npriority           — Priorities.REAL_TIME … BACKGROUND\nexpress            — Bool; bypass batching\nallowed_destination— Localities.ANY / SESSION_LOCAL / REMOTE\naccept_replies     — ReplyKeyexprs.ANY or MATCHING_QUERY\ncancellation       — a CancellationToken; cancel it to abort this get\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.get"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.GetHandler","page":"Queries","text":"GetHandler\n\nReply consumer returned by Zenoh.get(s, k, params; ...). Iterate or use take!/tryrecv! to consume Replys. Iteration terminates once the remote side stops sending (all peers replied or the timeout elapsed) — no explicit close needed.\n\nReplies are delivered by the callback ring (slot-free), drained on an internal task into a Channel; that task also owns teardown once the get completes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.GetHandler"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.Reply","page":"Queries","text":"Reply\n\nA response to a get call. Use is_ok(r) to discriminate, then sample(r) for success or error_payload(r)/error_encoding(r) for the error branch.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Reply"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.is_ok","page":"Queries","text":"is_ok(r::Reply) -> Bool\n\nDiscriminates a Reply: true when it carries a successful Sample (read it with sample), false when it carries an error (read it with error_payload / error_encoding).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.is_ok"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.sample","page":"Queries","text":"sample(r::Reply) -> Sample\n\nThe Sample carried by a successful Reply. The returned sample borrows from r, which it keeps alive while reachable. Throws ArgumentError on an error reply — guard with is_ok first.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.sample"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.error_payload","page":"Queries","text":"error_payload(r::Reply) -> ZBytes\n\nThe error payload of an error Reply, as a ZBytes borrowing r. Throws ArgumentError on a successful reply — guard with is_ok first; pair with error_encoding to interpret the bytes.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.error_payload"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.error_encoding","page":"Queries","text":"error_encoding(r::Reply) -> Encoding\n\nThe Encoding of an error Reply's payload, describing how to interpret error_payload. Throws ArgumentError on a successful reply — guard with is_ok first.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.error_encoding"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.CancellationToken","page":"Queries","text":"CancellationToken()\n\nA fresh cancellation token. Pass it to a get via cancellation=tok, then call cancel to abort that get — its reply stream ends. Handles produced by cloning (done internally when a token is handed to a get) share one flag, so cancelling the token you hold cancels the operation it was given to. close(tok) drops it early; it is also dropped on GC.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.CancellationToken"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.cancel","page":"Queries","text":"cancel(t::CancellationToken)\n\nCancel the operation t (or the clone handed to a get) is bound to — the get's reply stream ends promptly. Safe to call after the operation already finished.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.cancel"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.is_cancelled","page":"Queries","text":"True if t has been cancelled.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.is_cancelled"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.Querier","page":"Queries","text":"Querier\n\nLong-lived query handle returned by Querier(s::Session, k::Keyexpr; …). Defaults (target, consolidation, QoS, timeout) are baked in at declare time; each get(querier, params; …) reuses them. Two forms:\n\nchannel: get(querier, params; channel=:fifo|:ring, capacity=N) → GetHandler (iterate / take! / tryrecv! for Replys)\ncallback: get(f, querier, params; …) invokes f(::Reply) on a dedicated task per reply (single-slot latest-wins, like get(f, ::Session, …))\n\nCall close(q) to undeclare.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Querier"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.querier_id","page":"Queries","text":"querier_id(q::Querier) -> (; zid, eid)\n\nThe querier's global entity id: the Zenoh id of its session (zid, a z_id_t printable via show) paired with the session-local entity id (eid::UInt32).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.querier_id"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/queries/#Base.get-Tuple{Querier, AbstractString}","page":"Queries","text":"get(q::Querier, parameters=\"\"; kwargs...) -> GetHandler\n\nIssue a query on q, returning a GetHandler over the replies. Mirrors get(::Session, ::Keyexpr, params; …) but reuses the querier's declared target/consolidation/QoS.\n\nKeyword arguments: channel (:fifo/:ring), capacity, payload, encoding, attachment, cancellation (a CancellationToken; cancel it to abort this get — the only per-call bound a querier get has).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.get"},{"category":"method","location":"manual/queries/#Base.get-Tuple{Function, Querier, AbstractString}","page":"Queries","text":"get(f, q::Querier, parameters=\"\"; kwargs...)\n\nIssue a query on q and invoke f(::Reply) on a dedicated task for each reply that fits through the single-slot handoff. Mirrors get(f, ::Session, ::Keyexpr, params; …).\n\nKeyword arguments: should_close_on_error, payload, encoding, attachment, cancellation (a CancellationToken).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.get"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.ReusableGet","page":"Queries","text":"ReusableGet(q::Querier; capacity::Integer=1)\n\nA reusable, allocation-free request/reply handle over querier q. Allocates its whole apparatus once; each call! re-arms it in place and settles on the first reply.\n\nDeclare q with an explicit timeout_ms > 0 and (for the single-slot default) target = QueryTargets.BEST_MATCHING: the timeout bounds how long call! waits for a slow/absent server, and a single-reply target keeps the receive zero-alloc and the returned reply unambiguous.\n\nA ReusableGet is single-in-flight: concurrent call!s on the same instance throw ConcurrentUseError. For concurrency, use one per task or a small pool. It does not own q — close the querier yourself. close(rg) tears down the apparatus.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ReusableGet"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.call!","page":"Queries","text":"call!(rg::ReusableGet, parameters=\"\"; payload=nothing, attachment=nothing,\n      payload_len=length(payload), attachment_len=length(attachment),\n      cancellation=nothing) -> ReplyHolder | nothing\n\nIssue one query on rg and block until the first reply, returned as the pooled ReplyHolder (rg's reusable reply slot) — or nothing if the get completed with no reply (timeout / no matching queryable / cancelled). Read it with is_ok and sample/error_payload and decode it (copying out) before the next call! — the slot is reused on the next call, so the holder and anything borrowed from it (its sample, the sample's payload) are valid only until then (a zero-copy view held across a call! throws BorrowError).\n\npayload and attachment, when given as Vector{UInt8}, are aliased zero-copy (the first *_len bytes) for the duration of the call — do not mutate those buffers until call! returns. Returning the pooled holder (not a fresh wrapper) and aliasing the buffers is what keeps a steady-state call! allocation-free on the Zenoh.jl side.\n\ncancellation is an optional per-call deadline lever: pass a CancellationToken (typically armed by a Base.Timer) and cancel it to abort this call — the get ends and call! returns nothing. The querier's declared timeout_ms is the default bound; use cancellation only when a call needs a different deadline (it allocates a token clone, so the no-cancellation path stays allocation-free).\n\nSingle-in-flight: a concurrent call! on the same rg throws ConcurrentUseError.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.call!"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.ReplyHolder","page":"Queries","text":"ReplyHolder\n\nThe pooled reply slot a ReusableGet settles into. call! returns the same ReplyHolder every call and refills it in place, so a steady-state get allocates nothing on the receive side. Read the settled reply with is_ok, then sample on success or error_payload / error_encoding on error.\n\nIts contents — and anything borrowed from them (the sample's payload, key expression, and attachment) — stay valid only until the next call! reuses the slot. Copy out what you need before then; a borrowed view used across a call! throws a BorrowError, caught by the slot's recycle epoch.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ReplyHolder"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/queries/#Zenoh.ConcurrentUseError","page":"Queries","text":"ConcurrentUseError(msg)\n\nThrown by call! when a second call is attempted on a ReusableGet that is already servicing one. A ReusableGet is single-in-flight by design — use one per caller task, or a pool, for concurrency.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.ConcurrentUseError"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Matching","page":"Matching","text":"Matching answers one question about a Publisher or Querier: is there anyone on the other side of my key expression right now? Zenoh calls this the matching status: whether any entity whose key expression overlaps yours currently exists. For a publisher the matching set is the subscribers whose key expressions overlap its own; for a querier it is the queryables that match its key expression and target. Matching lets a producer skip work, log a warning, or pause until a consumer is present.\n\nZenoh.jl exposes exactly two operations, both boolean-valued. matching_status takes a one-shot snapshot. MatchingListener declares a foreground listener whose callback fires on every transition between an empty and a non-empty matching set. Both work uniformly across Publisher, Querier, and AdvancedPublisher.","title":"Matching"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#One-shot-poll","page":"Matching","text":"matching_status reads the current state and returns a Bool. true means at least one matching peer exists at the moment of the call.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nsession = Zenoh.open(Config())\npub = Publisher(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/example/**\"))\n\nif matching_status(pub)\n    @info \"at least one subscriber is listening\"\nelse\n    @info \"no subscribers yet\"\nend\n\nFor a Querier the same call reports matching queryables instead of subscribers:\n\nq = Querier(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/example/**\"))\nmatching_status(q)   # Bool: does any queryable match this querier's key expression and target?","title":"One-shot poll"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Reacting-to-changes","page":"Matching","text":"MatchingListener declares a foreground listener and runs your callback f(::Bool) on a dedicated Julia task. The callback is edge-triggered: it fires when the matching set crosses the empty/non-empty boundary, once per crossing regardless of how many peers cross it.\n\nf(true) — a matching peer now exists where there were none.\nf(false) — the last matching peer departed.\n\nml = MatchingListener(pub) do matching::Bool\n    @info matching ? \"a subscriber is now listening\" : \"all subscribers left\"\nend\n\n# ... publish while reacting to matching changes ...\n\nclose(ml)   # undeclare the listener\n\nFor a Querier, the transitions track queryables; the API is otherwise identical:\n\nml = MatchingListener(q) do matching::Bool\n    @info \"matching queryables present\" matching\nend","title":"Reacting to changes"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Delivery-is-single-slot,-latest-wins","page":"Matching","text":"Delivery is single-slot, latest-wins: each new status overwrites any undelivered one, so a slow callback always sees the current state (the same single-slot model as Subscriber). For matching status this is the right trade — transitions are infrequent and each notification is idempotent, so collapsing a rapid empty→non-empty→empty burst to its endpoint leaves you with exactly the state you need to act on.","title":"Delivery is single-slot, latest-wins"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Lifecycle","page":"Matching","text":"For deterministic teardown, call close on the listener: it tears the listener down promptly, drains any in-flight callback, and stops the consumer task. close is idempotent. GC finalization tears the listener down as a safety net, on no fixed schedule.\n\nBy default a callback that throws tears its own listener task down; pass should_close_on_error=false to keep the task alive and log each error instead.","title":"Lifecycle"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Advanced-publishers","page":"Matching","text":"AdvancedPublisher supports the same two operations with identical semantics (matching subscribers):\n\nap = AdvancedPublisher(session, Keyexpr(\"demo/example/**\"); cache=CacheOptions(max_samples=10))\nmatching_status(ap)                       # Bool\nml = MatchingListener(ap) do m; @info m; end\nclose(ml)\n\nSee Advanced Pub/Sub for the publisher itself.","title":"Advanced publishers"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#API","page":"Matching","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/matching/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Matching","text":"C symbols printed as plain code spans (z_undeclare_matching_listener, ze_advanced_publisher_*) exist in zenoh-c but are not surfaced in the rendered 1.9.0 API index; search the index for the name. The published teardown entry for a listener handle is z_matching_listener_drop.\n\nZenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nmatching_status(::Publisher) matching status snapshot Publisher::matching_status z_publisher_get_matching_status\nmatching_status(::Querier) matching status snapshot Querier::matching_status z_querier_get_matching_status\nmatching_status(::AdvancedPublisher) matching status snapshot (zenoh-ext) ze_advanced_publisher_get_matching_status\nMatchingListener(f, ::Publisher) MatchingListener Publisher::matching_listener z_publisher_declare_matching_listener\nMatchingListener(f, ::Querier) MatchingListener Querier::matching_listener z_querier_declare_matching_listener\nMatchingListener(f, ::AdvancedPublisher) MatchingListener (zenoh-ext) ze_advanced_publisher_declare_matching_listener\nf(::Bool) argument MatchingStatus MatchingStatus::matching() -> bool z_matching_status_t\nclose(::MatchingListener) listener undeclaration MatchingListener::undeclare / RAII drop z_undeclare_matching_listener\n\nmatching_status returns the same boolean as Rust's MatchingStatus::matching(): true when matching subscribers (publisher) or queryables (querier) exist. The notification semantics of MatchingListener match the zenoh::matching module exactly — a notification fires \"when the first matching subscriber or queryable appears, or when the last one disappears.\" The points below describe Zenoh.jl's design choices at this boundary; the behavior matches Rust.\n\nnote: No MatchingStatus value\nRust's MatchingStatus and C's z_matching_status_t are both structs, but each carries a single boolean field. Zenoh.jl unwraps that field at the boundary, so matching_status and the listener callback both deal in plain Bool.\n\nnote: No builder — eager constructor\nRust declares a listener through Publisher::matching_listener(), which returns a MatchingListenerBuilder you configure and resolve. Zenoh.jl folds declaration into the eager constructor MatchingListener(f, target), which takes the callback directly. Declaration, callback installation, and resolution all happen in that one call.\n\nnote: Callback-only, single-slot delivery\nThe matching API provides callback-form listeners with single-slot latest-wins delivery; unlike Subscriber and Querier replies, it has no handler-buffered (FIFO/ring) variant.\n\nwarning: Foreground listeners only\nThe background C entrypoints z_publisher_declare_background_matching_listener, z_querier_declare_background_matching_listener, and ze_advanced_publisher_declare_background_matching_listener exist in the bindings but are deliberately left unwrapped: they return no handle, so the closure lifetime would have to be pinned to the target or session. Only foreground listeners — those returning a MatchingListener you close explicitly — are available, across publisher, querier, and advanced publisher.\n\nnote: Unified z_/ze_ surface\nC splits matching across the core z_ prefix and the zenoh-ext ze_ prefix: the advanced-publisher path calls ze_advanced_publisher_declare_matching_listener / ze_advanced_publisher_get_matching_status. Zenoh.jl exposes all three targets through the same MatchingListener type and matching_status generic, reusing the z_-prefixed z_owned_matching_listener_t and z_undeclare_matching_listener for teardown.\n\nnote: Explicit lifecycle\nRust relies on RAII drop (or an explicit undeclare()). Zenoh.jl uses an explicit, foreground-task lifecycle: call close for prompt teardown, with GC finalization as a safety net. The Julia-only should_close_on_error keyword (default true) governs whether a throwing callback tears down its consumer task.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/matching/#Zenoh.matching_status","page":"Matching","text":"matching_status(pub::Publisher) -> Bool\n\nOne-shot poll of pub's current matching status. Returns true iff at least one matching subscriber exists right now. For change notifications use MatchingListener.\n\n\n\n\n\nmatching_status(q::Querier) -> Bool\n\nOne-shot poll of q's current matching status. Returns true iff at least one matching queryable exists right now. For change notifications use MatchingListener.\n\n\n\n\n\nmatching_status(ap::AdvancedPublisher) -> Bool\n\nOne-shot poll of ap's current matching status (true iff at least one matching subscriber exists). For change notifications use MatchingListener.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.matching_status"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/matching/#Zenoh.MatchingListener","page":"Matching","text":"MatchingListener\n\nForeground matching listener returned by MatchingListener(f, ::Publisher) or MatchingListener(f, ::Querier). f(::Bool) is invoked on a dedicated Julia task each time the matching set transitions between empty and non-empty:\n\nf(true)  — at least one matching peer now exists\nf(false) — the last matching peer went away\n\nFor a Publisher the peers are subscribers; for a Querier they are queryables.\n\nSingle-slot latest-wins semantics — see Subscriber. For matching status this is rarely a concern (transitions are infrequent and idempotent), and the slow-consumer worst case is just seeing the final state rather than every intermediate flip.\n\nCall close(ml) to undeclare; the listener is also dropped on GC as a safety net.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.MatchingListener"},{"category":"section","location":"reference/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","text":"Every documented symbol in Zenoh, linked to where the manual documents it in context. The manual pages explain each symbol within its Zenoh domain; this page is the flat, alphabetical index.\n\n","title":"API Reference"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Scouting","page":"Scouting","text":"Scouting discovers other Zenoh nodes on the network. Zenoh defines it as the process of discovering Zenoh nodes in the network, driven by the transport layer and the active configuration. A node answers a scout probe with a Hello message carrying its identity, role, and reachable endpoints. A process can scout without ever opening a session.\n\nZenoh.jl exposes discovery through one exported function, scout. A single call runs one bounded scouting round against a copy of the supplied Config, delivers a Hello per node heard, and returns when the round ends. Two forms cover the common needs: a callback form that handles each Hello as it arrives, and a collecting form that hands back a Vector{Hello} once the round finishes. Reach for the callback form to act on each peer as it is discovered; reach for the collecting form when you want the complete set in hand.","title":"Scouting"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Running-one-round","page":"Scouting","text":"scout runs exactly one round and blocks the calling task until that round completes. A round ends when its timeout elapses or Zenoh otherwise terminates it, so a finite timeout_ms bounds how long the call blocks.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nconfig = Config()                       # default configuration\n\n# Collecting form: block, then return every Hello heard this round.\nhellos = scout(config; timeout_ms=1000)\nfor h in hellos\n    println(whatami_string(h.whatami), \" \", h.zid, \" @ \", h.locators)\nend\n\ntimeout_ms bounds the round in milliseconds. timeout_ms=0 (the default) uses Zenoh's default round length; it does not mean an instant or unbounded round.","title":"Running one round"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Handling-discoveries-as-they-arrive","page":"Scouting","text":"The callback form invokes f(::Hello) on a dedicated Julia task once per node announcement, and blocks until the round finishes. Reach for it to act on each peer as it is discovered.\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nscout(Config(); timeout_ms=1000) do h::Hello\n    @info \"discovered\" role=whatami_string(h.whatami) zid=h.zid locators=h.locators\nend\n\nThe collecting form returns every Hello once the round ends.","title":"Handling discoveries as they arrive"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Filtering-by-role-with-what","page":"Scouting","text":"The what keyword selects which node roles to probe for. It accepts a WhatAmI singleton, a collection of them, or nothing (the default) to use Zenoh's default filter. The singletons are WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER, and WhatAmIs.CLIENT; combine roles by passing a tuple.\n\n# Routers and peers only.\nscout(Config(); what=(WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER), timeout_ms=1000) do h::Hello\n    @info \"node\" role=whatami_string(h.whatami)\nend\n\n# A single role.\nhellos = scout(Config(); what=WhatAmIs.PEER, timeout_ms=1000)\n\nwhat uses the same WhatAmI values that come back on Hello.whatami, so the role you filter on and the role you read are spelled identically.","title":"Filtering by role with what"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Reading-a-Hello","page":"Scouting","text":"Each Hello exposes three fields:\n\nzid — the node's Zenoh ID.\nwhatami::WhatAmI — its announced role, a WhatAmI singleton (WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER, or WhatAmIs.CLIENT).\nlocators::Vector{String} — the endpoints the node is reachable at.\n\nA returned Hello is fully detached and safe to keep indefinitely: every field, including each locator string, stays valid after the round ends.\n\nUse whatami_string for Zenoh's lowercase role name; show renders the singleton as WhatAmIs.PEER:\n\nh = first(scout(Config(); what=WhatAmIs.PEER, timeout_ms=1000))\nwhatami_string(h.whatami)   # \"peer\"\nh.whatami                   # WhatAmIs.PEER\n\nwhatami_string accepts the role singleton directly, so whatami_string(h.whatami) and whatami_string(WhatAmIs.PEER) both work.","title":"Reading a Hello"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Choosing-a-discovery-strategy","page":"Scouting","text":"Which nodes answer a scout round depends on the transport configuration. Two strategies dominate, configured through the Config:\n\nMulticast scouting. Nodes in peer mode join multicast group 224.0.0.224 on UDP port 7446 and automatically connect to the peers and routers they discover there. Client mode runs multicast scouting too, to find a node to attach its single session to.\nGossip scouting. Peer-mode nodes forward the applications and routers they already know to newly scouted nodes, bootstrapping discovery from entry points listed in the configuration's connect section. Gossip scouting is the fallback when multicast is unavailable.","title":"Choosing a discovery strategy"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#API","page":"Scouting","text":"The role values returned in Hello.whatami are documented with the rest of the quality-of-service singletons: see WhatAmI and WhatAmIs on the Quality of Service page.","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/scouting/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Scouting","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nscout (callback form) scouting round + callback handler zenoh::scout → ScoutBuilder → Scout z_scout\nscout (collecting form) scouting round drained to a list awaiting a Scout and receiving every Hello z_scout + manual collection\nHello Hello message zenoh::scouting::Hello z_owned_hello_t\nHello.zid / .whatami / .locators Hello identity / role / endpoints Hello::zid() / whatami() / locators() z_hello_zid / z_hello_whatami / z_hello_locators\nWhatAmI node role zenoh::config::WhatAmI z_whatami_t\nwhat keyword (WhatAmI) role filter WhatAmIMatcher z_what_t + z_scout_options_t.what\ntimeout_ms keyword round length scout duration z_scout_options_t.timeout_ms\nwhatami_string role name string — z_whatami_to_view_string\n\nThe callback form of scout is the whole-pipeline equivalent of Rust's zenoh::scout(what, config) with a callback handler: it calls C z_scout with the moved config, a moved z_closure_hello_t, and a z_scout_options_t, then fires f(::Hello) per reply. The collecting form is the analogue of awaiting a Rust Scout and receiving every Hello, returning them as a Vector{Hello}. Each Hello field maps one-to-one onto a Rust accessor and the matching z_hello_* call. The what keyword is Zenoh.jl's spelling of the WhatAmIMatcher: WhatAmIs.ROUTER/.PEER/.CLIENT OR-combine into a z_what_t bitset, and timeout_ms writes straight into z_scout_options_t.timeout_ms only when it is greater than 0, leaving libzenohc's default round length in place otherwise. The Config is cloned before the call because C z_scout takes z_moved_config_t and consumes it — the same owned/loaned/moved model that governs the rest of the bindings.\n\nFour behaviors diverge from Rust:\n\nwarning: Single bounded round, no Scout handle\nRust's zenoh::scout returns a ScoutBuilder, and the resulting Scout scouts continuously until it is dropped. Zenoh.jl exposes neither a builder nor a handle: scout runs exactly one bounded round and blocks until libzenohc ends it. Bound the round with timeout_ms. There is no Scout handle to drop for early termination.\n\nnote: Callback-only transport, no streaming receiver\nlibzenohc provides only the z_closure_hello_t callback channel for scouting; it ships no FIFO/ring handler for Hello. Zenoh.jl mirrors this directly. Rust's streaming receiver (while let Ok(hello) = receiver.recv_async().await) has no Zenoh.jl counterpart: pass a callback, or take the whole Vector{Hello} after the round finishes. The collecting scout form is built on top of the callback form (push! under a lock), not from a generic handler.\n\nnote: Eager copy, not lazy borrow\nRust's Hello accessors borrow from the live message. Zenoh.jl copies every field — including each locator String — into Julia-owned memory at construction, because the underlying z_owned_hello_t is dropped before the user touches the Hello. The Julia Hello is therefore fully detached and safe to retain.\n\nnote: `what` is Symbol-based\nElsewhere Zenoh.jl uses typed WhatAmI singletons, but scout's what filter takes Symbols (:router/:peer/:client), compound symbols (:router_peer), or symbol collections. Passing a WhatAmI value to what is unsupported and errors. Roles are read back as WhatAmI values on Hello.whatami.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/scouting/#Zenoh.scout","page":"Scouting","text":"scout(f, config::Config; what=nothing, timeout_ms=0,\n      should_close_on_error=true) -> Nothing\n\nInvoke f(::Hello) on a dedicated Julia task for each peer announcement heard during a scouting round. Blocks until libzenohc finishes the round (timeout elapsed or scout otherwise terminated).\n\nwhat filters which node roles to scout for; accepts a WhatAmI singleton, a collection of them, or nothing to use the libzenohc default. Pass WhatAmIs.ROUTER, .PEER, or .CLIENT; combine roles with a tuple, e.g. what=(WhatAmIs.ROUTER, WhatAmIs.PEER).\n\nconfig is cloned — z_scout consumes its config, so the caller's Config remains usable.\n\n\n\n\n\nscout(config::Config; what=nothing, timeout_ms=0) -> Vector{Hello}\n\nBlock until scouting completes and return every Hello heard. See the callback form for the meaning of what and timeout_ms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.scout"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/scouting/#Zenoh.Hello","page":"Scouting","text":"Hello\n\nA peer announcement delivered by scout. Fields:\n\nzid::z_id_t — the peer's Zenoh ID.\nwhatami::WhatAmI — WhatAmIs.ROUTER, .PEER, or .CLIENT.\nlocators::Vector{String} — endpoints the peer is reachable at.\n\nUse whatami_string(h.whatami) for a human-readable role string.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Hello"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/scouting/#Zenoh.whatami_string","page":"Scouting","text":"whatami_string(w::z_whatami_t) -> String\n\nHuman-readable name for a z_whatami_t value (lowercase: \"router\", \"peer\", \"client\" — matches what libzenohc returns).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.whatami_string"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Encoding","page":"Encoding","text":"An Encoding is the format descriptor that travels alongside a payload so a receiver knows how to interpret the bytes it gets. It is a MIME-like media type in type/subtype[;schema] form — \"application/json\", \"text/plain;utf-8\" — matching Zenoh's definition of encoding as \"a description of the value format, allowing Zenoh (or your application) to know how to encode/decode the value to/from a bytes buffer\".\n\nEncoding is metadata, not a transform. Zenoh carries the descriptor on the wire and hands it back unchanged. Attaching the right encoding lets higher layers (content filtering, automatic deserialization in other clients) act on the payload, while the predefined media types keep the network cost small.","title":"Encoding"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Constructing-an-encoding","page":"Encoding","text":"Encoding holds two fields: a mime media-type string and an optional schema. Build one from a string, append a schema with the keyword, and serialize back to the wire form with string:\n\nusing Zenoh\n\ne = Encoding(\"text/plain\"; schema = \"utf-8\")\ne.mime     # \"text/plain\"\ne.schema   # \"utf-8\"\nstring(e)  # \"text/plain;utf-8\"\n\nEncoding(\"application/json\")  # schema defaults to nothing\n\nThe schema is an arbitrary substring appended after a semicolon. Zenoh leaves its semantics to the implementer and carries it verbatim — utf-8 for text/plain is the conventional example. Zenoh.jl passes the schema through verbatim; apply any escaping your consumers require.\n\nA Julia Base.MIME constructs an encoding too, by stringifying it:\n\nEncoding(MIME(\"application/json\")) == Encoding(\"application/json\")  # true\n\nEncoding(::AbstractString) always succeeds — any string is a valid mime, so construction never fails. Encoding values are immutable and compare and hash by their fields, so they work directly as Dict and Set keys.","title":"Constructing an encoding"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Well-known-encodings","page":"Encoding","text":"The Encodings submodule provides 53 named constants for standard media types. Access them with the qualified name — they are not exported, so Encodings.NAME is required:\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nZenoh.Encodings.APPLICATION_JSON   # Encoding(\"application/json\")\nZenoh.Encodings.TEXT_PLAIN         # Encoding(\"text/plain\")\nZenoh.Encodings.ZENOH_BYTES        # Encoding(\"zenoh/bytes\")\n\nEach constant is a precomputed Encoding value carrying the literal media-type string. The names follow Zenoh's predefined media-type families: application/* (20), audio/* (5), image/* (5), text/* (10), video/* (10), and zenoh/* (3).\n\nzenoh/bytes is Zenoh's default encoding for raw binary data. Zenoh.jl has no zero-argument Encoding() constructor: to send a payload without specifying a format, pass nothing (the default) for the encoding keyword and Zenoh applies the zenoh/bytes default for you.","title":"Well-known encodings"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Three-interchangeable-input-forms","page":"Encoding","text":"Every operation that takes an encoding keyword — put, get, Publisher, reply — accepts an Encoding, an AbstractString, or a Base.MIME. (get on a Querier takes encoding at get time, not on the querier constructor.) Most paths annotate the keyword as Union{Nothing, Encoding, AbstractString, Base.MIME}; reply annotates it as plain encoding=nothing. All of them route the value through the same _as_encoding coercion to an Encoding, so you can pass whichever form is most convenient:\n\nke = Keyexpr(\"demo/key\")   # or kexpr\"demo/key\"\n\n# All three are equivalent at the call site.\nput(session, ke, data; encoding = Zenoh.Encodings.APPLICATION_JSON)\nput(session, ke, data; encoding = \"application/json\")\nput(session, ke, data; encoding = MIME(\"application/json\"))\n\nPassing a bare string is the lightweight path for one-off custom types; the named constants document intent and give you compiler-checked names for the common cases.","title":"Three interchangeable input forms"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Reading-an-encoding-off-a-sample","page":"Encoding","text":"The encoding accessor on a received Sample returns an Encoding, reconstructed from the wire form. Reply errors expose theirs through error_encoding:\n\nenc = encoding(sample)\nenc.mime\nenc.schema   # nothing unless the sender appended one\n\nSplitting the wire string on its first ; round-trips well-formed values exactly.\n\nwarning: Semicolons in the media type\nRead-back takes everything after the first ; as the schema, so a media type containing its own ; is misread. Keep media-type strings free of semicolons and confine any ; to the schema you control.","title":"Reading an encoding off a sample"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/encoding/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Encoding","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nEncoding (struct) Encoding zenoh::bytes::Encoding z_owned_encoding_t / z_loaned_encoding_t\nEncoding(mime; schema=…) type/subtype[;schema] FromStr + with_schema z_encoding_from_str + z_encoding_set_schema_from_str\nstring(::Encoding) wire string to_string z_encoding_to_string\nEncodings.NAME predefined media types Encoding::APPLICATION_* consts z_encoding_*() accessors\nencoding(sample) sample encoding sample encoding() z_sample_encoding\n==, hash (Julia-side) value equality PartialEq z_encoding_equals / z_encoding_clone (both unbound)\n\nZenoh.jl's Encoding is the Julia-side mirror of Rust's zenoh::bytes::Encoding: a MIME-like media type plus optional schema, used as payload-format metadata on samples and replies. Rust itself treats that sample/reply encoding as optional metadata, which is why omission (nothing) is the natural absence model. The keyword schema constructor combines what Rust splits into FromStr and with_schema, and what C splits into z_encoding_from_str plus z_encoding_set_schema_from_str. Marshalling into a put/get/reply allocates a libzenoh-owned z_owned_encoding_t and moves it into the option struct; reading one back goes through z_encoding_to_string and a semicolon split.\n\nSpecific divergences from the Rust and C APIs:\n\nnote: Constants are literal-string values, not libzenoh handles\nEncodings.* are constructed as Encoding(\"media/type\") at module load, bypassing the C accessor functions (z_encoding_application_json() and friends). They are plain immutable Julia values. The predefined-string-to-integer-id wire optimization happens later inside libzenoh during marshalling, when the constant is used.\n\nnote: No default-encoding constructor\nRust provides Default = ZENOH_BYTES and C provides z_encoding_loan_default(). Zenoh.jl has no Encoding() and never calls loan_default. Express absence by passing nothing to the encoding keyword; libzenoh's own zenoh/bytes default then applies.\n\nschema is a constructor keyword. Pass it inline — Encoding(mime; schema=…) — where Rust uses the chained with_schema builder. Encoding is immutable; z_encoding_set_schema_from_str runs only as an internal marshalling step.\nSchema is passed through verbatim. The write path concatenates mime;schema with no escaping; the read path splits on the first ;. Round-tripping is exact for well-formed inputs (see the warning above).\nEquality and hashing live in Julia. == and hash operate on the struct fields. z_encoding_clone and z_encoding_equals are not bound; the immutable value is re-marshalled on demand.\nThe submodule exports nothing. Only the names Encoding and Encodings are exported; constants must be qualified as Encodings.APPLICATION_JSON. Rust exposes them as associated consts on the Encoding type itself.\nEncoding is purely the format descriptor. Payload bytes are a separate concern, reached through the sample's payload accessor.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/encoding/#Zenoh.Encoding","page":"Encoding","text":"Encoding(mime::AbstractString; schema=nothing)\nEncoding(m::Base.MIME; schema=nothing)\n\nIdentifies the payload type of a Zenoh sample. mime is the media type string (e.g. \"application/json\"); schema is an optional, arbitrary substring appended after a semicolon when serialised on the wire. The schema is passed through verbatim — callers are responsible for any escaping their consumers require.\n\nFor well-known types, prefer the named constants in Zenoh.Encodings, e.g. Encodings.APPLICATION_JSON.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Encoding"},{"category":"module","location":"manual/encoding/#Zenoh.Encodings","page":"Encoding","text":"Zenoh.Encodings\n\nNamed Encoding constants for the well-known media types Zenoh recognizes, mirroring Rust's Encoding associated constants and the C z_encoding_* accessor set. Each is a precomputed literal-string value (e.g. APPLICATION_JSON == Encoding(\"application/json\")), spanning the application/*, audio/*, image/*, text/*, video/*, and zenoh/* families plus ZENOH_BYTES, ZENOH_STRING, and ZENOH_SERIALIZED.\n\nThe constants are not exported, so reach them with qualified access:\n\nZenoh.Encodings.APPLICATION_JSON\nZenoh.Encodings.TEXT_PLAIN\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.Encodings"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Liveliness","page":"Liveliness","text":"Liveliness is Zenoh's dedicated presence API: a node declares a liveliness token on a key expression, and that token is seen as alive by any other node monitoring the key for as long as the declaring node keeps the token (and stays connected). Other nodes subscribe to be notified the moment a token appears or disappears, or query the key for a one-shot snapshot of who is currently present. This is the purpose-built way to track availability — node membership, service discovery, leader presence.\n\nA token carries presence: its identity is its key expression, and subscribers and queries learn which token changed by reading keyexpr off the sample. A token's appearance and withdrawal arrive as PUT and DELETE sample kinds; a liveliness sample has no payload. When the declaring node drops the token or exits, every watcher observes the DELETE — liveliness tracks the connection, so a crashed or partitioned node is reported gone automatically.\n\nZenoh.jl exposes three constructable entities — LivelinessToken to announce presence, LivelinessSubscriber to watch changes, and LivelinessSubscriberHandler for buffered watching — plus the verb liveliness_get for a snapshot. They reuse the data-plane callback and channel machinery, so their queue and delivery semantics match Publish & Subscribe and Queries exactly.","title":"Liveliness"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Declaring-a-token","page":"Liveliness","text":"LivelinessToken declares presence on a key expression. The token signals \"alive\" to every matching liveliness subscriber for as long as it lives. Hold the returned handle; close it to withdraw explicitly.\n\nusing Zenoh\ns = Zenoh.open(Zenoh.Config())\n\ntok = LivelinessToken(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/42\"))\n\n# ... node is alive while `tok` is held ...\n\nclose(tok)   # withdraw -> matching subscribers see a DELETE\n\nclose(tok) emits a DELETE to every watcher the instant it runs, giving deterministic withdrawal. Withdrawal is also automatic if a held token is never closed, but that fallback fires on garbage collection and so is not prompt — close explicitly when you want watchers to see the departure promptly. Presence is the token's whole surface: it takes no declare-time options.","title":"Declaring a token"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Watching-for-changes","page":"Liveliness","text":"LivelinessSubscriber reports tokens appearing and disappearing on a matching key expression. The callback form runs your function on a dedicated Julia task for each change:\n\nsub = LivelinessSubscriber(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/*\"); history=true) do sample\n    if kind(sample) === SampleKinds.PUT\n        println(\"alive: \", keyexpr(sample))   # a token appeared\n    elseif kind(sample) === SampleKinds.DELETE\n        println(\"gone:  \", keyexpr(sample))   # a token withdrew\n    end\nend\n\n# ... later ...\nclose(sub)\n\nPUT means a token appeared; DELETE means a token withdrew. Read keyexpr on the sample to learn which token changed — the sample's identity is the token's key expression. The callback form is latest-wins single-slot; see Subscriber for the delivery semantics it inherits.\n\nhistory=true replays the already-live tokens at subscribe time, so a late joiner sees the current membership set immediately rather than waiting for the next change. history is a subscriber-side option only — neither the token nor liveliness_get exposes it.","title":"Watching for changes"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Buffered-watching","page":"Liveliness","text":"Omit the callback to get the buffered form, a LivelinessSubscriberHandler you drain by iteration, take!, or tryrecv!. This mirrors the data plane's callback-versus-channel split.\n\nsub = LivelinessSubscriber(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/*\"); channel=:fifo, capacity=16)\nfor sample in sub\n    println(kind(sample) === SampleKinds.PUT ? \"alive: \" : \"gone:  \", keyexpr(sample))\nend\n\nchannel=:fifo and channel=:ring both buffer in a drop-oldest ring and return a LivelinessSubscriberHandler; channel=:keep_all buffers unboundedly, exactly as the data plane's open(s, k; channel=:keep_all) does. The queue semantics are inherited verbatim from SubscriberHandler, including its zero-allocation caveat: a yielded Sample is valid only until the next iteration step, so call take! to retain one past the loop.","title":"Buffered watching"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Snapshotting-who-is-present","page":"Liveliness","text":"liveliness_get is a one-shot query: it returns the tokens currently alive on a key expression, then completes. The buffered form returns a GetHandler you iterate for replies; each reply's sample carries a live token's key expression.\n\nfor reply in liveliness_get(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/*\"); timeout_ms=1000)\n    println(\"present: \", keyexpr(sample(reply)))\nend\n\nA liveliness get is a query whose replies are token announcements, so it reuses the same Reply and GetHandler machinery as a data-plane get.\n\nTo abort a snapshot early, pass a CancellationToken and cancel it (for example from a deadline timer). Your handle stays valid after you pass it, so you can still cancel from it:\n\nct = CancellationToken()\nh = liveliness_get(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/*\"); timeout_ms=5000, cancellation=ct)\nTimer(_ -> cancel(ct), 0.5)   # give up after 500 ms\nfor reply in h\n    println(\"present: \", keyexpr(sample(reply)))\nend\n\nThe callback form invokes f per reply on a dedicated task with latest-wins single-slot semantics and blocks until every reply has arrived — every peer responded or the timeout elapsed:\n\nliveliness_get(s, Keyexpr(\"group/member/*\"); timeout_ms=1000) do reply\n    println(\"present: \", keyexpr(sample(reply)))\nend\n\n:fifo and :ring both deliver through the same drop-oldest ring on liveliness_get, so the channel keyword is interchangeable here; it is accepted for source compatibility with the data-plane get.","title":"Snapshotting who is present"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Liveliness-and-Advanced-Pub/Sub","page":"Liveliness","text":"An AdvancedPublisher can auto-declare a liveliness token to assert its own presence, letting AdvancedSubscribers detect publishers joining and leaving. See Advanced Pub/Sub for how that presence signal drives history and recovery.","title":"Liveliness and Advanced Pub/Sub"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#API","page":"Liveliness","text":"","title":"API"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/liveliness/#Mapping-to-Zenoh,-Rust,-and-C","page":"Liveliness","text":"Zenoh.jl Zenoh abstraction Rust zenoh-c\nLivelinessToken(s, k) Liveliness token Liveliness::declare_token → LivelinessToken z_liveliness_declare_token\nclose(t::LivelinessToken) undeclare token LivelinessToken::undeclare z_liveliness_undeclare_token\nLivelinessToken finalizer drop token Drop for LivelinessToken z_liveliness_token_drop\nLivelinessSubscriber(f, s, k; history) liveliness subscriber Liveliness::declare_subscriber (closure handler) z_liveliness_declare_subscriber\nLivelinessSubscriberHandler / LivelinessSubscriber(s, k; channel) liveliness subscriber (channel handler) Liveliness::declare_subscriber (FifoChannelHandler / RingChannelHandler) z_liveliness_declare_subscriber\nliveliness_get Liveliness::get (replies are Liveliness Token messages) Liveliness::get z_liveliness_get\nhistory keyword history option LivelinessSubscriberBuilder::history z_liveliness_subscriber_options_t.history\ncancellation keyword cancellation token LivelinessGetBuilder::cancellation_token (unstable in 1.9.0) z_liveliness_get_options_t.cancellation_token\n\nThe mapping is direct: LivelinessToken(s, k) is the Rust session.liveliness().declare_token(k).await, calling z_liveliness_declare_token with a defaulted (empty) options struct. close(t) is the explicit Rust undeclare() (z_liveliness_undeclare_token), moving the token out so the GC finalizer's z_liveliness_token_drop is a no-op on the emptied slot; the finalizer alone mirrors Rust's automatic undeclare-on-drop. The callback LivelinessSubscriber is the Rust subscriber with a closure handler, the buffered form is the Rust subscriber with a channel handler, and both issue the same z_liveliness_declare_subscriber call. The PUT/DELETE semantics are Rust's SampleKind::Put/SampleKind::Delete. liveliness_get is session.liveliness().get(k); because z_liveliness_get consumes a reply closure, it reuses the existing GetHandler/Reply machinery rather than introducing a liveliness-specific result type.\n\nThe divergences from upstream Rust are deliberate:\n\nConstructors and keywords replace builders. Zenoh.jl exposes plain constructors and keyword args (history, channel, capacity, timeout_ms, cancellation) where Rust has LivelinessTokenBuilder, LivelinessSubscriberBuilder, and LivelinessGetBuilder.\nSession passed directly. Zenoh.jl folds away Rust's Session::liveliness() -> Liveliness intermediary and passes the Session straight to each constructor and to liveliness_get.\nOne Rust subscriber, two Julia types. Rust models callback versus channel purely by a handler type parameter on a single Subscriber. Zenoh.jl splits this into LivelinessSubscriber (callback, latest-wins single slot) and LivelinessSubscriberHandler (buffered), selected by the presence or absence of the callback f.\nliveliness_get's channel keyword does not affect delivery. :fifo and :ring both map to the same drop-oldest ring; the keyword is accepted only for source compatibility with the data-plane get (whose own subscriber uses :keep_all to select a distinct heap-backed path).\nToken is option-free. z_liveliness_token_options_t is empty (a _dummy byte in the binding), so LivelinessToken exposes no declare-time options at all.\n\nThe cancellation keyword maps to Rust's LivelinessGetBuilder::cancellation_token (an unstable API in 1.9.0) and to z_liveliness_get_options_t.cancellation_token. Passing cancellation=tok clones the token and moves the clone into that field, so cancel(tok) aborts the in-flight query while your handle stays valid. See CancellationToken.\n\nwarning: Not wrapped\nThe C entrypoint z_liveliness_declare_background_subscriber exists in the bindings but has no Julia equivalent: every liveliness subscriber here is an owned handle with explicit close and a finalizer fallback.\n\nThe liveliness types subtype the data-plane AbstractCallbackSubscriber / AbstractSubscriberHandler and share their callback and channel machinery. They sit outside the AbstractPublisher hierarchy, and LivelinessToken is a standalone owned-handle type.","title":"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/liveliness/#Zenoh.LivelinessToken","page":"Liveliness","text":"LivelinessToken(s::Session, k::Keyexpr)\n\nDeclare a liveliness token on k. The token signals \"alive\" to every liveliness subscriber matching k for as long as it lives. Call close(t) to withdraw explicitly; the finalizer drops on GC as a safety net (a no-op on the null slot left by close).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LivelinessToken"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/liveliness/#Zenoh.LivelinessSubscriber","page":"Liveliness","text":"LivelinessSubscriber(f, s::Session, k::Keyexpr; history=false,\n                      should_close_on_error=true)\n\nCallback form. f(::Sample) runs on a dedicated Julia task for each token announcement/withdrawal on k:\n\nkind(sample) === SampleKinds.PUT — token appeared\nkind(sample) === SampleKinds.DELETE — token withdrew\n\nhistory=true replays existing tokens at subscribe time so a late subscriber sees the current set of live tokens.\n\nLatest-wins single-slot semantics — see Subscriber.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LivelinessSubscriber"},{"category":"type","location":"manual/liveliness/#Zenoh.LivelinessSubscriberHandler","page":"Liveliness","text":"LivelinessSubscriberHandler(s::Session, k::Keyexpr;\n                             channel=:fifo, capacity=16, history=false)\n\nBuffered form. Iterate / take! / tryrecv! to consume token samples. See SubscriberHandler for queue semantics.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.LivelinessSubscriberHandler"},{"category":"function","location":"manual/liveliness/#Zenoh.liveliness_get","page":"Liveliness","text":"liveliness_get(s::Session, k::Keyexpr;\n               channel=:fifo, capacity=16, timeout_ms=0, cancellation=nothing) -> GetHandler\n\nOne-shot snapshot of currently live tokens matching k. Iterate the returned GetHandler to consume replies; each sample(reply) carries the token's keyexpr. Pass a CancellationToken as cancellation and cancel it to abort the snapshot early.\n\n\n\n\n\nliveliness_get(f, s::Session, k::Keyexpr;\n               timeout_ms=0, should_close_on_error=true)\n\nCallback form. Blocks until libzenohc finishes delivering replies (every peer responded or the timeout elapsed). Latest-wins single-slot semantics — see get.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Zenoh.liveliness_get"},{"category":"section","location":"#Zenoh.jl","page":"Home","text":"Zenoh is a pub/sub/query protocol that unifies data in motion, data at rest, and computation over one location-transparent key/value space. Applications talk to keys arranged in a /-separated hierarchy; the network routes a put toward every matching Subscriber, serves a get from every matching Queryable or storage, and discovers peers and routers automatically. See the Zenoh abstractions manual for the full vocabulary — keys, key expressions, selectors, values, publishers, and the rest.\n\nZenoh.jl is a typed Julia wrapper over zenoh-c, the official C binding for the Rust Zenoh implementation. Each Zenoh entity — a Session, a Publisher, a Keyexpr, a Queryable — is a Julia struct with Julia-native ergonomics: GC-managed lifetimes, errors raised as exceptions, and eager operations that return a value or throw. The current surface spans publication and subscription, queries and queryables, liveliness, queriers, matching, advanced pub/sub, shared memory, and scouting.","title":"Zenoh.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Home","text":"Zenoh.jl is hosted on GitHub and bundles its native dependency through a JLL, so no separate Zenoh install is required:\n\nusing Pkg\nPkg.add(url = \"https://github.com/BenChung/Zenoh.jl.git\")\n\nusing Zenoh\n\nThe first run compiles the package and loads libzenohc. To talk to other Zenoh applications you need either peer connectivity or a running zenohd router; the examples throughout this manual assume one is reachable.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#A-first-session","page":"Home","text":"using Zenoh\n\n# Build a config: defaults, or from a JSON5 string / file / the ZENOH_CONFIG env var.\ncfg = Config(; str = \"\"\"{mode: \"peer\"}\"\"\")\ncfg[\"connect/endpoints\"] = [\"tcp/localhost:7447\"]   # JSON5-serialized insert\n\ns = open(cfg)                 # eager: returns a Session or throws ZenohError\ntry\n    @show isopen(s)\n    @show zid(s)              # this session's 16-byte Zenoh ID\n    @show router_zids(s)      # IDs of connected routers\n\n    k = kexpr\"demo/example\"   # a Keyexpr via the string macro\n    put(s, k, \"hello\")        # eager publish; throws on failure\nfinally\n    close(s)                  # deterministic teardown; idempotent\nend\n\nThe Getting Started page walks through this end to end; Sessions & Configuration covers the full configuration surface.","title":"A first session"},{"category":"section","location":"#The-wrapper-model","page":"Home","text":"Four conventions hold across every page of this manual, so each feature page can assume them.","title":"The wrapper model"},{"category":"section","location":"#GC-managed-lifetimes","page":"Home","text":"Every Zenoh entity is garbage-collected. An unreferenced Session, Publisher, or Config frees its resources on its own, with no explicit teardown required.","title":"GC-managed lifetimes"},{"category":"section","location":"#Deterministic-close-alongside-GC","page":"Home","text":"For resources whose teardown order matters, close (or undeclare for declared entities) tears the resource down immediately on the calling task. A Session shuts down gracefully and drains its background runtime on that task, where teardown order is predictable, rather than leaving it to the garbage collector. Closing the same entity again is a no-op, and GC remains a safety net for entities never closed explicitly.\n\nwarning: A closed session throws on use\nAny operation on a closed Session raises an ArgumentError. close is idempotent, but operations are not retryable after it.","title":"Deterministic close alongside GC"},{"category":"section","location":"#Errors-as-exceptions","page":"Home","text":"Every operation either returns its result or throws a ZenohError. A successful call returns the wrapped object or nothing; there is no status code to inspect.","title":"Errors as exceptions"},{"category":"section","location":"#Eager-operations,-no-builder-layer","page":"Home","text":"Every Zenoh.jl operation runs immediately. open, put, Publisher(s, k), get, and their siblings perform the operation on the spot and return the result or throw — there is no separate builder or resolve step.\n\nSome features (advanced pub/sub, the structured serializer) come from the zenoh-ext extension rather than the core protocol; each such page flags this where it applies.","title":"Eager operations, no builder layer"},{"category":"section","location":"#Manual-map","page":"Home","text":"Each page anchors a Zenoh domain and links its counterparts in the three official doc sets.\n\nPage Zenoh domain Rust (docs.rs) zenoh-c\nSessions & Configuration the network entity and its config session, config z_open\nKey Expressions key expression key_expr keyexpr\nPublish & Subscribe publisher, subscriber pubsub pub/sub\nSamples sample / value sample sample\nPayloads & Serialization value bytes bytes / serializer\nEncoding encoding bytes::Encoding encoding\nQueries queryable, selector query query\nQuality of Service QoS / priorities qos QoS\nLiveliness liveliness tokens liveliness liveliness\nMatching matching status matching matching\nScouting scouting / discovery scouting scout\nAdvanced Pub/Sub zenoh-ext advanced pub/sub zenoh-ext ze_ advanced\nShared Memory shared-memory transport shm SHM\nLogging runtime logging init_log_from_env_or logging\n\nThe API Reference lists every exported symbol in one place.","title":"Manual map"},{"category":"section","location":"#Implementation-notes","page":"Home","text":"The conventions above are the user-facing contract; this section records how the wrapper realizes them over zenoh-c, and where it diverges from the Rust API. Each manual page carries its own \"Mapping to Zenoh, Rust, and C\" section for its domain.\n\nZenoh.jl Rust zenoh-c\nSession zenoh::Session z_owned_session_t, z_open\nConfig zenoh::config z_owned_config_t, zc_config_from_*\nopen(::Config) Session::open (a Resolvable) z_open\nclose(::Session) Session::close (a builder) z_close + z_session_drop\nZenohError zenoh::Error / Result z_result_t + Z_OK","title":"Implementation notes"},{"category":"section","location":"#Ownership-categories","page":"Home","text":"zenoh-c splits its types into four categories: owned (z_owned_*_t, holding a resource that must be dropped), loaned (z_loaned_*_t, a borrow), moved (z_moved_*_t, consumed by the callee), and view (z_view_*_t, a pointer into external data). Every owned C handle is wrapped in a Julia struct holding a Base.RefValue, with a finalizer that drops it on garbage collection — RAII reaching Julia. src/core/ownership.jl generates the lifecycle verbs at module load: it scans LibZenohC for every z_owned_*_t, finds the matching moved and loaned types, and dlsyms the corresponding C functions to emit the applicable _loan/_loan_mut/_move/_take/_drop verbs — only those whose C symbols exist. View types own nothing, so they need no verbs and are never dropped.","title":"Ownership categories"},{"category":"section","location":"#Close-and-error-mechanics","page":"Home","text":"A Session carries a closed flag and cached SHM state in mutable Ref cells beyond the bare z_owned_session_t, and every declare/put/get checks that flag before calling into C. close calls z_close then drops the handle (z_session_drop) — both on the caller's task, so Zenoh's runtime drains where ordering is predictable rather than on the finalizer thread. Fallible C calls return a z_result_t code; the wrapper throws ZenohError on any non-Z_OK result. The Rust API defers operations through a Resolvable builder finished with .wait()/.await; the pre-resolved C API (z_open, z_put, z_declare_publisher) and Zenoh.jl run on the spot.","title":"Close and error mechanics"},{"category":"section","location":"#Prefix-taxonomy","page":"Home","text":"The wrapped C symbols carry one of three prefixes:\n\nz_ — the core API, shared with zenoh-pico (z_open, z_put, z_declare_subscriber).\nzc_ — zenoh-c specific (zc_config_from_env, zc_config_to_string).\nze_ — zenoh-ext, outside the core protocol.\n\nwarning: Not core Zenoh\nSome features sit outside the core protocol. Advanced Pub/Sub wraps zenoh-ext (ze_* symbols), as does the structured serializer on Payloads & Serialization.\n\nnote: ZRef has no Zenoh counterpart\nZRef — a typed, transport-agnostic payload handle — is a Zenoh.jl construct with no direct Zenoh, Rust, or C equivalent.","title":"Prefix taxonomy"}]
}
